<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY (AP) -- The U.S. military will hand over a naval base  
to Panama about six weeks earlier than originally planned as part 
of the turnover of Canal Zone facilities, Panamanian officials said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rodman naval base, built more than 60 years ago, will be  
turned over to Panama on March 11 instead of April 30 as originally 
scheduled, said officials at the Interoceanic Region Authority, 
which is trying to attract investment to the area. 
</P>
<P>
	The base is on the Pacific side of the Panama Canal, which is to  
be turned over to Panama by the end of the year under the 1977 
Torrijos-Carter treaty. Rodman and four other remaining major bases 
house 4,000 U.S. military personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2,194-acre base was a center of U.S. military activity  
during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CUERNAVACA, Mexico (AP) -- Officials said Wednesday they have  
arrested six people accused of poisoning milk and snack foods to 
extort money from manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Leonardo Castillo, attorney general of the central state of  
Morelos, said members of the group confessed to injecting poison 
into products at convenience stores in Mexico City and seven 
states. 
</P>
<P>
	They would then call product manufacturers and demand money in  
exchange for revealing the stores where the products had been 
poisoned. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would call the companies, and they came right away,''  
Carlos Gomez Meza, one of the suspects, told reporters at a news 
conference arranged by prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	Castillo said the group obtained as much as $59,000 from a milk  
company. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez has restored  
constitutional guarantees on Venezuela's tense border with 
Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	The constitutional guarantees were suspended in 1995 to allow  
security forces to fight leftist rebels from the neighboring 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Wednesday, Venezuelans living in the area will enjoy  
freedom of movement and assembly and have the right to refuse 
warrantless searches along the 1,300-mile border with Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	When he announced his plan to restore the guarantees 10 days  
ago, Chavez also issued a stern warning to Colombian rebels who 
might enter Venezuela, saying ``we demand that they not commit a 
single act in our territory because we will respond.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN CARLOS DE BARILOCHE, Argentina (AP) -- Forest fires Wednesday  
gobbled up pristine forest in southwest Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	The flames erupted this week in Cascadas de los Alerces and  
Cerro Catedral in mountains near this lake resort, 870 miles 
southwest of Buenos Aires. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports said 200 backpackers and campers were evacuated as  
towering plumes of smoke rose from rugged mountains in the Nahuel 
Huapi National Park, a popular tourist spot in the South American 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria Julia Alsogaray, a minister for national resources, said  
the fires had consumed more than 74,000 acres of forests and 
grazing lands. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Chile's government Wednesday ordered the  
expulsion of three foreigners, accusing them of meddling in 
national affairs by supporting protests by Mapuche Indians in 
southern Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	The Interior Ministry identified the foreigners as Arnaud  
Fuentes, of France; Patricia Ballestero Vidal, of Spain; and Lee 
Pope, an American. 
</P>
<P>
	Acting Interior Minister Belisario Velasco said Pope and  
Ballestero joined a protest Feb. 18 by Mapuche Indians opposing 
construction of a $460 million hydroelectric dam at the Bio-Bio 
river, 350 miles south of Santiago. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuentes, Velasco said, actively supported a Mapuche protest on  
Friday in Traiguen, 270 miles south of Santiago. The protest 
against a timber company triggered a clash that injured 8 police 
officers and led to the arrest of 28 Mapuches. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuentes was identified as a university student from southern  
France. Ballesteros told Chilean TV she was a tourist. No 
information was available on Pope. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Thousands of poor, unemployed  
Venezuelans lined up outside the presidential palace Wednesday to 
ask President Hugo Chavez for help. 
</P>
<P>
	The gathering took place two days after Chavez, a wildly popular  
former coup leader, promised to incorporate the poor into an 
ambitious ``military-civic'' plan to build roads and hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the 5,000 people were registered as possible  
participants in the plan, which will include 70,000 soldiers and 
80,000 ordinary citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, 44, has vowed to raise the army's profile by using it to  
help build public works, a move that has raised worries about the 
possible militarization of Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
