<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Feb. 24, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Off 144.75  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks beat a hasty retreat in the final hour of  
trading to close lower, after bond prices slid and pushed interest 
rates higher. The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 144.75 
at 9,399.67. The Dow opened softer but quickly rallied in the 
morning, peaking at just over 9,600, or up 55 points, before 
trimming its gains in late morning and then staging an outright 
retreat in the afternoon. The price of the 30-year bond was down 
more than a point, or $10 for every $1,000 valuation. Its yield, 
which moves opposite the price, moved above the critical 5.5 
percent to 5.51 percent. The rise in interest rates was 
particularly injurious to technology and financial stocks, which 
had been providing some leadership to the upside in recent 
sessions. The Dow was led lower by Hewlett-Packard, down 2 3/8 at 70 3/4, 
and American Express, down 3 15/16 at 107 11/16. The Nasdaq 
composite index was down 36.97 at 2,339.48. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:         9399.67 - 144.75
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1202  Declines 1782  Unchgd  570
NYSE Volume:         750,889,340
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online87 1/2   -   1/2
S&AMP;P 500:         1253.41 - 17.77
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          695.79  -  5.13
Nasdaq Composite Index        2339.48  - 36.97
Gold(final) -    $289.20    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.

</P>
<P>
	Broadcasters Plan To Sue DirecTV  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Broadcasters want a court to immediately stop  
the nation's largest satellite TV company from beaming CBS and Fox 
programs to its customers. DirecTV Inc. plans to directly offer 
customers nationwide tomorrow the option of buying a new package of 
broadcast network stations, including CBS and Fox affiliates. By 
dumping its supplier, PrimeTime 24, and directly offering the 
network programs itself, DirecTV contends it is not affected by a 
federal court order that would cut customers off from CBS and Fox 
signals on Sunday. But broadcasters disagree, calling DirecTV's 
plans ``a brazen attempt to ignore'' the court order issued last 
year by a federal judge in Miami. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Glitch Hits Schwab Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charles Schwab became the latest Internet  
brokerage to frustrate online investors as a computer crash just 
minutes after today's opening bell left the industry's dominant 
player offline for most of the morning. The online system went down 
at 9:37 a.m. EST due to software problems with a new mainframe 
computer that was added to help Schwab handle its booming Internet 
business, a spokesman said. The problem was fixed by 11:08 a.m., 
but some customers continued to experience delays as technicians 
gradually restored the system. By early afternoon, the company 
said, service was back to normal. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Warns About Minimum Wage  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Raising the minimum wage could deny some  
teen-agers their chance at entry-level jobs, Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan said today. He was responding to questions 
from House Banking Committee members while delivering the Fed's 
semiannual report to Congress, Greenspan said increasing the wage 
probably would push inflation higher. But he said his main concern 
was ``individuals who become unemployed because of the minimum 
wage.'' He said that being unemployed as a teen-ager is detrimental 
to learning by training and becoming a productive member of the 
work force,'' he said. President Clinton has proposed raising the 
wage by $1 to $6.15 by September 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Denies Sabotage Claim  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Microsoft engineer rejected as ``completely  
unfounded'' a courtroom claim by Apple Computer that Microsoft 
tried to sabotage Apple's multimedia software. Eric Engstrom also 
argued forcefully that proposals to cooperate with Apple on 
Internet video and audio software stemmed from Microsoft's desire 
to help frustrated customers, not from a desire to eliminate 
competition. Later today, the government began questioning Joachim 
Kempin, the senior Microsoft executive responsible for the 
company's business deals with the nation's computer makers. 

</P>
<P>
	GM Cutting 1,100 Canadian Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	ST. CATHARINES, Ontario (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will  
eliminate more than 1,100 jobs at two Canadian plants, most of them 
at a brake and axle factory that is losing a contract to supply 
truck axles, the No. 1 automaker announced today. Layoff notices 
will be issued starting Monday and the job cuts will begin in July. 
The workers' union contract and provincial labor law require at 
least 16 weeks of notice of layoffs. GM hopes to minimize the 
effect on workers by offering early retirements to some, spokesman 
Stew Low said. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Delays ADM Sentencing  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A federal judge has delayed sentencing former  
Archer Daniels Midland executive Michael Andreas, who was convicted 
of price fixing. U.S. District Judge Blanche Manning delayed 
sentencing Andreas and two others convicted in the conspiracy in 
order to gain more time to determine how much money ADM reaped and 
assess a possible fine. Andreas is a former executive vice 
president of the agribusiness giant. He was convicted together with 
Terrance Wilson, the former head of ADM's corn division, and 
imprisoned ADM biochemist Mark Whitacre. All three were to have 
been sentenced Friday. 

</P>
<P>
	Turner Readies Southeast TV Network  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Turner Broadcasting System today announced plans  
for a new regional TV network meant for southeastern viewers, 
featuring shows about Southern lifestyles, country music and pro 
wrestling. The Turner South channel will draw upon the Turner movie 
and TV series library, along with original Southern-flavored shows 
and games of the company's pro sports franchises -- the Atlanta 
Braves in baseball, the Hawks in basketball and the Thrashers 
hockey franchise that debuts next season. 

</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris To Close a Plant  
</P>
<P>
	FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- Philip Morris will close its Louisville  
cigarette manufacturing plant, costing as many as 1,400 jobs, and 
consolidate production at its plants in Virginia and North 
Carolina. The world's biggest tobacco maker, which makes Marlboro 
cigarettes, said today the move was designed to ``adjust its 
production capacity to demand and maintain its cost 
competitiveness.'' According to a release from the company, the 
Louisville manufacturing plant will be phased out and closed by 
December 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	P&AMP;G May Sell Coast Soap Brand  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. says it might sell its  
Coast brand of bar soap, which was introduced nationally in 1976. 
P&AMP;G said today it is soliciting offers but will keep the brand if 
no acceptable bid is received. The brand, now sold throughout North 
America, is profitable but does not fit into P&AMP;G's long-term 
business plans, management said. 

</P>
<P>
	Brazilians Show Resentment of IMF  
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- As Brazil negotiates with the  
Washington-based International Monetary Fund for help to fix its 
battered economy, a long-standing resentment of ``yankee'' 
influence is slowly reviving. The hostility could make it harder 
for President Fernando Henrique Cardoso to make the budget cuts he 
promised to the IMF in return for a $41.5 billion loan package. 
Senate president Antonio Carlos Magalhaes, a veteran power-broker 
and conservative ally of Cardoso said recently that the 
government's need to seek IMF help is understandable. ``...But that 
doesn't mean the IMF can meddle in national problems...'' he added. 

</P>
