<DOCNO> APW19990224.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings Re-sign Free Safety Thomas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Orlando Thomas is staying with the Minnesota  
Vikings, and it looks like Jerry Ball and Derrick Alexander are on 
the way out. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings re-signed Thomas, their starting free safety, on  
Wednesday to a four-year contract worth $11 million. The deal 
includes a $2.75 million signing bonus -- most of it deferred -- and 
incentive money aimed at improving Thomas' workout habits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings hope that will help Thomas avoid the nagging  
hamstring injuries that have bothered him in recent seasons. When 
Thomas was healthy during his first two seasons he had 14 
interceptions; he has four over the last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very optimistic that he can regain that level (of  
1995-96) over the next few years,'' said Jeff Diamond, Minnesota's 
senior vice president for player personnel. ``We're going to work 
on some things to try to strengthen those hamstrings that gave him 
some problems last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keeping Thomas became a priority after cornerback Corey Fuller  
signed with the expansion Cleveland Browns this month. Losing half 
of the starting secondary would have been devastating, especially 
with backup free safety Torrian Gray trying to return from a 
serious knee injury that cost him the final nine games last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't enjoy the prospect of having to perhaps replace two  
starters in the secondary,'' Diamond said. ``Now we just have to 
find another corner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas' deal probably is the last one the Vikings will work out  
with their own free agents. That leaves Ball and Alexander, two key 
members of last season's defensive line, looking for work. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball, a 330-pound nose tackle, is coming off a season in which  
he tied teammate Ed McDaniel for the NFL lead with 15 tackles for 
losses. But he is seeking about $3 million a year, considerably 
higher than an offer Ball already has rejected in Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, who has played mostly at right end, has had a solid  
but unspectacular career since the Vikings took him with the 11th 
overall pick in the 1995 draft. He was second on the team last 
season with a career-best 7 1/2 sacks, but he has been bothered by 
injuries most of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're really pretty much there with our veteran guys now,''  
Diamond said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
