<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits 17-Month High Vs. Pound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar hit a 17-month high against the  
British pound Wednesday as it rose broadly on speculation that 
interest rates may be hiked because of the strong U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose against the yen as Treasury Secretary Robert  
Rubin said that the Japanese economic outlook remains recessionary. 
The dollar also rose against the euro on the continued expectations 
of an interest rate cut by the 11 countries served by the new 
currency. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a dollar strengthening ... on expectations of a  
strengthening (U.S.) economy,'' said Elena Shperling, chief 
currency trader at Banco di Sicilia. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the British pound fell to $1.5962 from  
$1.6134. During the trading day, the pound fell to $1.5960, its 
weakest point against the dollar since Sept. 18, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in late trading, the dollar was quoted at 121.80 Japanese  
yen, up from 120.81 Tuesday. The euro was quoted at $1.0990, down 
from $1.1007. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders scooped up dollars Wednesday as Federal Reserve Chairman  
Alan Greenspan reiterated his testimony from the day before, 
telling the House Banking Committee that the economy is strong and 
should remain so. But analysts believe that Greenspan seems 
inclined to raise rates if the economy gets too strong. 
</P>
<P>
	Lisa Finstrom, a senior currency futures analyst for Salomon  
Smith Barney Inc., said U.S. Treasury bonds took the hint Wednesday 
as prices dropped significantly and yields rose. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fed may indeed feel a need to do something to cool it  
down,'' Finstrom said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's rise against the pound came a day after British  
Prime Minister Tony Blair laid out a multimillion-dollar plan to 
adapt computers and cash registers for the euro. Britain is not one 
of the 11 countries that embarked upon euro use at the beginning of 
the year and has no immediate plans to join in. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors sold off pounds because they foresaw the weakening of  
the British currency or its demise and because they speculate the 
Bank of England will cut rates again to prime England's lagging 
economic pump. Lower interest rates make a country's currency and 
assets less appealing to foreign investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4485 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4477, and 1.4979 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4961. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7797 German 
marks, up from 1.7768; 5.9701 French francs, up from 5.9595; and 
1,760.56 Italian lire, unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
