<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chen Ready To Join Braves' Rotation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- Bruce Chen, just 21 but already drawing  
comparisons to Tom Glavine, seems well qualified to join the 
Atlanta Braves' magnificent rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	Well, not quite.  
</P>
<P>
	His golf game stinks.  
</P>
<P>
	``The last time I went, I shot a 110,'' Chin said, smiling  
meekly. ``And we were playing mulligans, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chen, a native of Panama, only took up golf last year. Clearly,  
he is not yet ready to join the elite foursome that includes Tom 
Glavine, Greg Maddux, John Smoltz and Kevin Millwood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would probably be on the fifth hole while they're on the  
12th hole,'' Chen joked. ``I would like to go out with them. But 
first, I've got to catch up with their pitching, then I'll catch up 
with their golf. I don't want to be out there on the course with 
them going, `Gee, Bruce, you're killing us. We have to be home by 
5.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Give him time. Already, Chen has defied the odds by rising from  
Double-A at the beginning of last season to a likely spot in the 
Braves rotation behind Glavine (20-6), Maddux (18-9) and Smoltz 
(17-3) -- all Cy Young winners. 
</P>
<P>
	An opening was created when the Braves traded 16-game winner  
Denny Neagle to Cincinnati during the offseason, allowing Kevin 
Millwood (17-8) to take the fourth starter slot. 
</P>
<P>
	So, how does Chen cope with joining a group that combined to win  
72 games a year ago? 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, I'm not feeling any pressure,'' he said, sitting in  
the dugout after a spring training workout at the Disney World 
complex. ``I think I'm more relaxed and more loose this spring 
training. Last year was my first spring (in the big-league camp). 
Now, I know what to expect and what level of baseball they play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a taste of the big leagues last spring, Chen returned to  
Class AA Greenville, where he went 13-7 with a 3.29 ERA. He was 
promoted to Triple-A Richmond, pitching only four games but well 
enough (2-1, 1.88 ERA) to earn a late-season trip to Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Braves running away with the NL East, Chen was able to  
make four starts in the big leagues. The left-hander was 2-0 with a 
3.98 ERA, his poise and style drawing comparisons to Glavine in the 
early years of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you're compared to Tom Glavine, that's great,'' Chen  
said. ``But everyone is different. He knows what he can do, and I 
know what works for me. I'm not trying to copy him. ... I want to 
learn from him. I want to know why he's successful. But I also want 
to be myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defending NL Cy Young winner acknowledged the similarities  
in their pitching styles, though Chen's best pitch is a curve while 
Glavine relies more on his change-up. Personality-wise, they 
resemble each other as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a great demeanor, a great presence on the mound,''  
said Glavine, renowned for his stoic demeanor. ``At the same time, 
he doesn't have one luxury that John and I had when we first came 
up. When we got up here, we expected to lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine and Smoltz both came to Atlanta in the late-80s, when  
the Braves were a last-place team that could afford to groom its 
young pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Glavine went 7-17 with a 4.54 ERA as a rookie; Smoltz also  
struggled (2-7, 5.48) during his initial big-league season. 
</P>
<P>
	``When guys come in now, they're joining a winning ballclub  
that's expected to win and they're expected to be part of that,'' 
Glavine said. ``They don't have the luxury of struggling like we 
did or saying, `So what, it's not about winning.' It's all about 
winning now. 
</P>
<P>
	``That will add a little bit more pressure, a different kind of  
pressure for Bruce. We'll see how he handles it, but I suspect 
he'll be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anticipating the longer big-league season, Chen worked hard over  
the winter to improve his upper-body strength. He also attended a 
quarter of classes at Georgia Tech, working toward a degree in 
civil engineering and improving his mental skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it helps my mind when it comes to remembering  
batters,'' he said of the college experience. ``Sometimes, your 
mind loses focus and your memory starts deteriorating. I was able 
to work my mind as well as my body.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next up, a few more trips to the links.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to surprise those guys,'' Chen promised. ``They all  
say, `Oh, Bruce, he has never played before.' But one of these days 
I'm going to be shooting in the 80s or maybe even the high 70s.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
