<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 05:18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Feb. 24, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	China Airplane Crashes, 64 Dead  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- A Chinese domestic airliner crashed today in  
southeast China, killing all 64 people aboard, an airport official 
said. The plane crashed near the southeastern city of Wenzhou, 
about 800 miles southeast of Beijing, officials at the Wenzhou 
airport said. The plane belonged to China Southwest Airlines, said 
another airport official, who refused to give his name. 

</P>
<P>
	Attacks Against America Uncovered  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- U.S. intelligence agencies have stopped  
accused terrorist Osama bin laden from carrying out at least seven 
bomb attacks on overseas facilities since the bombings of two U.S. 
embassies in Africa last August. USA Today cites unidentified 
senior intelligence officials, and reports that the thwarted 
attacks were against embassies in Albania, Azerbaijan, Ivory Coast, 
Tajikistan, Uganda and Uruguay. 

</P>
<P>
	Dragging Death Jury To Mull Penalty  
</P>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- Jurors will hear more evidence today about  
whether a white supremacist should die for the death of a black 
man. Yesterday, the jury found John William King guilty of capital 
murder for tying James Byrd to a pickup truck and dragging him to 
his death on June 7. Jurors today start considering whether King 
should receive the death penalty for his action. King was the first 
of three white men to go on trial in the slaying. 

</P>
<P>
	Holocaust Victim List Computerized  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- An Israeli memorial that compiled millions of  
names of Holocaust victims in a computer over the years is being 
unveiled today. The list will first be used to help track victims' 
unclaimed assets in Swiss banks. But in the long run, Israel's Yad 
Vashem Holocaust Memorial hopes to establish a central database, to 
be accessible through the Internet and to boost research, said 
memorial chairman, Avner Shalev. 

</P>
<P>
	Atom Bomb Is Top Story of Century  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prominent U.S. journalists and scholars have  
declared the dropping of atomic bombs in Hiroshima and Nagasaki 
during World War II the top news event of the 20th century. A 
selection of the top 100 news events of the last 100 years named 
U.S. astronaut Neil Armstrong's walk on the moon in 1969, second on 
the list. 

</P>
<P>
	Partial Kosovo Peace Deal Reached  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- Serbs agreed in principle yesterday  
to give limited self-rule to majority ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, 
but the two sides failed to conclude a deal for ending their 
yearlong conflict. More talks were scheduled for March as a new 
round of violence shook the province. The partial settlement puts 
on hold, at least temporarily, NATO's threats to bomb Serb targets 
if they don't withdraw troops from Kosovo and accept NATO 
peacekeepers. 

</P>
<P>
	Austria Avalanche Kills at Least 10  
</P>
<P>
	LANDECK, Austria (AP) -- Austrian soldiers took advantage of a  
break in heavy snowfall today to mount a rescue of avalanche 
victims from a stricken Alpine town. They joined villagers who dug 
with their bare hands in a frantic effort to reach those buried 
below. The confirmed death toll from Tuesday's avalanche at Galtuer 
stood at 10 early today, but was expected to rise. Provincial 
governor Wendelin Weingartner told reporters 31 people were still 
missing in the village in the Tyrol province, near the Swiss 
border. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock End Day Down  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Shares fell after a two day rise as the Nikkei shed  
145.20 points, closing the day at 14,355.45. 

</P>
<P>
	Rodman Signs With Lakers  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- It's official -- Dennis Rodman is a Los  
Angeles Laker. The NBA's dominant rebounder of the '90s has signed 
a one-year contract with the Lakers and will participate in a 
limited practice session today, team spokesman John Black said. A 
source close to Rodman said the eccentric forward spent much of 
yesterday doing post-production services on the movie ``Simon 
Sez,'' to be released later this year, but took a break to sign the 
contract. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KATHLEEN SAMPEY  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
