<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 13:36:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Lower; Dow Off 144.75 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks beat a hasty retreat in the final hour of  
trading to close lower, after bond prices slid and pushed interest 
rates higher. 
</P>
<P>
	At the closing bell on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 144.75 at 9,399.67. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow opened softer but quickly rallied in the morning,  
peaking at just over 9,600, or up 55 points, before trimming its 
gains in late morning and then staging an outright retreat in the 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although (stock) market internals don't look so bad, the  
weakness in bonds is a problem,'' said Scott Bleier, chief 
investment strategist at Prime Charter. ``There doesn't seem to be 
any great desire to one thing or another, except that bonds are 
lower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year bond was down more than a point, or $10  
for every $1,000 valuation. Its yield, which moves opposite the 
price, moved above the critical 5.5 percent to 5.51 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The rise in interest rates was particularly injurious to  
technology and financial stocks, which had been providing some 
leadership to the upside in recent sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was led lower by Hewlett-Packard, down 2 3/8 at 70 3/4, and  
American Express, down 3 15/16 at 107 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The late decline in technology stocks pushed broad indicators  
lower as well. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, which had been in 
record high territory earlier in the session, was off 17.77 at 
1,253.41. The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was higher 
most of the day but finally capitulated, too, ending 36.95 lower at 
2,339.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues overtook advancers late in the day on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where volume was moderate and well below 
Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds weakened after the Treasury sold a total of $15 billion in  
new, two-year notes at 5.009 percent, a six-month high. 
</P>
<P>
	And neither market was helped by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan  
Greenspan's testimony before a Congressional committee. Making his 
second appearance in two days on Capitol Hill, Greenspan reiterated 
signals that the Fed is more likely to raise interest rates over 
the near term than to shorten them. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said the Fed expects the U.S. economy to slow to a  
growth rate of between 2.5 percent and 3 percent this year, down 
from about 4 percent in 1998. But, he warned that the economy is 
``stretched'' after eight years of expansion and suggested the Fed 
may need to raise interest rates if the growth in the economy does 
not slow as expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock investors would not welcome higher interest rates, which  
would raise corporate borrowing costs and could eat into earnings. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 05:44:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Leader Warns Against Infighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Republican National Committee chairman  
Jim Nicholson says he'll ``blow the whistle'' on GOP presidential 
candidates who begin attacking each other and voters will punish 
those contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to GOP activists just a year before the first  
presidential primaries and caucuses, Nicholson said the party can't 
endure another bruising primary season if it hopes to recapture the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have an adversary and it is not us, it is them,'' Nicholson  
said. ``It is the Democratic Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said he would serve as the GOP's referee, crying foul  
when a Republican begins attacking another. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, I am pulling on the striped shirt and I will blow the  
whistle on any candidate or campaign that tries to tear down 
another Republican with personal attacks,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The site for his speech was chosen with care. Iowa's precinct  
caucuses traditionally are the opening round in the nominating 
season and the campaign in 1996 was brutal. 
</P>
<P>
	Publisher Steve Forbes jumped in late and based his hopes on a  
television advertising campaign that blasted eventual nominee Bob 
Dole. Dole said that assault weakened him in the general election, 
and Nicholson agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, we looked at '96 in taking the steps that we're  
taking,'' he said. ``I think Senator Dole was hurt by personal 
attacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Nicholson quickly added that his latest effort was aimed at  
the entire GOP field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not aimed at anyone in particular,'' he said. ``It is  
aimed at seeing it doesn't happen again and we're trying to head it 
off at the pass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While party leaders have little ability to enforce discipline,  
Nicholson said voters will enforce the new campaign standard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
