<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Padres Could Sell Out in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) -- Baseball officials expect a sellout for  
the first international opener in major league history, even though 
it will cost many Mexican fans more than two days' wages for the 
cheap seats. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the reasons for having these games is to underscore the  
presence of baseball in these countries and the possibility in the 
future that major league baseball would come to a country like 
Mexico,'' Sandy Alderson, the new executive vice president of 
baseball operations in the commissioner's office, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the Montreal Expos and Alderson's former team, the  
Oakland Athletics, unsure of their future, Alderson didn't sound as 
if another round of expansion is ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure it's likely that there will be any expansion in  
the next four or five years, regardless of location,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 14,000 tickets for the April 4 opener between the NL  
champion San Diego Padres and Colorado Rockies go on sale in Mexico 
on Thursday. Another 12,000 tickets for the game at the 26,000-seat 
Estadio Monterrey are reserved for the two teams, sponsors, 
officials and dignitaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The cheapest seats in the outfield will be on sale for 100  
pesos, nearly $10 at the current exchange rate and 2.5 times the 
minimum wage earned by a large percentage of workers. 
</P>
<P>
	More expensive tickets range from 150 pesos to 600 pesos --  
roughly $15 to $60. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball takes a back seat to soccer in most of Mexico, but its  
roots here go back for generations and Mexican sports commentators 
often noted last year that Mexico has more internationally 
successful baseball players than soccer players. 
</P>
<P>
	Monterrey is the heart of an urban area of about 3 million  
people at the edge of the eastern Sierra Madre mountain range and 
is one of Mexico's most dynamic business centers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres and New York Mets played a three-game series at  
Estadio Monterrey in August 1996, the first regular-season games 
outside the United States and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego sold 40,000 tickets in the Baja California city of  
Tijuana during the 1998 season and last year opened a retail store 
there, according to Mike Dee, the team's vice president of business 
operations. Dee also said that 20 percent of the team's fans are 
Hispanic and a ``significant portion'' come from Mexico. Of the 
team's nine probable opening-day starters, five will be of Mexican 
or Latin American descent, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not view Mexico as an extension of our market,'' he  
said. ``We view Mexico as our home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball officials are planning more promotions in Mexico and  
are studying a plan to allow All-Star balloting in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
