<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Saddam Won't Intimidate US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today accused Saddam Hussein  
of trying to score ``a symbolic victory'' by targeting U.S. 
warplanes over Iraq, but said America will not be intimidated. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joint news conference with President Jerry Rawlings of  
Ghana, Clinton also said the United States had not given up hope of 
eventually restoring United Nations inspections of Iraq's weapons 
holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, speaking hours after U.S. and British warplanes  
attacked targets on the outskirts of the Iraqi capital, said, 
``They're trying obviously for the symbolic victory of shooting one 
of these planes down and perhaps trying to intimidate us from 
enforcing the no-fly zone, which we're still bound to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said, ``We have not given up on the prospect of restoring  
inspections'' in Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	It was his second meeting with reporters since the Senate  
acquitted him of perjury and obstruction of justice charges on Feb. 
12 in connection with his affair with former White House intern 
Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, events overseas dominated the questioning.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the United States has an interest in resolving the  
Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``Does the United States have an immediate selfish interest in  
what happens on some lonely road in Kosovo to some poor family 
driving some wagon with horses that are underfed because they 
haven't been able to get food? No. I would argue we have a 
humanitarian interest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States does have a direct interest in whether there  
is instability in the Balkans,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is considering sending up to 4,000 U.S. troops as part  
of a 28,000-strong NATO force that would go to Kosovo for at least 
three years if a peace plan were implemented. Peace talks in France 
ended this week without a solid agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings said assistance from the United Nations would be  
helpful in peacekeeping, and he would be willing to lend troops to 
such a force. But he said other countries may have to contribute as 
well, because African nations are struggling under the burden of 
responding to conflict in other parts of the continent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our resources are stretched to the very limit,'' Rawlings  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Touching on domestic issues, Clinton said he has ``some ideas''  
about whether the independent counsel statute under which Kenneth 
Starr investigated him should expire, but said he will not make 
them public until others air their views. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would be better for me at this time to say less so  
that others can say more,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said White House lawyers will testify before Congress  
about the independent counsel law next week, and he would make his 
feeling known at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	The law, which was inspired by the Watergate scandal, expires  
this summer and many legislators in both parties are anxious to see 
it expire or undergo a dramatic overhaul. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton refused to comment on allegations by a Little Rock,  
Ark., woman, Juanita Broaddrick, who says she was sexually 
assaulted by him in 1978. Clinton, who was attorney general at the 
time, said he stood by his the statement of his attorney, who has 
called the allegations ``absolutely false.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And he dismissed the claim by some Republican lawmakers that  
they can't trust him in the wake of the Lewinsky affair. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their feelings are not important here,'' he said. ``Just like  
my feelings are not important. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have an oath to fulfill, and a responsibility to fulfill.  
We were hired to do the public's business,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
