<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 15:43:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spotlight Is Off D-Backs' Williams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Matt Williams isn't the focus of attention  
at spring training this year, and he loves it. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, he was arguably the biggest name in the clubhouse of  
the expansion Arizona Diamondbacks, and what followed was one of 
his toughest seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he's quietly preparing for what he hopes will be a comeback  
year with fewer nagging injuries and lots more RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' Williams said. ``I may  
hit a whole bunch of homers this year. What I'm going to try to do 
is be as consistent as possible. Consistency is the key. Whether I 
hit five home runs or 40 home runs, my job is to drive in runs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams is no rah-rah guy, no big talker. Not rude but not  
outgoing, either. He's intense and extremely self-critical. So last 
year's statistics were frustrating -- a .267 batting average with 20 
home runs, his fewest since 1992, And worst of all, 71 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a difficult year,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Defensively, he was as good as ever. He had 11 errors, none in  
the last 35 games, and finished fourth among NL third basemen with 
a .972 fielding percentage. 
</P>
<P>
	But both ankles and both hands were hurt at one point or  
another, either by foul balls or by pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly make no excuses,'' he said, ``but it's not fun  
going out there with both hands hurting and your feet hurting. It 
took me probably to mid-November or December to heal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He hit into 19 double plays and struck out 102 times in 510  
at-bats. All the while, he felt the glare of attention. 
</P>
<P>
	But Williams, 33, has been around long enough to know that it's  
just one year. He has had at least 20 homers in each of the last 
nine seasons, something no other current player has accomplished. 
He's one homer short of the 300 mark for his career. And he's come 
back before. 
</P>
<P>
	``In '92 I had a down year,'' he said, ``I played everyday. I  
wasn't injured, but I had a down year, and I came back the next 
year and had a good one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statistics bear him out. In 1992, his sixth of 10 seasons  
with the San Francisco Giants, Williams hit .227 with 20 homers and 
66 RBIs. The next year, he hit .294 with 38 homers and 110 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	His huge year was the strike-shortened 1994 season, when he hit  
43 home runs in 112 games. People talked about him breaking Roger 
Maris' record of 61. He joked last season, as he watched Mark 
McGwire go through the intense media attention, that he'd probably 
have refused to talk to anyone as the pressure got higher. 
</P>
<P>
	During the offseason Williams worked out rigorously.  
</P>
<P>
	``Running, lifting, treadmill work, agility work, running the  
stairs in the stadium -- you name it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was married -- to actress Michelle Johnson -- in a lavish  
ceremony at his home in the Phoenix suburb of Paradise Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	As reporters and television cameras crowded around the lockers  
of others this spring, Williams happily stayed in the background. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we're getting closer to creating a better and  
better atmosphere that doesn't put all the focus on one guy having 
to carry the weight,'' manager Buck Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	After he was traded to Arizona from Cleveland, he signed a  
five-year, $45 contract extension that begins with this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I'm physically able to go out there and compete at a high  
level, then I'll continue to play,'' he said. ``When the day comes 
where I can't compete anymore physically, where I'm not able to get 
to that ground ball or I'm not able to hit the ball the way I want 
to, then I'll hang them up and have no regrets. Until that day 
comes, I'll go out and give them hell.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
