<DOCNO> APW19990224.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 15:34:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres' Hasek Will Sit It Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Dominik Hasek has been so good for so long  
that the Buffalo Sabres sometimes take their superstar goaltender 
for granted. That is, until he gets hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes we get used to him making great saves,'' defenseman  
Darryl Shannon said. ``But that doesn't mean we don't skate as hard 
when he's in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He usually doesn't give up more than two goals,'' Sabres coach  
Lindy Ruff said. ``In the beginning of the season when we really 
didn't play well as a team he filled the holes in a couple of games 
where we gave up 20 to 30 scoring chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even machines break down when they run too hot for too long.  
When Hasek injured his groin in a 3-2 loss to Toronto last week it 
proved he was human. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always want to be on the ice, but I cannot be on the ice if  
I am not healthy or my groin is not good enough,'' Hasek said. ``I 
have to be careful. I hope I'll be back this week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff said Hasek probably would practice Thursday and play  
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he ever admits he needs a rest,'' Ruff said.  
``That's the kind of thing where I have to start stepping in and 
just give him a rest even when he doesn't want it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Which is never. ``He likes to play, he likes to work,'' Ruff  
said. ``With today's schedule, it's the mental part of the game 
that wears a player down most.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until sidelined by injury, Hasek had started all but three of  
the Sabres' 55 games and faced 1,553 shots, second most in the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	Dwayne Roloson had made only three starts when he got the call.  
He stopped 30 shots in a 4-2 victory over San Jose and made 34 
saves in a 4-4 tie with defending league champion Detroit on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, who led the league in save percentage each of the past  
five seasons and won the Hart Trophy the past two seasons as the 
NHL's most valuable player, has raised a lofty standard. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the best goalie in the world right now and I'll just  
learn whatever I can from him and hope that things work out,'' 
Roloson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roloson knows he's no Dominik Hasek. But at times this season,  
even Hasek hasn't been himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek was starting to show signs of wear after playing his  
sharpest hockey at the beginning of the season. The NHL named him 
its player of the month for December, in which he had a 1.45 
goals-against average and four shutouts. 
</P>
<P>
	But New Jersey chased Hasek off the ice early in the second  
period of a 7-4 victory on Dec. 28. The Devils scored goals on 
their first three shots and four goals on six shots. 
</P>
<P>
	After losing an overtime game to Anaheim two nights later, Hasek  
gave up seven goals on 31 shots in a 7-2 loss to Anaheim on New 
Year's Day. Roloson got his first two starts soon after. 
</P>
<P>
	As Buffalo struggled earlier this month Hasek criticized the  
team for what he identified as a lack of effort. He didn't name any 
names, but his teammates got the point. 
</P>
<P>
	Media, players and fans braced for a Hasek meltdown, but the  
team turned things around. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, he's had a better a season than last year,'' Ruff  
said. ``The first 30 games he was unbelievable. Any goaltender can 
have a couple games where you would like some goals back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others try to emulate Hasek's acrobatic flops but few have the  
quickness. Sabres goaltender Martin Biron, a 21-year-old who has 
shown promise playing in Rochester this season, believes it helps 
to pay attention to Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way Dominik has been playing the last couple of years has  
been changing a lot of things for goalies,'' Biron said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way he lies on his back in the crease when there is a  
scramble, the way he throws his stick away and uses his blocker,'' 
said Biron, a first-round draft choice for the Sabres in 1995. 
``These are things that Steve Shields started doing when he was 
here a couple of years ago. Dwayne Roloson is starting to do them 
and now I'm starting to do them, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, if they could just find someone who could do them as well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
