<HEADLINE> Hoffman Talks Contract With Padres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ariz. (AP) -- San Diego Padres general manager Kevin  
Towers and closer Trevor Hoffman spent four hours discussing the 
player's pending free agent status at the end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt it was pretty productive,'' Towers said of the Tuesday  
night meeting, declining to give details. ``I felt pretty good when 
I left. Hopefully it was mutual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffman left Wednesday's workout early to tend to his wife  
Tracy, who is expecting the couple's third child. Reached through a 
spokesman, he declined to comment his talk with Towers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres have offered Hoffman a $24 million, four-year  
extension, but he is believed to be seeking $30 million over four 
years with a no-trade clause. Talks between the two sides broke off 
in December, so the dinner represented the first discussions since 
then. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never at all looked at by going in and having dinner with  
him I was going to come out and have him signed,'' Towers said. 
``More than anything it was just to talk, just as friends, and find 
out what his thought process was. I think I left the dinner having 
a pretty good idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Towers said they didn't talk about salary. He didn't elaborate,  
except to say, ``Trevor likes San Diego. I'll let him talk for 
himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Towers also said left-handed reliever Randy Myers likely won't  
be at camp until Saturday. That will be nine days after the 
pitchers and catchers reported, and four days after the 
full-squad's reporting date. 
</P>
<P>
	Towers is frustrated that he hasn't heard from Myers. Towers  
left a telephone message with Myers about nine days ago telling him 
he'd really like him in camp by Feb. 23. The mandatory reporting 
date for is March 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers, who has a history of reporting late to camp, is  
reportedly spending the extra time working with his charitable 
foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	``He may have a good excuse, but just to be late to be late, I  
don't think is right,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
