<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Continue Retreat / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) --Grain and soybean futures retreated again today on  
the Chicago Board of Trade, weighed down by a pessimistic outlook 
for export demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat and soybeans led the declines, pressured by government  
forecasts this week that supplies will continue to grow while 
global economic troubles curb demand from Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans have faced the heaviest pressure amid expectations of  
increased U.S. plantings this spring and large competing crops from 
Argentina and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, wheat for March delivery fell 2 3/4 cents to  
$2.49 a bushel; March corn fell 1 3/4 cents to $2.13 1/4 a bushel; March 
oats fell 1/2 cent to $1.01 3/4 a bushel; March soybeans fell 6 cents to 
$4.68 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and pork futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while feeder cattle were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle fell 0.07 cent to 67.55 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle rose 0.13 cent to 74.10 cents a pound; April lean 
hogs fell 0.80 cent to 44.45 cents a pound; March pork bellies fell 
1.45 cents to 51.35 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
