<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $65M Offer To Buy Out Marge Schott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A group headed by the brother of Cablevision's  
chairman has offered to buy controlling interest in the Cincinnati 
Reds, the first step in a lengthy process that will end up with 
Marge Schott selling most of her shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's limited partners have the right to match the offer by  
Larry Dolan's group and keep control of baseball's first 
professional franchise in local hands. The limited partners have 
indicated they are willing to match any offer. 
</P>
<P>
	No sale is expected for months because there are so many steps  
left in the process and details to work out. 
</P>
<P>
	``The process is just beginning,'' Dolan's son, Paul, said  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Dolan, who is based in Cleveland, has been part of groups  
that attempted to buy other sports franchises, including the NFL 
expansion Cleveland Browns, Washington Redskins and New York 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	The 68-year-old lawyer is the brother of Charles Dolan, chairman  
of Cablevision Systems Corp., a major cable television provider and 
the owner of Madison Square Garden, the New York Knicks and New 
York Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan's offer, first reported in The Cincinnati Enquirer and  
later confirmed by a baseball official who spoke on the condition 
he not be identified, would give Schott $65 million for 5 1/2 of her 
6 1/2 shares in the team. By holding onto one share, Schott could 
still keep a ceremonial role with the Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott, 70, agreed last year to sell her control over the team  
rather than accept another suspension. The current ownership 
arrangement expires on Dec. 31, 2000, when the limited partners can 
vote her out. 
</P>
<P>
	Backed into a corner by major league baseball and the  
partnership's upcoming expiration, Schott has been listening to 
offers to sell. Paul Dolan, a lawyer in his father's firm, said 
that the Reds were an attractive franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's Ohio, it's nearby to us, it's a storied franchise and  
it's baseball,'' Paul Dolan said in a telephone interview from his 
law office in Cleveland. ``For us, it's comfortable. It's not our 
hometown, but it kind of feels like it's a cousin, if you will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan declined to say whether his group has contacted any of the  
team's limited partners. If the partners decide to match the offer, 
Dolan's group would not be interested in trying to obtain a limited 
role, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not interested in being one of the limited partners,''  
Dolan said. ``This is something we'd want to own and control. 
Whether we do that with partners or without them is dependent upon 
this process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dolan's group has not yet signed a definitive contract, the  
baseball official said. Dolan's next step would be to meet with the 
limited partners, who control the other 8 1/2 shares. 
</P>
<P>
	If Dolan's group signs a contract, the limited partners would  
have the right to match it. Dolan is not expected to sign a deal 
until he knows the limited partners' intentions. 
</P>
<P>
	If Dolan signed a deal and the limited partners didn't match, he  
could wind up controlling a partnership whose status is uncertain 
after December 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott did not return telephone messages on Wednesday.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
