<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Surgery Shown on Experimental Net </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a live demonstration of the promise of a  
superfast Internet, a physician in Washington collaborated 
Wednesday night over a special high-speed network with surgeons 
working on a patient at a hospital in Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The remote ``operation'' took place over the $500 million  
Abilene Network, a new data pipeline that links more than three 
dozen research universities nationwide. It works at speeds 45,000 
times faster than the best telephone modems that people now use to 
surf the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2.4 gigabits a second, the computer connection is faster than  
all but a few experimental federal government networks. It was 
largely financed privately by corporations and is run by a 
nonprofit group based in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Rogers, the director of the Abilene Network, said the  
advances in research from the network promise to revolutionize the 
Internet familiar to most computer users. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our Internet of today will be as different than TV is from  
books,'' Rogers said Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Abilene Network will be used solely by academics and other  
professional researchers, with no way to let home users dial in. 
But its benefits are expected to trickle down to consumers in just 
a few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is inevitable that applications would migrate to the  
consumer Internet for the benefit of all users,'' said Stephen 
Wolff, executive director of Cisco Systems Inc.'s advanced Internet 
division. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco supplied about $5 million worth of high-tech plumbing for  
the network. 
</P>
<P>
	The demonstration linked Dr. Jerry Johnson, at Washington's  
Union Station rail terminal, with a surgical team at Ohio State 
University's hospital, performing laparoscopic surgery by snaking a 
miniature video camera inside a volunteer patient suffering from a 
gastrointestinal disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, a doctor and researcher at Ohio State, talked with his  
colleagues using wireless microphones and a video camera, with the 
words and pictures transmitted across the high-speed Internet 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Remote surgery is not feasible with today's Internet, in part  
because of the potential for gridlock caused by the huge flow of 
other data -- everything from Web sites to office jokes circulated 
via e-mail to computer games played across the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	To avoid such Internet traffic jams, hospitals typically use  
expensive closed-circuit video systems sent over satellite links 
instead. 
</P>
<P>
	The network is named after the town in Kansas that was an  
important railhead in the nation's history. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:59:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NASA May Repair Hubble Telescope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mechanical problems that threaten to shut down  
the astronomical observations of the Hubble Space Telescope may 
prompt a repair mission six months earlier than planned to the $1.7 
billion spacecraft, NASA officials told Congress on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is ailing gyroscopes, said Daniel Goldin, the  
administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. 
Gyroscopes are used for the stability and fine pointing the Hubble 
needs to gather light from stars billions of light years away. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of all gyroscopes would mean the space telescope could  
not make astronomical observations, but it would not threaten the 
spacecraft, officials said. Instead, the failure of the gyros would 
cause the craft to go into an automatic ``safe mode'' until the 
repairs are made. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hubble was launched in 1990 and immediately had problems.  
Astronomers discovered that the 2.4-meter mirror on the telescope 
had been ground to the wrong curvature and the instrument, in 
effect, was nearsighted. 
</P>
<P>
	But a new set of optics installed by astronauts in 1993  
corrected the problem. And since then, the Hubble has made 
photographs of tens of thousands of previously unseen galaxies, 
giving unprecedented views of the heavens. Some of the stellar 
targets are more than 13 billion light years away, near the 
theoretical edge of the universe. The Hubble was designed to remain 
operational until 2010. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hubble needs three gyroscopes to work properly and it has  
lost two of its six. Another gyro ``is sick and may go down in 
three months,'' Goldin said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Hubble loses a fourth gyro, it will have to be shut down  
until a space shuttle crew goes up to the orbiting telescope and 
installs a new set of gyroscopes, he said. A decision about an 
emergency mission is expected no later than next week. 
</P>
<P>
	For practical planning, the spacecraft is already on the edge of  
losing gyroscope control because one of the remaining four control 
instruments ``is quite ill,'' said David S. Leckrone, senior 
project scientist for the telescope. 
</P>
<P>
	``If another gyro fails, we would not put the fourth gyro back  
into service,'' he said, meaning that the Hubble is only one 
failure away from being shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is in wires that carry power to the rapidly spinning  
gyroscopes. The gyros can operate on either of the two wires, but 
when one wire breaks, it causes an increase in voltage carried by 
the other. 
</P>
<P>
	In earlier gyroscope failures, engineers saw a sudden increase  
in voltage carried by one wire. Within weeks, that wire also 
failed. One wire has already failed in the ailing gyro, said 
Leckrone. 
</P>
<P>
	Should all of Hubble's gyroscopes shut down, he said, the  
spacecraft would switch automatically to a safe mode that keeps its 
solar power array pointed at the sun. As long as the craft is 
powered by the sun, engineers on the ground can control it. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA already had planned for a June 2000, Hubble servicing  
mission that would include replacing all of the gyroscopes, along 
with a computer and some other instruments. But Leckrone said he 
and others at the Goddard Spaceflight Center have proposed that an 
emergency mission be flown this October to change out the ailing 
gyros, and that the rest of the serving be done on a mission in 
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier servicing mission to change cameras and other  
equipment was flown in 1997, and a final servicing mission is 
planned for 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 15:34:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BoSox Offerman Takes It in Stride </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Don't expect Jose Offerman to do what Mo  
Vaughn did for the Boston Red Sox. And don't expect the $26 million 
man to apologize for a contract criticized as too rich. 
</P>
<P>
	Free agency cost the team Vaughn, who hit 40 homers last season,  
and brought them Offerman, who has 22 since he arrived in the 
majors in 1990 with Los Angeles. While the Red Sox wouldn't give 
Vaughn the $80 million contract Anaheim did, they rewarded Offerman 
with a four-year deal averaging $6.5 million annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Not bad for a .278 career hitter.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care what people say,'' Offerman said Wednesday. ``I  
believe they paid me for a reason and thank God it happened with 
them because there was another team that was interested in me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland appeared to be Boston's main competition for Offerman,  
although he said Baltimore and Seattle also were interested. 
</P>
<P>
	The criticism of the contract ``really doesn't bother me,'' Red  
Sox general manager Dan Duquette said. ``We're paying him about 
what we pay (third baseman) John Valentin. That, to me, is like the 
going rate for qualified established major-league infielders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The contract, though, and his connection with Vaughn could make  
Fenway Park fans impatient for Offerman to produce. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not fair to compare myself with him,'' Offerman said.  
``We are two different players, and the things he can do are hard 
for me to do. My job is to be on base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did that well the past three years with Kansas City, hitting  
.303, .297 and a career-high .315. He led the majors with 13 
triples last season and was fifth in the American League with a 
.403 on-base percentage and 45 stolen bases. 
</P>
<P>
	He went to Kansas City after the 1995 season in a trade from Los  
Angeles. During his stay with the Dodgers, he led the majors in 
errors in three times, causing strained relations with manager 
Tommy Lasorda. 
</P>
<P>
	His defense and hitting both improved in Kansas City, where he  
was the everyday second baseman the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The difference was that I was a lot more comfortable there,''  
Offerman said. ``It was hard for me to play (in Los Angeles). There 
was a lot of pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Second base is his favorite position, although he could see time  
as at first and at designated hitter with Boston. He took grounders 
at second with the other starting infielders Wednesday, although 
his main competitor for the starting job, Jeff Frye, has a strained 
rib area that limited his activity. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was so young in LA,'' said Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez,  
a fellow Dominican and Offerman's teammate on the Dodgers in 1993. 
``It was a rough field. It's not only Jose who had some problems in 
the past in Dodger Stadium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez may have eased Offerman's transition to Fenway Park;  
more Dominican fans showed up when Martinez pitched. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there will be the focus on Vaughn's departure and  
Offerman's arrival. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have to try to do the things he does because my job is  
a lot different than his,'' Offerman said. ``He's got a lot more 
power than me. My job is to be on base for the rest of the guys. 
The money is no reason for me to change.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:59:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NASA May Repair Hubble Telescope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mechanical problems that threaten to shut down  
the astronomical observations of the Hubble Space Telescope may 
prompt a repair mission six months earlier than planned to the $1.7 
billion spacecraft, NASA officials told Congress on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is ailing gyroscopes, said Daniel Goldin, the  
administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. 
Gyroscopes are used for the stability and fine pointing the Hubble 
needs to gather light from stars billions of light years away. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of all gyroscopes would mean the space telescope could  
not make astronomical observations, but it would not threaten the 
spacecraft, officials said. Instead, the failure of the gyros would 
cause the craft to go into an automatic ``safe mode'' until the 
repairs are made. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hubble was launched in 1990 and immediately had problems.  
Astronomers discovered that the 2.4-meter mirror on the telescope 
had been ground to the wrong curvature and the instrument, in 
effect, was nearsighted. 
</P>
<P>
	But a new set of optics installed by astronauts in 1993  
corrected the problem. And since then, the Hubble has made 
photographs of tens of thousands of previously unseen galaxies, 
giving unprecedented views of the heavens. Some of the stellar 
targets are more than 13 billion light years away, near the 
theoretical edge of the universe. The Hubble was designed to remain 
operational until 2010. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hubble needs three gyroscopes to work properly and it has  
lost two of its six. Another gyro ``is sick and may go down in 
three months,'' Goldin said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Hubble loses a fourth gyro, it will have to be shut down  
until a space shuttle crew goes up to the orbiting telescope and 
installs a new set of gyroscopes, he said. A decision about an 
emergency mission is expected no later than next week. 
</P>
<P>
	For practical planning, the spacecraft is already on the edge of  
losing gyroscope control because one of the remaining four control 
instruments ``is quite ill,'' said David S. Leckrone, senior 
project scientist for the telescope. 
</P>
<P>
	``If another gyro fails, we would not put the fourth gyro back  
into service,'' he said, meaning that the Hubble is only one 
failure away from being shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is in wires that carry power to the rapidly spinning  
gyroscopes. The gyros can operate on either of the two wires, but 
when one wire breaks, it causes an increase in voltage carried by 
the other. 
</P>
<P>
	In earlier gyroscope failures, engineers saw a sudden increase  
in voltage carried by one wire. Within weeks, that wire also 
failed. One wire has already failed in the ailing gyro, said 
Leckrone. 
</P>
<P>
	Should all of Hubble's gyroscopes shut down, he said, the  
spacecraft would switch automatically to a safe mode that keeps its 
solar power array pointed at the sun. As long as the craft is 
powered by the sun, engineers on the ground can control it. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA already had planned for a June 2000, Hubble servicing  
mission that would include replacing all of the gyroscopes, along 
with a computer and some other instruments. But Leckrone said he 
and others at the Goddard Spaceflight Center have proposed that an 
emergency mission be flown this October to change out the ailing 
gyros, and that the rest of the serving be done on a mission in 
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier servicing mission to change cameras and other  
equipment was flown in 1997, and a final servicing mission is 
planned for 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
