<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campos' Dad Discusses Kidnapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The father of Mexican soccer star Jorge  
Campos said Wednesday that his captors told him they had been 
mistaken to take him hostage. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of the people, all of Acapulco, all of Guerrero (state)  
love you,'' Alvaro Campos said his kidnappers told him during his 
six days in captivity, the Televisa network reported. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after being freed, Campos spoke briefly from a  
second-story window to reporters gathered on the street outside his 
home in Acapulco. 
</P>
<P>
	The silver-haired Campos said he was in good health, and he even  
joked about his ordeal. ``They fed me better than my wife,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Campos, 66, was released Tuesday morning along a highway outside  
of Acapulco, the resort city in the western state of Guerrero. He 
did not say whether a ransom had been paid, and his son has told 
reporters he wasn't aware of any payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Armed men seized the elder Campos on Feb. 17 at a sports field  
named for his son near Acapulco. 
</P>
<P>
	Kidnapping has become a growing criminal industry in Mexico, but  
the crime stunned many because of the great affection for Jorge 
Campos, a star in the U.S. and Mexican soccer leagues who played in 
the 1994 and 1998 World Cups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:26:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from editorials in newspapers in the United  
States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 21  
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Enquirer, on income tax cuts:  
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, has proposed cutting income tax rates  
by 10 percent, returning about $375 billion to taxpayers over five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	This secular tithe should be a no-brainer. The feds are living  
high on the surplus hog, thanks to average Americans' hard work and 
productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	But as usual, the White House is twisting the argument.  
Spokesmen from President Clinton on down claim it would be 
irresponsible to ``spend'' -- an Orwellian choice of words -- any 
surplus on tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House wants to have it both ways. It counts on decades  
of surpluses and good economic news to project its Social Security 
fix. But the minute tax cuts are proposed, we hear doom and gloom 
and class-warfare slogans about ``tax breaks for the rich.'' 
</P>
<P>
	History has shown that the best way to encourage growth and  
prosperity is to cut taxes to a reasonable level that doesn't drain 
the economy. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 10  
</P>
<P>
	South County Journal, Kent, Wash., on Mexico and drugs:  
</P>
<P>
	What to do when a nation's drug trafficking and corruption are  
growing increasingly worse? Why, you reward them, of course. 
</P>
<P>
	That's essentially what President Clinton is proposing after his  
summit with President Zedillo of Mexico. Clinton praised Mexico's 
effort to ``root out this scourge.'' He is expected to ask Congress 
to re-certify Mexico's anti-drug compliance, which would avoid 
trade and economic sanctions. Mexico, the president says, is 
``fully cooperating'' on this issue. 
</P>
<P>
	True, Mexico has announced ``a total war against drug  
trafficking.'' Government officials vowed to spend close to $500 
million over the next three years on better radar, ships and planes 
to patrol its drug corridors. But this new strategy was 
conveniently announced just 10 days before Clinton's visit to 
Mexico. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 21  
</P>
<P>
	Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal, on possible attack in Kosovo:  
</P>
<P>
	Air Force stealth fighters from Holloman departing for the  
potential war zone bring the increasing tensions over Kosovo in 
Yugoslavia home to New Mexico. But even without the prospect of 
pilots from New Mexico going into action, the escalating rhetoric 
over NATO response to Serb intransigence on a settlement of ethnic 
conflict in the Yugoslavian province should be more carefully 
considered. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., warned of the possibility of U.S.  
casualties if American ground forces were committed to a 
peacekeeping force, as proposed by President Clinton. Domenici said 
he had no objections to NATO air strikes to persuade Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic to see the error of his ways -- but air 
strikes alone will never decide the issue. One has only to consider 
the intransigence of Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein to acknowledge 
that American air power is a hollow instrument of coercion when 
applied alone. 
</P>
<P>
	The tragedy of atrocities against the Albanian ethnic majority  
in Kosovo cry out for solution, but a reflexive military response 
with no long-term plan could multiply the tragedy without solving 
the problem. NATO and the United States should carefully plan a 
complete operation in a form that has some reasonable possibility 
of success before committing forces to action. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 21  
</P>
<P>
	Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune, on Y2K readiness:  
</P>
<P>
	Warnings that fear of the year 2000 computer glitch might cause  
more problems than the ``millennium bug'' itself may not surprise 
many retirees. Having survived the Great Depression, several wars 
and the generational revolution of the '60s, they aren't likely to 
panic over a few zeros. ... 
</P>
<P>
	In some systems, when the computer's internal clock rolls over  
to 00 on Jan. 1, the computer won't know it means the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Seniors are likely to approach the so-called ``Y2K'' glitch as  
if it were a hurricane, taking many of the same precautions they 
would for such a storm -- putting away some cash, topping off the 
gas tank in the car and storing a few days' supply of food and 
other staples. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Computer systems analysts and project managers remain divided in  
their projections of the impacts of the Y2K problem. But there's a 
strong consensus on what not to do -- panic. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Some good advice ... transcends not only seasons but the passage  
of time and the acceleration of the computer age. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 16  
</P>
<P>
	The Register-Herald, Beckley, W.Va., on Ken Starr:  
</P>
<P>
	The impeachment trial is over, but Independent Counsel Ken  
Starr's costly and mostly fruitless probe into William Jefferson 
Clinton's life continues. 
</P>
<P>
	How much money must be spent and how many lives ruined before  
Starr's lust for Republican revenge is satisfied? 
</P>
<P>
	Enough is enough. Call off your dogs, sir.  
</P>
<P>
	Starr's original intentions might have been good. Somewhere  
along the way, however, Starr's quest for the truth lost any 
resemblance to business and became strictly personal. 
</P>
<P>
	He's obsessed with bringing Clinton down. The Senate has  
acquitted the president, but now Starr is talking about indicting 
the president himself. Some insiders say Starr has already made up 
his mind to do it. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's case doesn't hold water. The impeachment process proved  
that. He cannot be allowed to waste more tax dollars on this witch 
hunt. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Starr had his chance and failed. Rather than being a sore loser,  
the independent counsel should take his lumps and get over it. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Antelope Valley Press, Palmdale, Calif., on Elizabeth Dole:  
</P>
<P>
	Dole for President? Again? ... No, not that Dole. That was Bob  
Dole. He lost in a run for president a couple of years ago, but he 
may make another bid for the White House -- as the nation's first 
first gentleman. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole, a Harvard-educated lawyer who's worked for  
presidents since Lyndon Johnson in the mid-60s, is showing all the 
signs of running for president in 2000. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole, 62, is smart, smooth, quick on her feet, and she  
knows the issues. ... It's way too early for endorsements, but we 
welcome Elizabeth Dole to the table. It's about time a woman had a 
legitimate shot at the highest office in the land. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole knows how to go about things. Take education. The  
Republicans get into trouble when they bash education and allow the 
Democrats to paint them as ``anti-child.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than ranting and raving about what's wrong, there's a  
better way to go about it, and Dole gets it. Speaking before the 
American Council on Education ... she laid out an education 
platform centered on teacher quality. 
</P>
<P>
	She advocated school choice and accountability, cornerstones of  
the GOP vision for education. ... 
</P>
<P>
	If Elizabeth Dole can use these same methods -- solid principles,  
no alienation -- in all other planks of her platform, she could be a 
formidable candidate indeed. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 18  
</P>
<P>
	The Morning News, Florence, S.C., on the Buckle Up, America  
campaign: 
</P>
<P>
	Probably no one is surprised that President Clinton's boundless  
compassion extends to our automobiles. His Buckle Up, America, seat 
belt initiative calls for 85 percent of drivers to be buckled in by 
2000, 90 percent by 2005. After being stuck at 60 percent, seat 
belt usage climbed to 65 percent last Memorial Day and 70 percent 
last Thanksgiving. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, it was not because motorists were getting  
smarter; it was because of stepped-up police enforcement under 
primary and secondary seat belt laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Under widespread secondary laws, police can ticket a driver for  
not wearing a seat belt only after pulling the driver over for 
another offense like speeding. Under primary laws, a driver can be 
pulled over and ticketed solely for not wearing a seat belt. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Safety experts believe all the Americans who will voluntarily  
use seat belts are now doing so. If compassion and common sense 
won't get us to that 90 percent mark, maybe traffic court will. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 19  
</P>
<P>
	The Times-Picayune, New Orleans, La., on curbing alien species:  
</P>
<P>
	Science-fiction fans perked up earlier this month when President  
Clinton signed an executive order that creates an interagency 
Invasive Species Council -- and proposes additional federal spending 
to fight alien entities. 
</P>
<P>
	The order was issued the same week that the Fox network was  
hyping a ``X-Files'' episode that promised to detail an alien 
race's plans to take over the earth. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The ``aliens'' at issue here are terrestrial ones -- plants,  
insects and other animals that escape from their original habitats 
and begin multiplying somewhere else. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials are discussing a variety of ways of  
controlling the spread of unwelcome species. 
</P>
<P>
	One possibility is to give agricultural inspectors more power to  
stop the importation of certain plants and animals. Another is to 
require ships to discharge ballast water before they enter American 
harbors. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately some officials are rather soft on the  
alien-invader issue. Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt thinks 
America can only meet ``modest goals of containment.'' ... 
</P>
<P>
	Whether they come from across the ocean or across the galaxy,  
you have to fight them tooth and nail. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 24  
</P>
<P>
	La Repubblica, Rome, on Kosovo talks:  
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo talks in Rambouillet must not be regarded as a  
failure. Talks are not over, and will resume in a few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	In Rambouillet the Contact Group has obtained a result which  
could be hardly predicted at the beginning of the conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement is an 80-page document which describes in detail  
what sort of autonomy a sovereign State (Yugoslavia) must concede 
to one of its provinces. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither party has signed the agreement. Kosovars want a full  
independence, Serbs oppose the presence of a military force on 
their territory. They both oppose the creation of a police force to 
lead the country's reconciliation. ... 
</P>
<P>
	These are main points to disagree on, and it is still very  
possible that both parties decide to pull back, instead of moving 
forward on the peace path. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace is a long and exhausting process, which disregards all  
predictions. What's important is that, in the end, Europe and the 
United States force Serbs and Kosovars to at least tolerate each 
other without shooting at one another. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 22  
</P>
<P>
	Berliner Morgenpost, on Kurdish protests in Germany:  
</P>
<P>
	One can only hope that the government finally stops having fun  
in Bonn and starts to work. If the arbitrariness of their past 
decisions was worrisome, their relaxed approach to internal 
security should set off alarms. 
</P>
<P>
	That Bonn knew nothing about Ocalan's whereabouts for days is  
bad enough. What's worse is that when he was captured late at 
night, Bonn's civil servants did not dare to wake members of 
Germany's domestic security forces. Anyone who has even a remote 
understanding of the Ocalan/PKK affair would know what havoc 
Ocalan's capture would unleash in Germany, home to 10,000 PKK 
activists. 
</P>
<P>
	This government has to realize that governance is hard work and  
that its citizens' safety comes first. Why do we have a secret 
service that knows nothing about Ocalan, or an internal security 
system that knows nothing about the PKK in Germany? 
</P>
<P>
	Politicians are allowed to sleep, but only after they have done  
some work. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 23  
</P>
<P>
	The Times, London, on India-Pakistan talks:  
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the two-day visit by the Indian Prime Minister to  
Pakistan, the leaders of the world's newest nuclear powers 
committed themselves to extending their moratoriums on nuclear 
testing, notifying each other about ballistic missile tests and 
warning each other of accidental incidents that could lead to war. 
</P>
<P>
	These are the minimum steps necessary for coexistence. They do  
not chart a path for improved relations, promise an end to 50 years 
of mutual hatred or outline how they will tackle the underlying 
cause of tension, the unresolved issue of Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, this first summit in either country for a decade  
does, as the Indian press has enthusiastically remarked, break the 
ice. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 23  
</P>
<P>
	Mainichi Shimbun, Tokyo, on visit of Indian prime minister to  
Pakistan: 
</P>
<P>
	Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee is the first Indian  
prime minister to visit Pakistan in a decade, and under most 
circumstances, any improvement in relations between these two 
countries, which have been strained by the Kashmir problem, ought 
to be welcomed. But both countries could have built up their mutual 
trust and improved their ties without developing nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, high-ranking officials from both countries have  
talked about the need to turn the `balance of terror into something 
more stable' and have made other statements praising this nuclear 
balance. 
</P>
<P>
	How brazen of them to attribute their improved relations to the  
balance of terror! They are simply encouraging other nations in the 
Middle East and Asia that can't wait to get their hands on nuclear 
weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	It is clear that the current Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty  
framework is a far cry from the ideal of total abolition of nuclear 
weapons. Moreover, both the United States and China, which have 
been hounding India and Pakistan to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban 
Treaty, have not ratified the treaty, a fact that India and 
Pakistan have pointed to when trying to justify their own nuclear 
tests. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 23  
</P>
<P>
	Dagens Nyheter, Stockholm, on Nigeria:  
</P>
<P>
	When Abdulsalam Abubakar took over power in Nigeria in June of  
last year, he promised to lead the country to democracy. Free 
elections would take place, a peaceful transition of power would be 
ensured, the 15-year military leadership would be ended. 
</P>
<P>
	There are increasing indications that Abubakar meant what he  
said. Significant skepticism is still justified, the pitfalls are 
still many. Nigeria is a country with great intrinsic tension, the 
economy has been driven to the bottom, society is shot through with 
corruption and Nigerians have heard promises of democracy before. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the steps forward should be noted. Nigeria has  
up to now gone through with elections to local and regional 
assemblies, and on the weekend a parliamentary election was held. 
</P>
<P>
	There are reports of stolen ballot boxes and votebuying, but  
taken as a whole it seems the election went calmly and peacefully. 
... And the successes are a hint of what can be expected when 
Nigeria takes its final step in the transition to civilian rule. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 24  
</P>
<P>
	Sydney (Australia) Morning Herald, on possible deportation of  
Chilean Gen. Augusto Pinochet: 
</P>
<P>
	To mark World Peace Day on Jan. 1 this year, Pope John Paul II  
issued a statement in defense of human rights. ... These words 
appear to make inexplicable the news that the Vatican wrote to the 
British Foreign Office late last year, urging it to block former 
Chilean dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet's extradition to Spain to 
stand trial on human rights abuses. Instead, the Vatican argued, he 
should simply be allowed to go home. ... 
</P>
<P>
	These connections expose a questionable side of the Chilean  
church's role during the dictatorship. But there was another side, 
too. The church was the only significant institution allowed to 
function outside the military's control after 1973. It used its 
independence to defend the persecuted and speak out on their 
behalf. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The Chilean church, in other words, was as divided as Chilean  
society. Evidently, the Vatican feels that both church and society 
are still divided in Chile and that to put Pinochet on trial risks 
tearing the country apart again. Maybe so. But many Chileans are 
now among those who believe greater harm would be done if Pinochet 
is allowed to go free. On Jan. 1, the Pope appeared to have joined 
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
