<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC May Ease Demonstration Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani agreed to a limited  
reopening of the City Hall steps and the surrounding plaza to 
demonstrations and news conferences -- bringing to an end an 
administration policy that all but cut off public access to the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter the city's top lawyer sent to U.S. District Judge  
Harold Baer Jr. on Wednesday, the administration proposed allowing 
up to 50 protesters at a time to gather in the plaza. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar number could speak or protest on the steps if they  
were accompanied by a member of the City Council. 
</P>
<P>
	Baer had ordered the city to come up with reasonable rules of  
access after several groups sued, saying the ban was 
unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear if the judge would accept the  
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``This doesn't go far enough. ... There should be no restriction  
of up to 50 people,'' said Norman Siegel, executive director of the 
New York Civil Liberties Union, which was involved in the 
litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, following the bombing of two U.S. embassies in  
Africa, the city tightened security at City Hall and ordered the 
steps and surrounding area off limits, except for employees and 
people on city business. 
</P>
<P>
	That led to complaints that Giuliani was stifling dissent and  
stomping First Amendment rights -- charges he denies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
