<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raiders Coach Pleads No Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PLEASANTON, Calif. (AP) -- Oakland Raiders coach Jon Gruden was  
fined $750 after pleading no contest to alcohol-related reckless 
driving in a move to avoid drunken-driving charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Gruden was stopped by police in Pleasanton in October after  
leaving a team party. His blood-alcohol level was slightly above 
the legal limit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very pleased the DUI charges have been dropped,'' said  
his attorney, Christine Arguedas. ``I know he's glad to have this 
behind him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The coach was not in court during the brief courthouse hearing  
on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was described as ``borderline'' by prosecutor Ken  
Ryken. 
</P>
<P>
	Had Gruden been convicted of drunken-driving, he could have been  
fined $1,400, spend two days in jail or a work program and complete 
three years' probation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
