<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 11:34:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alien Deportation Defense Limited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court gave the government a big  
victory Wednesday in its 12-year effort to deport Palestinians 
accused of supporting foreign terrorists. Their lawyer says the 
decision limits all aliens' free-speech rights. 
</P>
<P>
	A five-member majority of the nine-member court ruled that  
aliens who are in the United States unlawfully have no right to ask 
federal courts to thwart deportation based on alleged selective 
enforcement of immigration rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians' lawyer, Georgetown law professor David Cole,  
called the decision both sweeping and shocking. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court effectively has ruled that aliens have no First  
Amendment rights; that they can be singled out for deportation for 
engaging in the kinds of First Amendment activities that every 
citizen unquestionably has a right to do,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The First Amendment protects freedom of speech.  
</P>
<P>
	``This remarkable holding ... is, indeed, a sad day for aliens  
in this country,'' Cole said. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Hobson, a lawyer for the conservative Criminal Justice  
Legal Foundation, praised the decision. ``As America faces a 
growing threat of terrorist acts, it has become critically 
important that our government be able to identify and quickly 
remove foreign nationals who encourage such acts from our midst,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the court that ``as a general  
matter ... an alien unlawfully in this country has no 
constitutional right to assert selective enforcement as a defense 
against his deportation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joining him in that conclusion were Chief Justice William H.  
Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy and 
Clarence Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	When granting review last June, the court specifically excised  
that constitutional issue from the case and said it would review 
only whether aliens can get into federal court and pursue 
selective-enforcement claims before their deportation hearings are 
held. 
</P>
<P>
	By an 8-1 vote Wednesday, the justices said federal courts  
cannot handle most claims by aliens before a final judgment is made 
on the deportations sought by immigration officials. By the 
separate 5-4 vote, the court then ruled that selective-enforcement 
claims almost never can be raised to challenge a deportation, no 
matter the timing. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has been trying since 1987 to deport seven Los  
Angeles-area Palestinians and the Kenyan-born wife of one of them. 
Immigration officials say they are members or supporters of the 
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, which the U.S. 
government has labeled a terrorist organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The aliens say they are victims of selective enforcement of U.S.  
immigration laws, and that they are being persecuted for 
fund-raising activities that should be protected by free-speech 
rights. They contend that they only published leaflets seeking 
support and money for the Palestinian group's lawful activities. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest court's decision did not clear the way for the  
aliens' deportations, but removed a significant hurdle the 
government had faced. Immigration and Naturalization Service 
officials now are free to schedule deportation hearings for the 
eight. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Justice David H. Souter voted to let aliens go into federal  
court with a selective-enforcement claim before their deportation 
hearings. Justices John Paul Stevens, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and 
Stephen G. Breyer voted against allowing federal court challenges 
before deportation hearings in such cases, but did not reach the 
constitutional issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress in 1996 enacted an anti-terrorism law that makes it a  
crime for anyone -- citizen or noncitizen -- to provide financial 
support to a foreign organization labeled as terrorist by the 
secretary of state. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals had ruled that the new  
immigration law did not bar a federal trial judge from studying the 
eight aliens' free-speech case. The Supreme Court set aside that 
ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
