caused organizers to suffer ``considerable financial losses,'' 
Mitter said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said 105,000 fans had come out for the first five days of  
competition, 50,000 below expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still believe, though, that we can reach the figure of  
200,000 by the weekend,'' Mitter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many owners of concession stands said they would not cover the  
expensive rent because of the fewer number of spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,600 volunteers have been working up to 16 hours of days  
in their battle against the wintry conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 16:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ryan Minor Set To Sub for Ripken </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Ryan Minor will forever be known as  
the man who replaced Cal Ripken at third base on the night the Iron 
Man finally decided to sit out a game. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a label Minor can live with, if only because he knows he  
still has plenty of time to enhance his list of accomplishments. 
</P>
<P>
	``All winter, people asked me about replacing Cal for that one  
game. That's something that's always going to be there,'' Minor 
said Wednesday. ``Hopefully I'll have an opportunity to play for a 
long time and get a chance to establish myself as not only the guy 
who played that night but someone who played a long time as a very 
productive baseball player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minor, 25, got his first major league start last Sept. 20, when  
Ripken voluntarily ended his consecutive games streak at 2,632 in 
the Orioles' home finale against the New York Yankees. Afterward, 
the baseball Hall of Fame asked Minor for a couple mementos of the 
occasion. 
</P>
<P>
	So, despite playing in only nine major league games, Minor has  
his bat and shoes in Cooperstown. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I never get back to the big leagues, I can always say I  
played that day. But that's not good enough for me,'' Minor said. 
</P>
<P>
	After making an impression on the Orioles during spring training  
last year, Minor spent the summer at Double-A Bowie before being 
called up by the Orioles on Sept. 11. He had 17 homers and 71 RBIs 
with Bowie, then hit .429 in nine games with Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	He impressed the small crowd at Fort Lauderdale Stadium by  
hitting three home runs in three swings during batting practice 
Wednesday, but Minor knows he will almost certainly be back in the 
minors in April. He's not quite ready for the majors yet, and 
Ripken certainly isn't ready to give up job at third base. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I want to do this spring is show them I still want to  
work hard and that I've improved over last year,'' Minor said. 
``You always want to be there right now, but things don't always 
work out that way. My situation is this: There's still a legend 
playing at third base and he will play there as long as he wants 
to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-7 Minor starred in basketball at Oklahoma, but  
decided to make a living playing baseball. There were times last 
season when he wondered whether he made the right decision, 
especially after he got off to a rocky start at Bowie. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was struggling at the plate and I didn't know how to shake  
the slump,'' he said. ``I started thinking some days, `Maybe I 
should play basketball again. Maybe I wasn't cut out to play 
baseball.' That was the first time I ever failed at anything in my 
life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With help from his family and fiance, Minor shook those negative  
thoughts. He now intends to stick with baseball for as long as he's 
got a chance to play in the big leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Minor may not have to wait too much longer.  
</P>
<P>
	``You watch him take ground balls and you watch him hit, and  
then you say, `This is a talent. This is a good athlete,''' manager 
Ray Miller said. ``Because of an injury or whatever, maybe he gets 
here sooner than anyone thinks. And I think he's going to be a 
player.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 16:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
