<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of Feb. 28-March 6:  
</P>
<P>
	65 years ago: Paramount signed Ray Milland, who had yet to star  
in a film, to a long-term contract. Milland had been working in a 
gas station to support himself. 
</P>
<P>
	60 years ago: John Ford's ``Stagecoach'' starred John Wayne. The  
film propelled Wayne to stardom. 
</P>
<P>
	45 years ago: Samuel Goldwyn paid $1 million plus 10 percent of  
the profits at an auction for the film rights to ``Guys and 
Dolls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: The Beatles began work in London on their first  
feature film. 
</P>
<P>
	And Gene Pitney entered the British charts with ``That Girl  
Belongs to Yesterday,'' a cover of a song written by Keith Richard 
and Mick Jagger. 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: ``The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie'' starred  
Oscar-winning Maggie Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	25 years ago: Actress Mia Farrow was on the cover of the first  
issue of People magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Glitter Band released its first single, ``Angel Face,''  
without vocals by lead singer Gary Glitter. 
</P>
<P>
	20 years ago: Sally Field starred in ``Norma Rae.'' She won an  
Oscar for her performance as a real-life Southern textile worker. 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: Michael Jackson won Grammy Awards for record of  
the year and best male rock vocalist for ``Beat It''; and album of 
the year and best pop male vocalist for ``Thriller.'' He won three 
other Grammys and shared an eighth award with Quincy Jones as 
producer of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: Director Martin Scorsese was given the Courage in  
Filmmaking Award by the Los Angeles Film Teachers Association for 
his movie, ``The Last Temptation of Christ.'' The film received 
critical praise but was blasted by some religious groups. 
</P>
<P>
	And Madonna's Pepsi commercial premiered on television. It was  
set to her new single, ``Like a Prayer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Whitney Houston won Grammy Awards for best pop  
female vocalist and record of the year for ``I Will Always Love 
You,'' her 10 million-selling cover of a country song that was 
barely noticed when Dolly Parton wrote it two decades earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	And David Letterman and Helen Hunt were named funniest lead  
performers in series television at the eighth annual American 
Comedy Awards. Meg Ryan and Robin Williams were cited for movies. 
Williams won for ``Mrs. Doubtfire.'' Ryan won for ``Sleepless in 
Seattle.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``It would be fun to do another part before I roll over. I'd  
love to do a picture with Michael Caine or Michael Douglas -- actors 
who have style but aren't pompous about it.'' -- Actress Audrey 
Hepburn. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``The Henry Fonda everybody loves on the screen was not the  
Henry Fonda at the dining room table. Dad could sit on the bus and 
talk to strangers for hours. But for us in the immediate family, he 
never knew how to fill the space. The more we demanded, the further 
he withdrew.'' -- Actor Peter Fonda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 20:12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC's Coles in Bribe Controversy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Olympic organizers were to produce air  
travel vouchers, courtesy notes and lodging reservations on 
Thursday as evidence that Salt Lake boosters lavished favors on an 
Australian member of the International Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Organizing Committee planned to publicly back up a  
finding by an internal ethics panel that Phil Coles took 
expense-paid junkets in 1995, the year Salt Lake City was awarded 
the 2002 Winter Games. Coles has repeatedly claimed the report is 
wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC says it has records that a reservation was made for  
Coles at the posh Goldener Hirsch Inn, a 20-room lodge at the Deer 
Valley ski resort, 26 miles east of Salt Lake City, but that the 
reservation was canceled. The organization was not divulging other 
lodging records on Wednesday. The documents include courtesy notes 
bid officials wrote to Coles on his trips to Salt Lake, SLOC 
spokeswoman Caroline Shaw said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles came under scrutiny in a lengthy report Feb. 9 from an  
ethics committee for the Salt Lake committee that said he treated 
his official IOC visits ``like vacations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report said Salt Lake bid boosters paid for four U.S. visits  
by the families of Coles and another IOC member, Willi Kaltschmitt 
of Guatemala. On one of the visits, Coles was treated to a Super 
Bowl game in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has called the allegations unfounded or inaccurate. In  
particular, he has denied staying at the Deer Valley lodge. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw said the committee was sending copies of all the supporting  
documents, including airline receipts, to Coles and the IOC. The 
material was inadvertently left out of an appendix of the 300-page 
ethics report. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hasn't seen the evidence and we wanted to get it off to  
him,'' said Shaw, who declined to provide copies of the materials. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC members are not supposed to accept gifts worth more than  
$150, and Coles is under investigation by the IOC for possibly 
breaking that rule. Coles stepped down from the organizing 
committee of the 2000 Sydney Games a day after he was named in the 
Salt Lake report. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics report said ``some IOC members treated their site  
visits more like vacations,'' and then discussed the case of the 
Coles and Kaltschmitt families. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Coles and Kaltschmitt families stayed at expensive hotels  
and followed the same recreational itinerary. Two of these trips 
were only four months apart in 1995, including a Super Bowl trip 
that does not appear to have included a visit to Salt Lake City. 
Mr. Welch served as their host at the Super Bowl; the expenses were 
paid as reimbursements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has strongly denounced those allegations and challenged  
Salt Lake officials to produce the documentation. He complained 
that the only thing missing from his media treatment was ``the 
guillotine in the city square.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He repeated his denials Tuesday for The Australian newspaper,  
saying that he and his family spent Christmas 1995 with fellow IOC 
member Jim Eason at Eason's condominium in Deer Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	``We stayed there. We cooked our own meals and did everything  
ourselves, and my records show that,'' Coles said. ``These people 
have got it wrong again.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:43:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Thousands March To Honor Dead Kurds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Watched over by police, thousands of demonstrators  
marched through Berlin today to honor three Kurds killed in 
protests over the capture of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan. 
</P>
<P>
	About 8,500 people followed two silver hearses decorated with  
flowers and carrying the coffins of Sema Alp, 18; Ahmet Acac, 24; 
and Mustafa Kurt, 29, all from Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	They were shot Feb. 17 by Israeli guards while trying to storm  
the Israeli consulate -- reportedly in response to rumors that 
Israeli agents helped Turkey trace Ocalan to Kenya, where he was 
arrested Feb. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Israel denied any involvement in Ocalan's capture, many  
marchers chanted ``Israel -- terrorist'' as they moved through snowy 
central Berlin carrying poster-sized pictures of the three victims 
and of Ocalan. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,500 police were deployed to prevent violence, and  
organizers called on marchers to remain peaceful. At least 44 
people were detained, mostly for displaying symbols of Ocalan's 
Kurdistan Workers Party, which is banned in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, occupants of an apartment house in the heavily  
Turkish neighborhood tossed something onto the passing crowd and a 
few marchers responded by throwing stones and rushing the building. 
But police blocked them from entering and the demonstrators 
eventually rejoined the parade. 
</P>
<P>
	Berlin officials banned all demonstrations last weekend, fearing  
violence, but agreed to the funeral march. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand that many Kurds and friends of Kurds, who can't  
be automatically classified as extremist or prone to violence, wish 
to publicly express their sorrow over the death of their 
countrymen,'' said Berlin's Interior Minister Eckart Werthebach. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies were to be flown to Turkey for burial Thursday. Some  
29 other Kurds involved in the storming of the consulate face 
charges, including causing bodily harm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:43:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Thousands March To Honor Dead Kurds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Watched over by police, thousands of demonstrators  
marched through Berlin today to honor three Kurds killed in 
protests over the capture of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan. 
</P>
<P>
	About 8,500 people followed two silver hearses decorated with  
flowers and carrying the coffins of Sema Alp, 18; Ahmet Acac, 24; 
and Mustafa Kurt, 29, all from Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	They were shot Feb. 17 by Israeli guards while trying to storm  
the Israeli consulate -- reportedly in response to rumors that 
Israeli agents helped Turkey trace Ocalan to Kenya, where he was 
arrested Feb. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Israel denied any involvement in Ocalan's capture, many  
marchers chanted ``Israel -- terrorist'' as they moved through snowy 
central Berlin carrying poster-sized pictures of the three victims 
and of Ocalan. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,500 police were deployed to prevent violence, and  
organizers called on marchers to remain peaceful. At least 44 
people were detained, mostly for displaying symbols of Ocalan's 
Kurdistan Workers Party, which is banned in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, occupants of an apartment house in the heavily  
Turkish neighborhood tossed something onto the passing crowd and a 
few marchers responded by throwing stones and rushing the building. 
But police blocked them from entering and the demonstrators 
eventually rejoined the parade. 
</P>
<P>
	Berlin officials banned all demonstrations last weekend, fearing  
violence, but agreed to the funeral march. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand that many Kurds and friends of Kurds, who can't  
be automatically classified as extremist or prone to violence, wish 
to publicly express their sorrow over the death of their 
countrymen,'' said Berlin's Interior Minister Eckart Werthebach. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies were to be flown to Turkey for burial Thursday. Some  
29 other Kurds involved in the storming of the consulate face 
charges, including causing bodily harm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
