<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wildcats' Turner Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Kentucky point guard Wayne Turner, six  
games shy of a national record for career games played, left 
Wednesday night's game against Vanderbilt briefly after hurting his 
knee. He returned for the second half. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner was hurt with just over eight minutes left in the first  
half. After stealing the ball from Atiba Prater, Turner went in for 
a layup. But he appeared to leave his feet awkwardly and missed the 
shot, landing in a heap under the Kentucky basket. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner, who has played in three straight national title games  
for Kentucky, was helped off the court and went to the locker room 
for treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Although not expected to return, Turner was back on the court  
for the start of the second half, wearing a black band around his 
knee and showing no ill effects. He stripped Prater of the ball 
twice more at the start of the half, converting breakaway layups 
both times to help Kentucky to a 45-26 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner had been honored in Senior Night ceremonies prior to the  
game, his final appearance as a player at Rupp Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	With his appearance against the Commodores, Turner tied former  
teammate Jared Prickett's school record for career games played 
with 143. With six additional games -- Kentucky's regular-season 
finale Sunday at Tennessee and five postseason games -- Turner would 
break Christian Laettner's national record of 148 games, set while 
Laettner was at Duke from 1988 to 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
