<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Bill Targets Debt Collection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government agencies would have to try harder  
to collect billions of dollars in outstanding debt and streamline 
the process for awarding federal grants under separate measures 
approved Wednesday by the House. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill targeting waste and fraud passed 419-1 and was sent to  
the Senate, which would not consider identical legislation last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're bringing the bill back before the American people  
because we believe it is the right thing to do,'' said Rep. Pete 
Sessions, R-Texas, a sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the government is owed $50 billion, excluding taxes.  
</P>
<P>
	The measure would amend existing law to expand the use of  
private collection firms, among other provisions, said Rep. Stephen 
Horn, R-Calif. Federal agencies also would be allowed to keep a 
portion of the delinquent debt recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would permit agencies to bar late payers from being  
eligible for the award or renewal of any federal financial 
assistance, such as a loan, or any federal permits or licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also would be allowed to withhold Social Security  
benefits from recipients who are delinquent in child-support 
payments to a state. 
</P>
<P>
	A second bill, approved 426-0 and sent to the Senate, requires  
agencies that administer similar federal grant programs to 
coordinate and streamline the application, administrative and 
reporting requirements. They also would be required to expand use 
of electronic applications and reporting via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsors say more than 600 such programs exist, many of which  
duplicate or conflict with each other. As examples, they said 11 
agencies administer more than 90 early childhood programs and more 
than $20 billion is spent on 163 job-training programs spread 
across 15 different agencies, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The Government Waste, Fraud and Error Reduction Act is H.R. 436;  
the Federal Financial Assistance Management Improvement Act is H.R. 
409. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
