<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Artists: The Modern Masters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Henri Matisse and Pablo Picasso, who  
were both companions and competitors, helped define modern art. 
</P>
<P>
	And the connection between the two masters becomes strikingly  
clear in ``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry,'' an exhibit 
running at the Kimbell Art Museum through May 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years in the making, it is composed of more than 100  
paintings, sculptures and drawings from collections around the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Picasso and Matisse began their rivalry in 1906, but the exhibit  
tracks them through the later stages of their careers, up to and 
after Matisse's death in 1954. It illustrates how they mimicked 
each other, borrowed from each other, respected each other and 
became best friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``Picasso really looked at Matisse toward the end of his life  
and after, but it's far less known that Matisse looked at Picasso 
very hard, as well,'' said the exhibit's guest curator Yve-Alain 
Bois, professor of modern art at Harvard University. 
</P>
<P>
	Bringing these great works together for the first time ``is like  
a dream come true. I'm so happy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kimbell's director, Timothy Potts, said the works haved been  
studied and exhibited from many angles, but ``there has not before 
been an exhibition that documents the keen and often touching 
rivalry, born of a strong mutual respect, between the two artists 
in the years of their maturity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit begins with works from 1929, when Matisse lacked  
inspiration and was nearly unable to paint, and Picasso was in top 
form. The Spanish artist parodied Matisse's style by painting 
acrobats and dancers, which observers have speculated was an 
attempt to revive his inspiration. 
</P>
<P>
	A few years later, Matisse resumed work. Picasso became  
fascinated with a series of the older French artist's earlier 
sculptures and paintings and produced similar works. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1933, Matisse was ready to respond to Picasso's challenge.  
His ``Daisies'' of 1939 features flowers identical to the primitive 
white daisies in Picasso's ``Basket of Flowers and Pitcher'' of 
1937. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the eeriest sections of the exhibit chronicles works from  
1940-44. The two artists exchanged works, but had minimal direct 
contact with each other because of World War II -- the Nazis 
prohibited Picasso from exhibiting, and Matisse kept a low profile. 
Yet each painted with the other in mind, trying to anticipate his 
next move. 
</P>
<P>
	Matisse and Picasso produced some of their most similar works  
during these years. Matisse's ``The Dream'' in 1940 is nearly a 
carbon copy of Picasso's ``Woman With Yellow Hair'' from nine years 
earlier. Both are side views of blond women leaning to the left and 
resting their heads across folded arms in sleep. Both rely heavily 
on yellow, pink and black. 
</P>
<P>
	Picasso painted ``The Rocking Chair'' in 1943, echoing Matisse's  
``Dancer in Repose'' of a year earlier. Both works feature women 
leaning back in chairs with their legs folded underneath them, and 
both are on backgrounds of undulating tiles. While Matisse's 
faceless dancer wears a blue dress, Picasso's woman has distorted 
facial features and wears an amorphous frock of white, yellow and 
green. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the war ended, the two men reunited. They became closer  
than ever, meeting often and exhibiting together frequently. 
</P>
<P>
	After Picasso painted ``Reclining Nude on Blue Bed'' in 1946,  
Matisse recreated the work almost identically with pencil and paper 
in a sketchbook two years later. Both are on display, side by side. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit concludes with a series of Picasso's paintings after  
Matisse's death in 1954, which Bois says is the most moving part 
for him. Picasso, who had always been terrified by death, was 
devastated by the loss of his friend and rival, and refused to 
answer the phone when he expected it would be a call with news of 
Matisse's death. He didn't even attend Matisse's funeral. 
</P>
<P>
	Picasso, who would outlive Matisse by 19 years, did, however,  
posthumously honor him through art. Reflective of Matisse's 
``Interior With Egyptian Curtains,'' the works use large amounts of 
black to create a contrast with blank white canvas space. Many of 
them picture empty studios, reminiscent of Matisse's large 
interiors. 
</P>
<P>
	The final piece of the exhibit, Picasso's ``Woman in a Rocking  
Chair'' of 1956, fuses both artists' styles. It has Matissean 
bright colors, a faceless woman sitting in a patterned chair and a 
palm tree visible in the background through a window. But Picasso 
adds his signature twisted body parts: The woman has a sharklike 
belly, a phallic arm and neck. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really is able to tell the world, 'I really like  
Matisse,''' Bois said. ``There's no irony, no pity. The way it's 
painted, the way the white of the canvas vibrates, the pattern on 
the back of the rocking chair, all that is pure Matisse.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
