<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Database May Flag Prescriptions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Using a computer database to flag  
prescriptions potentially harmful to older folks can persuade their 
doctors to try an alternative considered safer, according to the 
country's largest pharmacy benefit manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Merck-Medco Managed Care, a subsidiary of pharmaceutical giant  
Merck &AMP; Co., said such changes can help prevent nasty -- and costly 
-- side effects that often result in hospitalizations or dizziness 
causing falls and broken bones. Occasionally, medication errors 
cause death. 
</P>
<P>
	``Among the elderly, 17 percent of hospitalizations are due to a  
medication misadventure,'' and those hospital stays cost as much as 
$10 billion annually, said Dr. Mark Monane, senior director of 
geriatrics for Merck-Medco. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which processes pharmacy claims or directly mails  
medications to one in five Americans, including 10 million over age 
65, in 1995 began its Partners for Healthy Aging program. Its aim 
is to reduce adverse drug reactions caused by prescribing the wrong 
drug or the wrong dosage to senior citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	``The older population is growing rapidly, and it is not unusual  
for older people to be taking several medications,'' Monane said in 
a telephone interview after presenting his study, the largest to 
date, last month at the National Managed Health Care Congress 
meeting on Medicare and Medicaid in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	As people age, he said, the way their body breaks down  
medications and how quickly it excretes them changes, ``so a drug 
that was good for them at 40 no longer is at 60 or 70.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, few pharmacists and physicians have specialized  
training in geriatric medicine, and even pharmacists find it 
difficult to know every possible side effect or interaction a drug 
could have. In addition, an elderly patient's primary doctor may 
not be familiar with drugs prescribed by a specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	So Merck-Medco compiled the best research on geriatric medicine  
and, with a panel of experts, developed a database focusing on 11 
types of medications commonly used by seniors. The system 
automatically alerts a pharmacist at one of the company's 13 mail 
service facilities, and the pharmacist then calls the prescribing 
physician to point out the drug's dangers and suggest alternatives. 
</P>
<P>
	To determine whether the system is preventing patients from  
receiving the potentially dangerous drug, Merck-Medco examined a 
nationwide sample of 23,269 patients whose prescriptions triggered 
a total of 43,007 alerts from April 1996 through March 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In 24 percent of 24,266 cases, where pharmacists were able to  
discuss the prescription with the physician, he or she then opted 
for a different medication, another dosage or some other strategy, 
such as a dietary change. Most of the alerts and medication changes 
involved antidepressants such as Elavil and tranquilizers such as 
Valium. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something that obviously there's a need for,'' said  
Michael Donio of the People's Medical Society in Allentown, Pa. 
``We know that when drug manufacturers set a dosage ... it doesn't 
take into account that someone might be 78 or down to 100 pounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some individual and chain pharmacies have such warning systems,  
but at others the computer system merely determines the price, 
prints the label and tracks inventory. 
</P>
<P>
	Hedy Cohen, vice president of nursing at the Institute for Safe  
Medication Practices in Warminster, Pa., said raw data from a 
survey it is conducting among U.S. hospital pharmacies so far 
shows, ``the hospitals have not been able to adequately adapt 
warnings into their computer systems.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 07:05:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capitol Architect Has Many Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The first architect of the Capitol was  
literally the architect of the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	But Alan Hantman, the 10th architect of the Capitol, is  
variously a human resource administrator, threat analyst, union 
negotiator, crisis manager and bean counter. He oversees a $250 
million budget and 2,000 employees, balancing the competing goals 
of openness and security in ``the people's house'' and other 
buildings on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	``The early architects were brought on to do architecture,'' he  
says not at all wistfully. Nowadays, Hantman's job tests diplomacy 
as much as artistry. 
</P>
<P>
	Appointed by President Clinton two years ago, the former chief  
architect at New York's Rockefeller Center has been sued over 
employment grievances that predated his term, accused of moving too 
slowly on a new building and blamed for maintenance problems at 
existing buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials howled at a report finding the architect's  
office has the highest occupational injury rate in the federal 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional hearings were called to explore a report of fire  
hazards in the Capitol and other buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	After two Capitol police officers were shot to death last year,  
members of Congress complained that Hantman was taking too long 
with plans for a new, security-oriented visitors center. ``Build 
it, already,'' demanded an editorial in last week's Roll Call 
newspaper that criticized Hantman by name. 
</P>
<P>
	All the while, Hantman has pressed for more money to patch leaks  
in the Capitol dome and improve computer wiring to hundreds of 
congressional offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk about office politics: Hantman, 56, practices architecture  
at ground zero of American political life. As architect of the U.S. 
Capitol -- a federal position dating to the work of the first 
architect, William Thornton, in the 18th century -- he must answer 
to congressional committees as well as his own aesthetic standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Others might call it a giant headache. Hantman calls the job ``a  
magnificent challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of folks who don't understand that everything  
can't be done immediately,'' Hantman said. ``You have to request 
money from the federal budget a year in advance, do the design 
work, go through federal procurement processes -- you can't just 
snap your fingers and get things done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hantman, who earns $125,900 annually, moved to Washington from  
Teaneck, N.J., in 1997 after serving as vice president for planning 
and architecture at the Rockefeller Center. The American Institute 
of Architects recommended him for the federal post, Congress 
endorsed him and Clinton selected him for a 10-year term. 
</P>
<P>
	The architect has authority over the Capitol, eight  
congressional office buildings, the Library of Congress buildings, 
the Supreme Court building and other structures, including the 
Capitol's own power plant, plus murals, statues and grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The architect reports to a Senate committee, a House commission  
on matters related to House office buildings and the House speaker 
on questions related to the House side of the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	With so many responsibilities and so many masters, the architect  
of the Capitol has to wear many hats. Little wonder that Hantman's 
predecessor, George White, was not just an architect but an 
engineer, lawyer and graduate of Harvard Business School. 
</P>
<P>
	White, now semi-retired after 25 years on Capitol Hill, said  
controversy is a fact of life there. 
</P>
<P>
	``On most things Congress does, there's not unanimous  
agreement,'' he said. ``So even if you have Congress pass a law by 
60 to 40, you have 40 percent of the people that don't like it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Hantman, the most recent flare-up concerned fire safety.  
</P>
<P>
	The House inspector general reported in December that the  
Capitol and five House office buildings failed virtually every test 
of fire preparedness, with inaudible fire alarms, inadequate escape 
routes and inoperative fire-suppression sprinklers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hantman released a statement calling talk of fire traps  
``journalistic hyperbole.'' He said his office is hard at work on 
fire safety upgrades. 
</P>
<P>
	White said his successor has done good work in a tough job.  
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the attacks are a little -- I won't say exaggerated --  
but emphasis is put on them that makes them newsworthy,'' White 
said. In 25 years on the Hill, he has learned to choose his words 
diplomatically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
