<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veteran Sprinter Wins 60m Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS (AP) -- Veteran sprinter Merlene Ottey wiped out  
competition -- and any talk of retirement -- as she breezed to 
victory in the 60 meters Wednesday at the European Athletics 
Association Indoor Invitational. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jamaican, who hopes to run in the 2000 Sydney Olympics just  
before her 40th birthday, clocked 7.05 seconds and said she could 
have done better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did try,'' Ottey told reporters. ``Everybody said this was a  
fast track but its wasn't. I'm not going to pressure myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ottey sailed past Greece's Katerina Thanou, who finished in 7.16  
seconds, and Nigeria's Glory Alozie who was third with 7.20. 
</P>
<P>
	A surprise win by Nigeria's Sunday Emmanuel in the men's 60  
meters with 6.56 seconds left American Brian Lewis in third place 
at 6.59. Greece's Giorgos Theodoridis, tied the American's time but 
took second place after winning his heat. 
</P>
<P>
	Andres Diaz of Spain set a European indoor record in the 1,500  
meters with a time of 3:33.32, ahead of Kenyans William Tanumi, who 
was second with 3:35.17 and third-placed David Lelei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
