<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teamsters' Supervision Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans questioned Wednesday whether  
federal supervision of the Teamsters has done enough to prevent 
corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	A 17-month investigation of the union's 1996 presidential race  
revealed abuse of power, financial mismanagement and a ``profound 
lack of accountability by past Teamsters leaders,'' said Rep. Peter 
Hoekstra, R-Mich., who chairs the House Education and the Workforce 
Committee's oversight and investigations panel that conducted the 
probe. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings raise questions about whether the 1989 court order  
that put the International Brotherhood of Teamsters union under the 
supervision of the federal government is working well enough in 
preventing corruption not related to organized crime, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite sharp criticism from Democrats, the subcommittee agreed  
by voice vote to approve a report summing up the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal monitors overturned former Teamsters President Ron  
Carey's re-election in 1996 over James P. Hoffa after investigators 
found that his campaign had improperly benefited from donations the 
union made to third-party political organizations. In a new 
election last December, Hoffa won the office. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats contended the subcommittee abused its investigatory  
powers, wasted taxpayer money, implied guilt where none was proven 
and turned up nothing that hasn't already been revealed by other 
government probes. 
</P>
<P>
	The report ``contains nothing new,'' said Rep. Tim Roemer of  
Indiana, the panel's top Democrat. ``This subcommittee spent over a 
million dollars to discover that it could not find any illegal 
activity that was not already being redressed. I question the use 
of this much money to conduct an entirely duplicative effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than raise questions about the effectiveness of current  
law, the investigation showed the system is working as intended, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Roemer also accused the GOP majority of turning its  
investigation ``into a partisan effort,'' and ridiculed sections 
that questioned whether union leaders were considering the rank and 
file's best interests when they gave millions of union dollars 
almost exclusively to Democratic candidates and parties. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors in New York have been looking into the union  
since 1997, but Hoekstra said he believed their investigation has 
been ``stalled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since three Carey campaign consultants have pleaded guilty in  
September 1997, federal prosecutors have ``managed to obtain only 
guilty pleas from two minor players, and the indictment of the 
(union's) former political director,'' Hoekstra said. ``Not one 
individual has gone to trial.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
