<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Awards Ex-Mazda Worker $4.4M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A federal jury has ordered Mazda Motor Corp. to pay  
$4.4 million to a former employee who said her boss repeatedly 
touched her, chased her around the office and hit her with a 
telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabriella Arango also said Masaki Nakashima of the Japanese  
automaker's office in Miami said: ``If you obey what I say, you'll 
get anything you want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda denied the harassment allegations and will fight the Feb.  
17 jury award. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's Miami attorney, Courtney Wilson, said Mazda will  
ask the court next week to cut the award to about $1.3 million. 
That would bring it into line with federal civil rights law, which 
has stricter limits on compensatory damages, Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arango's attorneys filed suit under Title VII of the Civil  
Rights Act -- a federal anti-bias law -- and under state laws that 
allow higher damage awards. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury awarded Arango $3 million for emotional pain and  
suffering and $1 million for Mazda's ``negligent supervision and or 
retention'' of Nakashima. The award also included $300,000 for 
future wages and benefits, $90,400 in lost wages, $20,000 in future 
medical, psychological or psychiatric expenses and $300 in past 
medical costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Arango says she told the company in writing and on the telephone  
about the harassment. The company says it did receive complaints 
from both Arango and Nakashima, but they were about personality and 
office conflicts, not harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	Arango worked at Mazda's Miami office for five years before  
being fired in June 1996. She started as a secretary and rose to a 
marketing position in which she helped to arrange auto shows in 
Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda says Arango had shouting matches with Nakashima and didn't  
get along with another employees in the small office. Three times, 
Wilson said, the company sent a human-resources executive in to try 
to resolve the problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Arango said she was sometimes forced to lock herself in the  
office bathroom to get away from her boss. He occasionally ordered 
her to sit in a corner because she'd been ``a bad girl,'' Arango 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
