<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 12:56:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Bright Lights' Dims on Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's not just the memory of his ex-wife that  
haunts the young hero of ``Bright Lights Big City,'' a new musical 
at off-Broadway's New York Theater Workshop. 
</P>
<P>
	Also hovering over his shoulder is the ghost of the theater  
company's last big musical success, ``Rent,'' a show that moved to 
Broadway and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Such travels do not appear to be in the cards for ``Bright  
Lights Big City,'' a bland reworking of Jay McInerney's trenchant 
tale of urban angst and flight from responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Comparisons are inevitable -- and unfortunate. Both shows have  
pop rock scores and the same director, Michael Greif. Yet ``Rent'' 
has a spirit and drive, two qualities missing from ``Bright Lights 
Big City,'' which, incidentally has dropped the comma from the 
book's title. 
</P>
<P>
	The musical is the handiwork of Scottish composer Paul Scott  
Goodman, who wrote the book, music and lyrics. It's a virtually 
sung-through piece that has most of the performers playing several 
roles. 
</P>
<P>
	In its translation from page to stage, Goodman has diluted  
McInerney's cutting and often hilarious observations on living and 
working in New York. He opts instead for a sentimentality that 
works against the cold, calculating environment of a story set 
firmly in the excesses of the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodman's tunes, even with an occasional arresting melody,  
eventually grind the audience down, making the second act seem much 
longer than it should be. And his lyrics tend to the obvious, 
pushing for a rhyme even when he doesn't have a reason. 
</P>
<P>
	McInerney's novel, published in 1984, perfectly captured a time  
and place. Its hero, unnamed but called Jamie in this stage 
version, works as a fact checker for a magazine called Gotham, a 
thinly disguised stand-in for The New Yorker. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie is a glum, self-centered guy who finds refuge in drugs and  
drink. He has reasons. Wife Amanda, a high-fashion model, went to 
Paris several months ago and then phoned to say she was not coming 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie's job at the magazine is in jeopardy, even as he struggles  
to fact check a complicated article by its restaurant critic. And 
then there is his mother's death, a fact Jamie refuses to face as 
the first anniversary of her demise approaches. 
</P>
<P>
	There is one major difference in structure from the book, which  
was written in the second person. To keep that distance and to 
smooth some rocky transitions, Goodman has injected himself into 
the show as a sort of all-purpose narrator. It is a jarring 
conceit. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Wilson, a fine singer who was an impressive Billy  
Bigelow in the national tour of the most recent ``Carousel,'' works 
very hard. Yet he is stuck with an impossible role, particularly as 
Goodman has written it. This Jamie has very little humor, 
preferring to wallow in self-pity and sentiment much more than the 
character in the book did. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other strong voices in the show. Annmarie Milazzo, who  
also did the show's vocal arrangements, stands out as the mother. 
So does Napiera Daniele Groves as Amanda, the unfaithful wife, and 
Jerry Dixon as Jamie's party-loving, coke-sniffing friend. 
</P>
<P>
	The utilitarian, all-purpose stage design of a catwalk and  
sliding panels is symptomatic of the musical as a whole. It may 
allow Greif to move the show more quickly from scene to scene, but 
it unroots the musical from its very specific environment. This 
``Bright Lights Big City'' is as generic as its nondescript 
setting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 08:46:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Speaker: GOP May Exceed Spend Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert today left  
open the possibility that Republicans would exceed spending limits 
in the nation's balanced-budget accord as they fashion a spending 
plan for the next fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not saying we're going to bust them or not bust them,'' he  
told reporters. He said previous spending commitments include 
forward funding that would require as much as $17 billion above 
levels permitted under the caps. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending caps, which were put in place two years ago to hold  
domestic spending in check, constitute one of numerous thorny 
issues that Republicans are grappling with as they labor over their 
budget for the fiscal year that begins next Oct. 1. Tax cuts are 
another, as is the use of the federal surplus and its impact on 
Social Security and Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert, meeting with reporters in a ceremonial office just off  
the House floor, said a meeting Tuesday that President Clinton 
called with congressional leaders was a ``good first step.'' In his 
job less than two months, Hastert added, ``Sometimes you feel like 
a new kid on the block.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had ``made a point to the president that we need to  
work together on a real plan to save Social Security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois Republican renewed his pledge to work in a  
bipartisan fashion on the legislative agenda. A former deputy whip, 
Hastert said, ``If you don't have the votes you can't pass 
something,'' and if the president won't back it, legislation can't 
become law. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hold a narrow, six-seat majority in the House, the  
slimmest in decades, complicating GOP efforts to fashion an agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	On the budget, Republicans have accepted Clinton's call for  
setting aside 62 percent of anticipated surpluses to help secure 
Social Security. Clinton wants another 15 percent set aside for 
Medicare, but Hastert, as have other Republicans, declined to 
endorse that. He noted that a bipartisan Medicare commission is 
expected to issue a report shortly, and said that should first be 
reviewed. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's meeting at the White House was the first since  
Clinton's acquittal at a Senate impeachment trial, and also the 
first prolonged meeting with the bipartisan congressional 
leadership since July 15, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no substantive, specific progress on any of the issues  
they will address this year. But with each side eager to 
demonstrate that it has moved beyond impeachment to policy making, 
each said they were willing to try working through their 
differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president knows full well that what the American people  
expect from their political leaders in Washington is to work 
together and get their business done,'' White House spokesman Joe 
Lockhart said. ``And that's exactly what today's meeting was 
about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sounding almost the identical theme was Senate Majority Leader  
Trent Lott, R-Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to work together, hopefully across the party lines  
in the Congress and with the administration, to do what the 
American people expect of us,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and House Hastert, however, declined several opportunities  
to say they trust Clinton. When the impeachment trial ended Feb. 12 
with Clinton's acquittal in the Senate on perjury and obstruction 
of justice charges in the Monica Lewinsky affair, Lott questioned 
whether he could trust the president. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue is, will we work together to get our job done? That  
is the real issue,'' Lott said Tuesday in parrying the question. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Hastert: ``We are starting to work to put together ideas,  
and that's the first step.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The issue also came up inside the 80-minute meeting, said aides  
from both parties who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	They said Lott and House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas,  
told Clinton that overhauling Social Security and Medicare are so 
politically sensitive that Republicans would first have to believe 
Democrats would not use them against the GOP in next year's 
elections. Democrats have often accused Republican candidates of 
endangering the two programs, which serve tens of millions of 
elderly voters. 
</P>
<P>
	In a hint of disputes to come, Clinton insisted that lawmakers  
reserve 77 percent of anticipated future budget surpluses to 
bolster Social Security and Medicare, participants said. 
Republicans have broadly agreed to dedicate 62 percent of the 
projected surpluses for Social Security, but want to use much or 
most of the rest for tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	When Clinton said 23 percent of the surpluses could be used for  
tax cuts, education and other domestic initiatives, Lott said that 
would squeeze the GOP's tax cut plans too tightly, said aides from 
both parties. Overall, surpluses are projected to total about $2.5 
trillion over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic leaders at the meeting indicated they backed  
Clinton's insistence on setting aside 77 percent of the surplus for 
Social Security and Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, it is the threshold decision,'' said House Minority  
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
