<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Unions Target Tobacco Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Add another name to the growing list of  
adversaries going after the tobacco industry in court: unions suing 
for nearly $2 billion to recover the medical costs of treating 
smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	Already taxed heavily, sued vigorously and targeted by President  
Clinton, Big Tobacco is facing this new opponent this week in U.S. 
District Court in Akron, Ohio -- the first of more than a dozen 
similar lawsuits by health plans to reach trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming two weeks after a $51.5 million verdict against Philip  
Morris in California and several months after a $246 billion 
settlement with the 50 states, it raises the question: How much can 
the industry take before the gouges start leaving permanent damage? 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody suggests the industry is ready to crumble. While  
cigarette company stocks are way down, the two biggest players, 
Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco are involved in far more businesses 
than just tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't call it Big Tobacco for nothing. It's not on its  
knees yet,'' said Carl Bogus, a product-liability expert at Roger 
Williams University in Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
	The 100 Ohio labor union trust funds that joined the  
class-action suit join a litigant list that is spreading beyond 
smokers to health plans that are seeking seeking damages for 
smoking's costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The union lawsuit, filed in May 1997, claims tobacco companies  
advertised heavily using Joe Camel and the Marlboro Man because 
they knew such images influence less-educated blue-collar workers 
in particular. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing illegal about that, the companies contend; it's simply  
advertising. However, one defendant, the Liggett Group Inc., an 
industry maverick, settled and plans to cooperate with the unions' 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiffs against cigarette manufacturers have run the gamut:  
flight attendants; the nations of Guatemala, Panama and Bolivia; a 
pediatrician with emphysema who is the lead plaintiff in a $200 
billion class-action suit filed on behalf of all Florida smokers. 
And now Clinton has threatened to sue tobacco companies to recover 
smoking-related Medicare expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``This industry is under siege,'' Paul Patton, the governor of  
the tobacco-growing state of Kentucky, said last month. ``There's a 
limit to what this product can bear, and we're coming close to that 
limit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Union plans like Ohio's -- and any suits on behalf of Medicare --  
form another ring of plaintiffs. One name for them: ``secondhand 
entities,'' organizations or governments that claim financial 
damage rather than individuals who are sick. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine union cases have been thrown out. In one last year, a  
federal judge in Florida -- calling the claims too far away from the 
people actually damaged -- said the tobacco industry had become 
``the whipping boy of American political discourse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These claims are too remote. They've been a resounding  
failure,'' said Steven Rissman, assistant general counsel for 
Philip Morris. 
</P>
<P>
	``Akron is certainly an aberration,'' he said. ``We're not  
concerned about floodgates. This one has slipped through the 
cracks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, a victory for the Ohio plaintiffs ``would clearly  
break new ground,'' said Richard Daynard, chairman of the 
anti-cigarette Tobacco Products Liability Project at Northeastern 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Because last year's settlement with the state attorneys general  
immunized the companies from individual states' lawsuits, he said, 
many believed the industry ``would be basically home free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's now apparent that they're far from it,'' Daynard said.  
``If they settle this, they're in very bad shape,'' because 
``presumably you have other health-care providers in the wings. If 
they lose, they're in even worse shape because they've proven to 
people there's no reason these suits can't win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Helping future litigants are industry documents made public in  
earlier cases, including in-house research dating to the 1950s that 
links smoking and cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawsuits alleging financial rather than personal damage are more  
about economics than justice, says Uwe Reinhardt, a Princeton 
University health economist. He calls the union suits ``a 
profitable roulette game'' but says it won't last. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point, the judicial system is probably going to put a  
stop to it. Because they'll say they're killing an industry,'' 
Reinhardt said. 

</P>
<P>
	stock quotes graf, additional analysts  


</P>
<P>
	Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst with Solomon Smith Barney,  
acknowledges the high-profile cases -- and the internal documents 
they've dislodged -- can depress value and scare investors. But he's 
hardly staying away. 
</P>
<P>
	``Big settlements encourage the plaintiff bar to seek further  
ways of profiting from the tobacco pot,'' Feldman said. ``But at 
the end of the day, they face an industry that's well-funded and 
substantially has the law on its side.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
