<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Apologizes for Questions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Wednesday he was to  
blame for reporters asking questions that seem out of place at his 
news conferences with foreign leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really my fault because I don't let them ask me enough  
questions on other occasions, so I'm forcing them to use this 
opportunity to pepper me,'' Clinton said at a news conference with 
President Jerry Rawlings of Ghana. 
</P>
<P>
	``I apologize,'' the president said. Predictably, most of the  
questions from the U.S. press dealt with subjects other than 
Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has not held a full-scale news conference since last  
July 3 when he took questions from reporters in Hong Kong. The only 
other opportunities to ask questions have been the abbreviated news 
conferences with foreign leaders, except for quick photo 
opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings said he had been warned in advance that American  
reporters would probably ask about domestic matters. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton would do  
another limited press conference with Italian Prime Minister 
Massimo D'Alema next week. After that, Clinton plans to hold a 
full-scale news conference in the middle of March and then set a 
target of meeting with reporters about every six weeks to two 
months, Lockhart said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:33:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stabler To Call Alabama Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- Ken Stabler, who returned to his alma  
mater last season as the color analyst for Alabama football games, 
signed a three-year contract extension Wednesday with The Crimson 
Tide Network. 
</P>
<P>
	Stabler, an All-American quarterback for the Tide known as ``The  
Snake,'' debuted last season on the network. He originally signed 
on for just one season, partly because he wasn't sure how well he'd 
do. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was more than I expected, more fun than I expected,'' he  
said. ``It was a pleasure to be back, to be at Alabama football 
games and be able to bring my children. It was a very positive 
experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stabler is teamed in the booth with Eli Gold, who is entering  
his 11th year as Alabama's play-by-play man. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials announced Stabler's contract extension during a  
press conference, but declined to say beforehand what the 
announcement would be. That led fans across the state to speculate 
Gold might be leaving Alabama to concentrate on his NASCAR 
broadcasting career. 
</P>
<P>
	Butch Henry, general manager of Crimson Tide Sports Marketing,  
said that was a sign of the popularity of Alabama's broadcasting 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We probably have the two most recognized voices in the South  
on our radio network,'' Henry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stabler said he agreed to the contract extension because of how  
much he enjoyed being part of Alabama football again, as well as 
his belief the program is headed in a positive direction. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no patience in this business, but you have to be with  
this Alabama team because time is in Alabama's favor,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stabler said he learned quickly how to balance his love for  
Alabama and his need for impartiality in the radio booth. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold said his counterpart adapted well.  
</P>
<P>
	``We just clicked immediately,'' he said. ``He's taken snaps and  
I've never been under center before, so he can add something that I 
am not able to.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
