<DOCNO> APW19990224.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 23:53:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Government Questions Microsoft Tape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Another videotape presentation by Microsoft  
Corp. was questioned by the government during the antitrust trial 
against the computer software company. 
</P>
<P>
	The video was intended to demonstrate the apparent ease computer  
makers have in customizing their desktop, the first screen a user 
sees after turning on a computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft played the video in court before the government  
cross-examined the software maker's latest witness, Joachim Kempin. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department attorney David Boies immediately questioned a  
segment of the tape that featured the startup sequence for Compaq 
Computer Corp., the world's largest computer maker. 
</P>
<P>
	Boies got Kempin, the senior Microsoft executive responsible for  
the company's business deals with computer makers, to admit that 
two videotapes were made. The tape played in court Wednesday 
featured on the desktop an icon for Netscape's Internet browser, 
which competes with the one made by Microsoft. Kempin acknowledged, 
however, that the tape originally prepared for court and filmed 
last November lacked a Netscape icon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It basically shows how quick this industry changes,'' Kempin  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boies said the omission illustrated the impact on computer  
makers of Microsoft's restrictive contract licenses. The government 
has alleged those restrictions illegally hurt Netscape, Microsoft's 
primary Internet software rival. 
</P>
<P>
	In his written testimony submitted to court earlier in the week,  
Kempin has argued that Microsoft allows computer makers to install 
whatever rival software they choose and to make it easily 
accessible for consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Boies was to resume his cross-examination of Kempin today.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Wednesday, a Microsoft engineer rejected as ``completely  
unfounded'' claims that it tried to sabotage multimedia software 
made by Apple Computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Engstrom also argued forcefully that proposals to cooperate  
with Apple on Internet video and audio software stemmed from 
Microsoft's desire to help frustrated customers, not from a desire 
to eliminate competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleges that Microsoft encouraged Apple to adopt  
its own proprietary technologies, which would have required Apple's 
Quicktime customers also to use Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple executive Avadis Tevanian testified previously in the  
trial that Microsoft designed parts of Windows to bypass Quicktime 
and created misleading error messages. 
</P>
<P>
	But Engstrom said Microsoft blamed the problem on Apple's own  
faulty software, an explanation verified by some independent 
experts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was amazing to me that Dr. Tevanian could come in here and  
make the claim that we sabotage Quicktime,'' Engstrom said. ``At 
Microsoft, our company would never do anything like that.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
