<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PBS Studies Paul Robeson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The towering figure of Paul Robeson cast an  
oddly diminished shadow for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Robeson's rich, rumbling bass sounded as deep as the  
Mississippi. It was ``the voice of the century,'' as one biographer 
put it. 
</P>
<P>
	He was an all-American football player, Phi Beta Kappa scholar,  
attorney, author and stage and film actor. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also an activist whose commitment to black and radical  
causes earned him the enmity of his own country and turned him from 
one of the most widely admired Americans into one of the most 
despised. 
</P>
<P>
	The late Robeson's punishment was historical obscurity. Any  
scant attention inevitably was marked by willful misinterpretation, 
according to his son. 
</P>
<P>
	``The prescribed spin was, 'Too bad he got so political, strayed  
away from the interests of his own people. Great artist, 
well-meaning guy, but tragic victim of his own political 
misjudgment,' '' said Paul Robeson Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 100th anniversary of the artist's birth last year  
brought new attention to Robeson that continues with a PBS 
documentary as complex as the man himself -- and, at two hours, 
barely long enough to contain this remarkable life. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paul Robeson: Here I Stand,'' debuting 9 p.m. EST Wednesday as  
part of WNET's ``American Masters'' series, paints a respectful but 
honest picture of Robeson, whose brilliance and passion made him 
seem superhuman, but who had his share of human frailties. 
</P>
<P>
	The documentary allows us to meet him firsthand -- through news  
clips, movies and songs -- and through his friends and detractors, 
and to weigh him for ourselves. Rare film and documents amassed by 
Robeson Jr. add invaluable depth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the first film that gives Paul Robeson the floor to be  
himself, without any filter. Here he comes on civil rights, on 
communism -- warts and all by the way,'' his son said in an 
interview. ``There are people on camera who are highly critical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most compelling, of course, is the charismatic Robeson himself,  
whether singing what became his trademark song, ``Ol' Man River,'' 
explaining his acclaimed interpretation of the title role in 
``Othello'' or staking out his philosophical turf. 
</P>
<P>
	``The artist has to fight for freedom or slavery. I have made my  
choice,'' he said in a 1937 speech. It was a bruising battle that 
claimed payment in money, freedom and health, but which engaged him 
nearly until his death in 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	The grandson of a slave and son of a minister, Robeson was born  
April 9,1898, in Princeton, N.J. He won an academic scholarship to 
Rutgers University and lettered in baseball, basketball, football 
and track. 
</P>
<P>
	After graduating from Columbia Law School and running headfirst  
into the limitations imposed on a black attorney, he began to 
explore his creative gifts. He was encouraged by his ambitious and 
devoted wife, writer-anthropologist Eslanda Goode. 
</P>
<P>
	Robeson became, in short order, a cultural sensation.  
</P>
<P>
	He earned acclaim for his stage work, including Eugene O'Neill's  
``The Emperor Jones,'' while his recordings of popular and folk 
songs, spirituals and classical music made him the equivalent of a 
modern-day superstar. 
</P>
<P>
	His movies often abused his dignity and talent, turning him into  
a cartoon African or a naif, and drawing criticism from black 
leaders like Marcus Garvey. There were exceptions, largely the 
so-called ``race'' films made for black theaters and black 
audiences, in which Robeson portrayed intelligent, realistic and 
dynamic characters. Robeson's charm shone through both the good and 
the bad films, and he became a box-office hit. 
</P>
<P>
	He made a splash abroad with concert tours, musicals and plays,  
including his critically praised ``Othello.'' And he gained a 
global political view as he was exposed to the labor struggles of 
Welsh miners and colonial oppression in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1934 trip to the Soviet Union proved most influential.  
</P>
<P>
	``Here, for the first time, I am treated as a full human being.  
I walk in full human dignity. You cannot imagine what that means to 
me as a Negro,'' Robeson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus began a lifelong support of communism and socialism that  
made him the target of protests as well as investigations by the 
U.S. Department of State and the FBI. The protests and probes 
effectively buried his career for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``To the white elite, he was 'our special Negro.' They were  
outraged that 'our Negro would turn against us,' '' said his son. 
</P>
<P>
	Robeson never was officially a Communist Party member, but  
believed communist nations offered a bulwark against race and class 
oppression, said Robeson Jr. He continued to support the Soviet 
Union even after Stalin's murderous tyranny was exposed. 
</P>
<P>
	``That decision was based on the question of what's the main  
enemy: the right wing of the United States or Stalinism, communism, 
Maoism. ... One can argue whether my father was right or wrong, but 
it was a conscious choice in the interest of the progressive world, 
of African Americans,'' Robeson Jr. said. 
</P>
<P>
	His political battles were made fiercer by his race.  
</P>
<P>
	``The real Robeson image is the most powerful African American  
male image of this century, and perhaps ever. .... And this is what 
the establishment found threatening. The politics was significant 
but secondary,'' said his son. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had he been white ..., it wouldn't have had the same power,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	However Robeson's politics are judged, his extraordinary  
personal journey is moving. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tote that barge, lift that bale; get a little drunk and you  
land in jail. .... I'm tired of livin' and scared of dyin','' are 
the ``Ol' Man River'' lyrics Robeson sang early in his career. But 
the tune changed when he did, the documentary shows us. 
</P>
<P>
	``You show a little grit and you land in jail,'' an older  
Robeson sang in concert, altering the original Oscar Hammerstein 
lyrics to express something of his own defiance. ``I keep laughing 
instead of crying. I must keep fighting until I'm dying. And ol' 
man river, he just keeps rolling along.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	YEARWOOD'S ACTING JAG: Country singer Trisha Yearwood, who  
played a Navy Reserve pathologist last year on ``JAG,'' makes a 
return visit to the CBS drama. This time, her character is called 
in to help investigate the murder of a child at a Navy base. The 
episode airs 8 p.m. Tuesday, March 2. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
</P>
</TEXT>
