<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Senators Consider Punishing IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) - Senators are looking at ways to financially  
punish the International Olympic Committee if the organization does 
not clean up its operations, a congressional aide says. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, and Commerce Committee Chairman John  
McCain, R-Ariz., expect to decide Thursday whether to hold hearings 
next week on possible sanctions against the IOC, according to 
Trevor McCabe, Stevens' legislative director. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens is looking at several options to force change in the  
aftermath of the corruption scandal surrounding the 2002 games in 
Salt Lake City, McCabe said. The options under consideration 
include taking away or limiting the IOC's tax-exempt status and the 
revenue it earns from broadcast rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a move could cripple the committee, since the United States  
is home to nine of the IOC's 11 worldwide sponsors. Each pays $40 
million to $50 million every four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
