<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Low Demand Sinks Grains, Soybeans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures fell sharply on the  
Chicago Board of Trade Wednesday amid indications that demand will 
continue to weaken. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans tumbled to new lows amid reports that buyers of palm  
oil and Brazilian soybean oil had canceled shipments. That was taken 
as an indication that demand for U.S. products will not pick up some 
time. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybean prices already had been pummeled to their lowest levels  
in more than 12 years on expectations that demand from Asia region 
will remain low throughout 1999. Big crops anticipated in Argentina 
and Brazil also affected prices. 
</P>
<P>
        Even more vexing to traders are forecasts for American farmers  
to plant record soybean acreage this spring. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat sank as market participants eyed extremely low prices  
offered by competing French exporters for an Egyptian purchase. That 
reinforced views that prices must go much lower to stimulate demand 
for exports. 
</P>
<P>
        Corn futures retreated in sympathy with the plunging wheat  
and soybean prices. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for March delivery fell 7 1/2 cents to $2.44 1/4 a bushel;  
March oats fell 6 1/4 cents to $2.08 3/4 a bushel; March oats fell 
1 3/4 cents to $1.00 1/2 a bushel; March soybeans fell 16 1/2 cents 
to $4.57 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Meat and livestock futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
        April live cattle fell .17 cent to 67.45 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle fell .40 cent to 73.57 cents a pound; April lean hogs 
fell 1.83 cents to 43.42 cents a pound; March pork bellies fell 1.95 
cents to 50.85 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
