<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 15:41:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ghana Seeks U.S. Aid for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he supports a  
move by the Ghanaian parliament to extend dual citizenship to black 
American descendants of African slaves. ``I thought it was a rather 
clever idea myself,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	During a news conference with Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings,  
Clinton said he would not block black Americans who seek to accept 
Ghana's offer. Americans can hold dual citizenship with some other 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Ghana does this, it certainly won't hurt in trying to get  
more Americans interested in Ghana, going to Ghana and contributing 
to Ghana's future,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings said his parliament soon would vote on a bill to grant  
dual citizenship to black Americans, as a gesture of good will over 
its past as a slavery port. He seemed irked when a reporter asked 
why his country was making the gesture. 
</P>
<P>
	``My continent is the mother not of all continents, but humanity  
today,'' Rawlings said. ``There is no reason why I would deny my 
fellow black African the right to enjoy the same citizenship that I 
enjoy as an African.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two leaders spoke after a midday meeting at the White House.  
Clinton emerged from that session saying he would support 
``whatever necessary force'' is required to ensure peace in Congo, 
which has been seized for months by civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all have a stake in the resolution of the problems of the  
Congo,'' Clinton said. ``I was hoping we could avoid the bad year 
we've had in the Congo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's remarks came a day after U.N. Secretary-General Kofi  
Annan said U.N. peacekeepers probably will be necessary in the 
former Zaire if a settlement is negotiated there. But Annan said 
American troops likely would not be needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Clinton did not commit to the idea of offering soldiers,  
but said the United States would take part, if asked, in ``an 
internationally recognized'' peacekeeping effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly would do my best to support whatever necessary  
force to ensure the peace,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A rebel coalition of ethnic Tutsis, disaffected Congolese  
soldiers and opposition politicians took up arms in August, 
accusing President Laurent Kabila of misrule, corruption and sowing 
ethnic hatred. Backed with troops and armor from Rwanda and Uganda, 
they have advanced through Congo's eastern half, fighting 
government troops and Kabila's allies from Zimbabwe, Angola, 
Namibia and Chad. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings said assistance from the United Nations would be  
helpful in peacekeeping, and he would be willing to lend troops to 
such a force. But he said other countries may have to contribute as 
well, because African nations are struggling under the burden of 
responding to conflict in other parts of the continent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our resources are stretched to the very limit,'' Rawlings  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the United States has provided more than $75  
million in humanitarian assistance to refugees and victims of 
violence in Africa over the past 18 months. He said he would like 
to increase the U.S. contribution to ECOMOG, a West African 
peacekeeping force, ``and I hope Congress will support my proposal 
to do so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton praised the trade relationship of ``mutual respect and  
mutual benefit'' that is developing between the United States and 
Ghana, and cheered Ghana's participation in peacekeeping efforts in 
Lebanon and Bosnia, as well as the all-African forces now working 
in Liberia and Sierra Leone. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited the words of the black intellectual W.E.B. DuBois, who  
maintained dual U.S.-Ghanaian citizenship, that ``the difference 
between 100 and 1,000 years is less than you might think'' when 
change that once seemed painfully slow finally begins to occur. 
</P>
<P>
	``Something else of far-reaching importance is happening in  
Africa,'' Clinton said. ``You are doing so much of what must be 
done. It will live eternally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Rawlings said even though poverty and war are on the decline  
in Africa, they cannot be completely erased without a greater 
commitment from the United States. Many struggling African nations 
need debt relief, as well as help in resolving ``tragic strife'' 
that hinders U.S. business investment in Africa, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am here, on behalf of my fellow citizens from this  
continent, to invite America to join us to put an end to hunger, 
deprivation, starvation and conflict on my continent,'' Rawlings 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton greeted Rawlings in freezing temperatures on the White  
House South Lawn. Rawlings, bundled in a heavy gray overcoat, joked 
that he appreciated the cold -- especially after Clinton received 
``the treat of the African sauna bath'' when he arrived in Ghana in 
102-degree weather in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to get the feel of the air-conditioned atmosphere of  
the American weather,'' Rawlings said. ``So, ladies and gentlemen, 
here I am with you, and enjoying your weather, even if you don't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was the first American president ever to visit Ghana. He  
was met by 500,000 people there, the largest crowd of his 
presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
