<DOCNO> APW19990224.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 15:41:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ghana Seeks U.S. Aid for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he supports a  
move by the Ghanaian parliament to extend dual citizenship to black 
American descendants of African slaves. ``I thought it was a rather 
clever idea myself,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	During a news conference with Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings,  
Clinton said he would not block black Americans who seek to accept 
Ghana's offer. Americans can hold dual citizenship with some other 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Ghana does this, it certainly won't hurt in trying to get  
more Americans interested in Ghana, going to Ghana and contributing 
to Ghana's future,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings said his parliament soon would vote on a bill to grant  
dual citizenship to black Americans, as a gesture of good will over 
its past as a slavery port. He seemed irked when a reporter asked 
why his country was making the gesture. 
</P>
<P>
	``My continent is the mother not of all continents, but humanity  
today,'' Rawlings said. ``There is no reason why I would deny my 
fellow black African the right to enjoy the same citizenship that I 
enjoy as an African.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two leaders spoke after a midday meeting at the White House.  
Clinton emerged from that session saying he would support 
``whatever necessary force'' is required to ensure peace in Congo, 
which has been seized for months by civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all have a stake in the resolution of the problems of the  
