<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Competitors Subpoenaed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge is allowing Microsoft to  
subpoena documents from America Online, Netscape and Sun 
Microsystems about AOL's proposed purchase of Netscape for $4.2 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said Tuesday the papers are ``extremely relevant'' to  
its defense of government antitrust charges. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is trying the  
antitrust case and has expressed unease about AOL's pending 
purchase of Netscape, agreed to Microsoft's demands for the 
documents. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the AOL-Netscape deal announced last November, Sun  
would distribute Netscape's business-level software in exchange for 
AOL's purchase of Sun's powerful computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said it is seeking documents related to the purchase  
and its potential impact on online services, Internet software, 
computer operating systems and other technology platforms and Web 
sites called ``portals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	America Online, the world's largest Internet provider with more  
than 16 million subscribers, would become owner of two of the four 
most popular such ``portal'' sites on the Web if the sale is 
approved by federal regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would become owner of Netscape's popular Internet  
browser software, which competes with Microsoft's Internet Explorer 
browser. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun developed a new technology, called ``Java'' that lets  
consumers run software on a variety of operating systems other than 
Microsoft's Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	``This deal is designed to really reshuffle and reshape this  
industry,'' Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said. ``This deal 
shows that competition in the marketplace will take care of 
consumers far better than government interference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to America Online and Netscape weren't immediately  
returned late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun spokeswoman Lisa Poulson acknowledged receiving Microsoft's  
subpoena demanding e-mails about Sun's contract with AOL and about 
whether the agreement might have an impact on the antitrust trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Poulson also said Microsoft wanted copies of any communications  
about the AOL deal among Sun and Apple Computer Inc., IBM Corp., 
Novell Inc. and Oracle Corp. She said Sun was negotiating the 
release of documents with Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Jackson said in December that AOL's purchase of Netscape  
``might be a very significant change in the playing field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has argued that the AOL-Netscape deal, announced after  
start of its antitrust trial, illustrates the viability of a 
computer industry that does not need government intervention to 
ensure competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a Microsoft executive acknowledged in trial testimony  
Tuesday that his company offered Netscape ``several inducements'' 
to stop competing in the Internet browser market. 
</P>
<P>
	``We offered them several inducements if they adopted several of  
our technologies,'' testified Dan Rosen, Microsoft's general 
manager for new technology. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rosen has denied repeatedly that his company ever threatened  
Netscape. He said Microsoft simply tried to provide technological 
tools that would have allowed Netscape to make its Web browser 
compatible with Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen is a key witness because he was present at a disputed June  
21, 1995 meeting between Netscape and Microsoft officials. The 
government claims Microsoft offered to split the Internet browser 
market with Netscape. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
