<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons To Chair Women's World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President and Mrs. Clinton accepted Wednesday  
an invitation to serve as honorary co-chairpersons of this summer's 
Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tremendous honor for the Women's World Cup and the  
organizing committee,'' said Donna de Varona, the tournament's 
chairperson. ``The President and First Lady have always championed 
efforts to increase opportunities for women, and the Women's World 
Cup is truly a breakthrough event for women's athletics. We look 
forward to having the First Family share in the largest female 
sporting event in history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament, in which the United States is one of the  
favorites, begins June 19 at East Rutherford, N.J., and concludes 
July 10 at Pasadena, Calif. The third Women's World Cup -- the 
United States won in 1991 and Norway is the defending champion -- 
will feature 16 teams. 
</P>
<P>
	It is not known if the Clintons will attend any games.  
</P>
<P>
	Other venues for the games are Foxboro (Mass.) Stadium; Soldier  
Field in Chicago; Portland (Ore.) Civic Stadium; Spartan Stadium in 
San Jose and Stanford Stadium, both in California; and Jack Kent 
Cooke Stadium in Landover, Md. 
</P>
</TEXT>
