<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies, Walker at Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- As Larry Walker launched batting practice  
pitches into the parking lot behind right field, his agent Pat 
Rooney and Colorado Rockies general manager Bob Gebhard observed 
from above. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney and Gebhard sat together in a tower at the Rockies spring  
training complex for about 45 minutes Wednesday, swapping baseball 
stories from the past and trying to clear up Walker's plans for the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, who will make $5.075 million this year, is seeking a  
contract extension before the Rockies open the season April 4 in 
Monterrey, Mexico. Judging from lagging negotiations, it could come 
down to the wire. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no indication where it's going to go,'' Rooney said.  
``There's not much happening right now. There's nothing to 
report.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before receiving a fax from Walker's agents earlier this week,  
Rockies owner Jerry McMorris said he had no counterproposal to use 
as a starting point for negotiating. 
</P>
<P>
	The fax said Walker was ``not necessarily'' seeking an  
eight-year deal worth $15 million per season. Reports have said 
Walker last month turned down a four-year offer worth about $11 
million per year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney said the two sides ``have an understanding'' how  
negotiations are going to progress and another face-to-face visit 
could come next week. Neither he nor Gebhard would elaborate on 
what the next move will be. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney, a former minor-league player, and Gebhard have a  
baseball history together. Gebhard traded him from the Montreal 
Expos to the New York Yankees for Tim Burke in the early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
 *NOTES:* Gebhard also met with Todd Helton's agent. Helton,  
runner-up for NL Rookie of the Year in 1998, made $190,000 last 
season and has said he is willing to sign a multi-year contract, if 
he thinks it's a fair offer. Gebhard would only say that he and 
Mike Moye ``visited'' and will talk again. ... The Rockies have 
signed pitchers Lariel Gonzalez and Mike Kusiewicz to one-year 
contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
