<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Turner Creates New Cable Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Ted Turner is fixin' some Southern-fried  
television. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner Broadcasting System announced Wednesday it plans to  
launch Turner South, a cable network that hopes to keep y'all 
coming back to watch country music, Southern lifestyle shows, and 
all-time stars of pro wrestling such as Jesse ``the Governor'' 
Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner South will debut in the fall as the first regional cable  
entertainment network, targeting six southeastern states. Analysts 
said the regional network seems a good way to offer a programming 
identity among the melange of channels, and should attract 
advertisers looking to target their messages. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's definitely still a Southern identity that exceeds what  
I've found in the Northeast, Midwest and West Coast,'' said Tom 
Agan, a Massachusetts native and retail consultant for Kurt Salmon 
Associates in Atlanta. ``There's a certain set of values and images 
and stories that only Southerners get.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Reagan Wilson, director of the University of  
Mississippi's Center for the Study of Southern Culture, said a 
network whose initial lineup will include shows such as ``World 
Championship Wrestling Classics'' might give rise to stereotypes. 
But it underlines the growing popularity that traditionally 
Southern forms of culture -- such as wrestling, country music and 
stock-car racing -- have gained nationwide, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Burke, president of the TBS Superstation, will head Turner  
South for parent Time Warner Inc., where Turner now serves as vice 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Burke announced the new network before a breakfast of cheese  
grits, biscuits and peach cobbler. He said the strategy of 
celebrating Southerners' strong regional identity should prove both 
popular and profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be movies packaged as ``Kudzu Theater-Movies that  
Grow on You,'' a play on the ever-spreading vine. They won't all be 
Southern-based, but among titles planned are old favorites such as 
``Cool Hand Luke'' and recent movies such as ``Places in the 
Heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burke said that not only do Southern-themed shows such as ``Andy  
Griffith'' play particularly well in the region, some movies such 
as ``Dumb and Dumber,'' a slapstick comedy without a regional link, 
have gotten unusually high regional ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner South will also carry games of the TBS-owned pro sports  
franchises -- baseball's Atlanta Braves, basketball's Hawks, and 
hockey's Thrashers -- not being carried on other networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Among original shows planned are country music from Nashville's  
Bluebird Cafe; a weekly series developed with Southern Living 
magazine; ``The College Show'' using tapes submitted from regional 
campus stations; and ``WCW Classics'' with favorites including the 
current Minnesota governor who wrestled as Jesse ``The Body'' 
Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	Burke said the company will step up talks with other cable  
operators to secure space and expects its long regional ties to 
help. The network could reach up 6 million homes in Georgia, 
Alabama, Mississippi, Tennessee, North Carolina and South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner, the nation's largest cable operator, already has  
strong holdings in the Carolinas and Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner South joins the wide-ranging lineup of TV networks  
created by Turner, including CNN, TNT and Cartoon Network, and 
represents something of a return to his TV roots. In 1976, Turner 
made Atlanta-based TBS into the first ``superstation'' by using 
satellite to reach homes around the nation, featuring Braves and 
Hawks games and old TV series such as ``Andy Griffith.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 12:26:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Witnesses Say King Still a Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- The white supremacist convicted of the  
dragging death of a black man acted up in jail and is capable of 
more violence, prosecution witnesses testified today. A defense 
expert found mitigating qualities in the man. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury that found John William King guilty Tuesday of  
kidnapping and murdering James Byrd Jr. last June now must decide 
whether to sentence King to death. 
</P>
<P>
	As the punishment phase continued today, Dr. Edward Gripon told  
jurors that experts tend to base the predictions of future violence 
on two things. ``One is past history because it's the best way to 
predict,'' he said. ``The second is the sheer magnitude of some 
offense. Some are so extreme and so dramatic they remove all doubt 
what a person is capable of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gripon, who reviewed King's writings and photographs of his  
racist tattoos, saying the tattoos provided insight into the 
defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Part of the reason was to make a statement, to make himself  
someone feared,'' Gripon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also testifying today was a Jasper County investigator, Joe  
Sterling, who said King threatened to assault him when King refused 
to leave the jail for a January court appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he took it as a threat, Sterling replied: ``Yes, sir, I  
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A county jailer, Kenneth Primrose, testified how on that same  
day, King picked up a television in his cell and smashed it. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was transferred to another cell, deputies conducted a  
search, finding a homemade knife made from a radio antenna and a 
noose made from electrical cord. The discovery prompted officials 
to put King on a suicide watch, said Primrose, who was the final 
state witness during the punishment phase. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys, who contend a life prison term would be  
appropriate for King, called a psychologist as their first witness. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter Quijano, a former chief psychologist for the Texas prison  
system and now in private practice, said King's lack of drug 
history and the fact that he'd used no weapons during previous 
crimes contributed to his conclusion that a life term would fit 
King. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that in Texas, a life term means at least 40 years in  
prison before an inmate is eligible for parole. 
</P>
<P>
	``He would be about 64 when released,'' Quijano said. ``The  
probability of people at age 64 committing violence is very low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If King is sentenced to death, he would become the only white  
among 452 Texas inmates to be awaiting death for killing a black 
person. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say that Byrd, 49, was picked up by the suspects  
June 7 as he walked home after a party. He was then savagely beaten 
and chained to the truck. 
</P>
<P>
	A pathologist testified Byrd was alive and in excruciating pain  
as he was dragged along a bumpy county road, held fast by the 
24 1/2-foot logging chain. For part of the way, Byrd tried to prop 
himself up on his elbows to protect his head. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, it was a black man who delivered the news that could  
send King to death row. 
</P>
<P>
	King leaned forward slightly, drawing near to one of his  
attorneys apparently in hopes of avoiding the aim of a photographer 
as the jurors filed into the courtroom to announce the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	The only black juror, who had been elected foreman of the  
12-member panel, gave the papers with the jury vote to the bailiff, 
who handed them to state District Judge Joe Bob Golden. 
</P>
<P>
	``We the jury find the defendant guilty of the offense of  
capital murder,'' Golden read. 
</P>
<P>
	Some spectators applauded, and Byrd's family broke into tears.  
``I am relieved,'' said Stella Brumley, Byrd's sister. ``That's all 
we wanted, was justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two other white men, Shawn Berry, 24, and Lawrence Brewer, 31,  
await trial in the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I know is that there's one down and two to go,'' said Ross  
Byrd, the victim's son. 
</P>
<P>
	A few blocks from the courthouse, Craig Johnson, owner of the  
World of Sounds music store, later suggested a punishment for King: 
``He needs to go the same way that man did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The slaying thrust Jasper into a national spotlight that many in  
this racially mixed east Texas timber town of 8,000 said was 
unfair. Members of the Ku Klux Klan and New Black Panthers came to 
demonstrate outside the courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton said nationwide expressions of outrage over  
Byrd's death ``demonstrate that an act of evil like this is not 
what our country is all about.'' He added: ``Our work for racial 
reconciliation and an end to all crimes of hatred in this country 
will go on.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
