<DOCNO> APW19990224.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 18:52:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> APSE Honors Wilstein, Dahlberg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDONDO BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- National sports writer Steve  
Wilstein won his 17th writing award for breaking the news of Mark 
McGwire's use of a muscle supplement, and Tim Dahlberg was honored 
for enterprise reporting on Mike Tyson in Associated Press Sports 
Editors awards for AP staffers. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball writer Ronald Blum won the Grimsley award for overall  
body of work; Nancy Armour of Chicago won for best feature story; 
and Steve Wine of Miami was chosen sports writer of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Photographer Ed Reinke of Louisville won three out of four  
awards, including best overall portfolio, and Cliff Schiappa of 
Kansas City was honored for best action photo. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilstein, based in San Francisco, won story of the year honors  
for reporting that McGwire used androstenedione, a 
testosterone-producing pill that is legal in baseball but banned in 
the NFL, Olympics and the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Andro was the story in the story of the year,'' said Rick  
Vacek, assistant managing editor for sports at the Kansas City Star 
and one of seven judges on the contest selection panel. 
</P>
<P>
	``The story sent shockwaves across the country,'' said another  
judge, James D. Walker, executive sports editor of the Oakland 
Press in Pontiac, Mich. ``He owned that story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was gutsy to write what he saw,'' said Tracy Dodds, sports  
editor of the Austin-American Statesman. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Wilstein's 17th APSE writing award since 1988.  
</P>
<P>
	NBA writer Chris Sheridan was runner-up in story of the year  
honors for his account of the NBA Finals, particularly Michael 
Jordan's finale in Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
	``He made you feel as though you were there and he did a very  
good job of capturing the last moments of Jordan's last shot,'' 
Dodds said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball writer Ben Walker was third for his account of the New  
York Yankees' World Series victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Dahlberg, a sports writer based in Las Vegas, won the enterprise  
award for detailing how Tyson spent money almost as quickly as he 
earned it. He also was runner-up for the Grimsley award. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was really very wonderful reporting. The detail was  
incredible. He even talked to jewelers and car salesmen to see what 
kind of line of credit was extended to Tyson,'' Dodds said. 
</P>
<P>
	Runner-up was Milwaukee's Arnie Stapleton for a story on Reggie  
White and whether the University of Tennessee asked for a donation 
to retire his Green Bay Packers jersey; there was no third place. 
</P>
<P>
	Blum's Grimsley award-winning entries included exclusives on  
trades, such as Kevin Brown's $100 million contract with the Los 
Angeles Dodgers, and a profile of Yankees owner George 
Steinbrenner. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was superb reporting, often making complex numbers easy to  
follow,'' Walker said. ``On Steinbrenner, he did a nice job of 
putting him in perspective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dahlberg was runner-up for stories that included the final round  
of the Masters and Tyson regaining his license to box; Columnist 
Jim Litke was third for stories that included golfer Casey Martin 
and Jordan's Game 6 against Utah in the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Armour won the feature category for the story of how gymnast  
Dominique Moceanu's life was ripped apart by money, ambition and 
family differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the best story that I read about Moceanu all year,''  
Vacek said. ``It really kept me reading. There were a lot of voices 
-- she talked to a lot of people. She painted the images well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Runner-up was Philadelphia's Ken Berger for a heartbreaking tale  
of boxing great Jimmy Bivins' fight for his life in Cleveland; 
Jacksonville's Eddie Pells was third for a story on Auburn hero 
Terry Beasley's concussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wine was selected sports writer of the year for a range of work  
that included an interview with golfer Gene Sarazen looking back on 
the history he made, and the grudge still harbored by 1972 Super 
Bowl MVP Jake Scott against former Miami Dolphins coach Don Shula. 
</P>
<P>
	Wine also won the award in 1995.  
</P>
<P>
	Runner-up was Robert Baum of Phoenix and third place went to Tim  
Whitmire of Lexington, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
	Reinke won the Thomas V. diLustro Award for body of work for a  
portfolio that included high school basketball, horse racing, the 
Winter Olympics and McGwire's home run chase. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Hulshizer of Trenton, N.J., and Thomas Kienzle of Stuttgart,  
Germany, tied for second place. Eric Draper of Albuquerque, N.M., 
and Eric Gay of Dallas took honorable mentions. 
</P>
<P>
	Reinke won the feature category for his photo of McGwire and a  
home plate umpire following the flight of a home run ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Second place went to Amy Sancetta of New York for her picture of  
retired football players Mike Singletary and Tommy McDonald bumping 
bellies during an impromptu celebration when they were inducted 
into the Pro Football Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Third place went to Milwaukee's Morry Gash for his photo of a  
perplexed Jenny Chuasiriporn eyeing her bunker shot that landed 
short of the green in the U.S. Women's Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Honorable mentions went to Boston's Charles Krupa and to  
Hulshizer. 
</P>
<P>
	Reinke won the picture story category for McGwire's home run  
chase. 
</P>
<P>
	Second place went to Hulshizer for a picture story on the first  
all-women's boxing card to be presented in New Jersey. No other 
awards were given in this category. 
</P>
<P>
	Schiappa won in the action category for his photo of a defender  
grabbing a ball carrier's face mask in an NFL game. 
</P>
<P>
	Second place went to Washington's Doug Mills for his photo of a  
player smashing another player in the face with his stick during a 
hockey game. 
</P>
<P>
	Third place went to Dave Martin of Montgomery, Ala., for a photo  
of several players trying to call time out during a scramble for a 
ball in a college basketball game. 
</P>
<P>
	Honorable mentions went to Mike Conroy of Indianapolis and Mark  
Terrill of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Other judges for the writing contest included John Cherwa,  
associate managing editor for sports at the Chicago Tribune, Robert 
Mashburn, deputy sports editor of the Atlanta Journal and 
Constitution; Scott Monserud, sports editor of the Fort Worth 
Star-Telegram; and Jack Genung, sports editor of the Home News and 
Tribune of East Brunswick, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Photo judges were Dodds, Vacek and Bob Yates, sports editor of  
the Dallas Morning News. 
</P>
<P>
	The judging took place at the group's winter meeting in Redondo  
Beach, Calif. Winners will be honored at the APSE's annual awards 
banquet in June in Phoenix. 
</P>
</TEXT>
