<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yanks' Irabu Out of the Spotlight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Hideki Irabu is happy just to fit in these  
days. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of commotion going on around me last year.  
It's a lot nicer this year,'' Irabu said Wednesday. ``I know what I 
need to know here at spring training. It is more relaxed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attending his second spring training, Irabu appears better  
prepared both physically and mentally. He seemed relaxed and 
confident Wednesday as he threw strikes during his first 
batting-practice session of the spring against live hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to believe as the time passes, you're going to get  
into it a little bit more,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``It 
has to be more difficult coming from another country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu, no longer facing a daily barrage from the American and  
Japanese reporters, spent time Wednesday talking about conditioning 
and pitching with five-time Cy Young Award winner Roger Clemens, 
obtained from Toronto last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roger said when he was young, he learned a lot from Nolan  
Ryan,'' Irabu said through interpreter George Rose. ``It will help 
that I can be able to learn from his experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irabu, starting the third season of a $12.8 million, four-year  
contract, has been criticized in the past by the Yankees for lack 
of conditioning and lackadaisical efforts. He was 6-3 with a 2.91 
ERA in the first half of last season, then tailed off and went 7-6 
with a 5.21 ERA in the second half. He didn't throw a pitch in the 
postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it was more normal than 1997, when his rights were  
assigned to San Diego by his Japanese team, he held out and forced 
a trade to New York, then made his major league debut following the 
All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think last year, starting out with camp, having the full  
season and being with these guys -- I feel like I fit in now,'' 
Irabu said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other starters, Orlando Hernandez and David Cone, also threw  
10 minutes of batting practice Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to make my hitters look good,'' Cone joked. ``It went  
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, scheduled to throw batting practice for the first time  
Friday, will not pitch in the exhibition opening home-and-home 
series against the Blue Jays on March 4 and 5. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to avoid that since it just happened last week,'' Torre  
said. ``Not anything other than the media thing, And again, he 
hasn't been in camp as long as everybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre did not rule out Clemens starting the March 6 home game  
against Boston. Clemens, who has been working out before and after 
the regular spring training sessions, will continue his long toss 
regiment Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far, so good,'' Clemens said. ``I'm getting with the  
program.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Seventeen-year old Dominican right-hander Ricardo  
Aramboles, who underwent major elbow surgery last October, remains 
on target to pitch extended spring training games in April and 
possibly join Class-A Greensboro by early May. ... Welcome to the 
majors Alfonso Soriano. After hitting two consecutive home runs off 
Hernandez fastballs, the highly-regarded infield prospect was 
frozen by a sharp breaking ball. ... Venezuelan outfielder Jackson 
Melian, who received a $1.6 million signing bonus as a 16-year old 
in 1996, will continue his climb through the minors and start at 
Class-A Tampa this season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
