<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock 
Market, and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
 *American Greetings Corp. fell 11 3/16 to 23 7/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company said revenues in fiscal year 2000 will be reduced by  
$100 million by a ``productivity initiative'' designed to get cards 
to market faster. The company expects to report fiscal 1999 
earnings of $2.60 to $2.70 a share, and fiscal 2000 earnings of $2 
to $2.10 a share, excluding restructuring charges. Analysts had 
expected earnings of $2.97 for fiscal year 2000, which begins March 
1, 1999, and $2.65 for fiscal 1999. 

</P>
<P>
 *Boeing Co. fell 1 3/4 to 35 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	An internal Boeing study, confirmed by the company, found that  
one-quarter of the $13 billion the company is investing in its 
product lines will produce no meaningful returns. 

</P>
<P>
 *Delta Air Lines Inc. rose 3 1/16 to 61.    	
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. named Delta its ``Focus 1'' stock of the  
week, saying it was attractively priced and that new management 
could produce annual earnings of $8 to $10 a share. Merrill raised 
its 1999 earnings-per-share estimate to $6.70 from $6.50. The 
company earned $6.87 a diluted share in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
 *Biomatrix rose 8 15/16 to 64 3/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	Better-than-expected earnings and recent federal approval to  
ship an arthritis product helped drive the shares higher, the 
company said. BancBoston Robertson Stephens substantially raised 
its earnings estimates and stock-price target for the company. On 
Tuesday, Biomatrix reported fourth-quarter earnings of 61 cents a 
share, outstripping analysts' consensus forecast of 50 cents per 
share. 

</P>
<P>
 *Capital Re Corp. rose 2 to 16 13/16.    	
</P>
<P>
	Fourth-quarter operating profits were 69 cents per share, easily  
topping analysts' estimate of 59 cents. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Ciena rose 2 5/8 to 27 1/4.    	
</P>
<P>
	BancBoston Robertson Stephens upgraded the stock to buy from  
long-term attractive, saying the company should benefit from 
``robust and accellerating'' demand for fiber-optic systems. 

</P>
<P>
 *Advanced Fibre Communications Inc. fell 1 7/16 to 8 1/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	NationsBanc Montgomery Securities Inc. cut its first-quarter  
earnings projection because of concerns that slower orders from 
Mexico, Venezuela and China are keeping international business 
below targets. 

</P>
<P>
 *Xylan Corp. rose 3 5/8 to 25 5/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	Nutmeg Securities analyst Andy Schopick, said the company has  
``performed beautifully'' on a promise to deliver double-digit 
revenue growth in every quarter of the year. 

</P>
<P>
 *Twinlab fell 2 1/2 to 7.    	
</P>
<P>
	The vitamin maker restated first-, second- and third-quarter  
results for 1998, effectively reducing numbers. Twinlab also said a 
slowdown in nutritional supplements sales hurt fiscal 1998 
earnings. 

</P>
<P>
 *S3 Inc. rose 1 5/32 to 9 5/32.    	
</P>
<P>
	The company revealed that a top-five personal-computer  
manufacturer, which it declined to identify, has adopted its S3's 
Savage4 graphics chip. 

</P>
</TEXT>
