<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 09:26:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Virtual Life: Ronin DVD Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- DVD movie disks are nothing new. Online  
celebrity chats are even older news. Put them together though, 
adding loads of behind-the-scenes goodies, and you have a 
breakthrough. 
</P>
<P>
	Bypassing the limitations of Internet bandwidth constraints,  
which prevent quality real-time video feeds, MGM Studios is packing 
its regular DVD disk of the 1998 John Frankenheimer movie ``Ronin'' 
with extensive additional footage, most of it accessible only via 
the World Wide Web. 
</P>
<P>
	The novel concept will allow film fans and high-tech buffs to  
take part live in an online event March 14 with Frankenheimer where 
he'll reveal moviemaking secrets, display storyboard sketches, 
on-set still photos and much more, accompanied by high-resolution 
video clips showing what he's talking about. 
</P>
<P>
	Starring Robert De Niro and Jean Reno, the ``R'' rated film set  
in France is a thriller about international intelligence agents and 
mercenaries who lost their government jobs at the end of the Cold 
War. It features some of the best car chase sequences ever filmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankenheimer, 69, is a living film legend whose credits include  
``The Manchurian Candidate,'' ``Seven Days in May,'' ``Grand Prix'' 
and ``The Birdman of Alcatraz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The multimedia marriage of Internet and DVD intrigues  
Frankenheimer, who admits that although he has witnessed tremendous 
technical development during his life and is highly computer 
literate, he remains mystified by the rapid growth of the World 
Wide Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankenheimer says he would never have imagined it 10 years ago.  
``I'm not a great visionary,'' he said in a telephone interview 
from Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	In the ``Ronin'' online event, everything but the video will be  
transmitted over the Internet, while the clips come from the movie 
disk to make playback quick and high-quality regardless of modem 
speed. The clips, encoded so they can be seen only by logging onto 
MGM's Web site, feature additional footage not used in the film's 
final edit, behind-the-scenes clips showing how stunts were staged, 
and a few blooper outtakes. 
</P>
<P>
	A basic description doesn't do it justice. The end result is a  
rich, visually stunning presentation that feels like a multimedia 
film school lecture hall, with the professor, Frankenheimer, 
discussing moviemaking problems and solutions while the film clips 
show the results. 
</P>
<P>
	He's excited by the idea of sharing his work with thousands via  
the Internet, while recognizing that revealing too many secrets 
behind movie wizardry can spoil the audience's fun. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a way it does bother me, because in another generation and  
another time I don't think anybody really cared that they shot 
`Casablanca' on the Warner Bros. backlot,'' he said. ``It was just 
a good movie, and it was an illusion. Sometimes it's better not to 
know how it was done, and just enjoy the magic of it. But that's 
not the age we live in anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For people who can't resist seeing how directors perform movie  
magic but can't take part in the live online event, and for those 
who want to see it again and again, the presentation will be 
recorded and saved on an Internet server so disk owners can view it 
anytime 
</P>
<P>
	And all the online access extras included on the disk that hit  
store shelves Feb. 23 are free. 
</P>
<P>
	The disk, which can be used to play the film normally on DVD  
players and computers equipped with DVD drives, has a list price of 
about $25, no more than regular DVD movie disks and less than many 
that, like ``Ronin,'' also offer some extra footage and director 
commentary that buyers don't need an Internet hookup to view. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a first-time effort for MGM that has wide-reaching  
implications since the studio holds video distribution rights to 
more than 6,700 other films dating back decades, many of which are 
classics that would be prime candidates for similar combined 
online-DVD efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The format also could extend far beyond movie marketing, with  
alternative possible applications including other performing arts, 
sports, education, business, even military training. 
</P>
<P>
	Uniting so many forms of media in a single presentation presents  
a tantalizing look at the future of multimedia. It may also 
frighten traditionalists who don't like the Internet and home 
entertainment centers making inroads into a domain still dominated 
by the old-fashioned movie theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankenheimer, however, has no fears about cinema ever becoming  
obsolete. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that's ever going to happen. I think there's  
something about the group experience, going OUT to see a movie, 
that's a part of our existence,'' he said. ``And it would be a 
shame if it did, leaving just total isolation. That whole group 
experience, I think that's special.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 13:56:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lou Henson on Threshold of 700 Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) -- There are times when Lou Henson wonders  
why he can't shake his craving for competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every now and then I think, this is ridiculous,'' Henson said.  
``I'm putting too much pressure on myself. It's not like I'm trying 
to save my job. I'm not 35. I don't have four kids (to support).'' 
</P>
<P>
	What Henson, who turned 67 last month, still has is the ability  
to turn out winning basketball teams. He's done it so well for 36 
years that he's one win away from becoming only the 13th coach in 
Division I to win 700 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Now in his second stint at New Mexico State, Henson's career  
record is at 699-353 going into Thursday's game against Utah State 
in Las Cruces. 
</P>
<P>
	The impending 700th win has become a major topic in New Mexico.  
House and Senate members in the state Legislature gave Henson a 
standing ovation when he visited this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Henson's road to 700 started 44 years ago with his graduation  
from New Mexico State. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was trying to decide whether I wanted to coach or go into  
administration,'' Henson said. ``I was thinking about getting a 
high school job somewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Henson was a high school coach in the late '50s and early '60s.  
But the legacy of the dapper-dressing, success-driven and congenial 
Henson is what he accomplished since then at Hardin-Simmons, 
Illinois and New Mexico State. 
</P>
<P>
	He came out of retirement last season to take over the program  
at his alma mater. NMSU athletic director Jim Paul replaced Neil 
McCarthy with Henson, who agreed to be the interim coach for a 
salary of $1 a month. After the season, Henson signed a four-year 
contract that will run through his 70th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Once back, Henson realized he had lost none of his love for  
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even after 40 some years, you put pressure on yourself to do  
it. It doesn't change,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona State coach Rob Evans, who played for Henson at New  
Mexico State in the late '60s and was his assistant for six years, 
said Henson absolutely hates to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the most competitive person I've ever been around,''  
Evans said. ``Very few people know he's a champion checkers player. 
You don't want to play him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Henson honed his talent for checkers and dominoes while growing  
up in Okay, Okla. (population 300 when Henson lived there). 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing to do in Okay but play checkers and  
dominoes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	On a basketball court, said Evans, there are few coaches better  
than his old boss. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was tough, really tough on us. You knew when you hit that  
floor he was the boss and you were the worker,'' Evans said. ``But 
we could, after a ballgame, sit down and play cards with him. Very 
few people can balance both things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant coach Rus Bradburd described Henson as ``the George  
Foreman of college basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Like George, everybody thinks he's a nice guy and he is a  
genuinely good person. But you strip away the niceness, the smile 
and good nature and you find a fierce competitor,'' Bradburd said. 
``There's no complex formula. He just outworks people and now 
because of his experience, he outsmarts them, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After graduating from New Mexico State, Henson was hired at Las  
Cruces High School as the junior varsity coach, then promoted to 
head coach. The school won three state championships and 103 of 119 
games in four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	By then, colleges were recruiting him.  
</P>
<P>
	Henson turned down an assistant's job at New Mexico to be the  
head coach at Hardin-Simmons. In four seasons there, Henson had a 
67-36 record. He returned to New Mexico State for 10 years, leading 
the Aggies to five NCAA tournaments and an overall 191-83 record. 
In 1969-70, the Aggies went 27-3, losing to UCLA in the semifinals 
of the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1975, Illinois hired Henson. In 21 seasons there his record  
was 423-225, and included 12 trips to the NCAA tournament and the 
Final Four in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Henson retired in 1996, but agreed to help NMSU when McCarthy  
was removed two days before the start of practice last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't going to coach again,'' Henson said. ``I had started  
playing golf. When Jim Paul approached me, I was shocked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But now Henson plans to finish out his contract and doesn't  
think about what might have happened had he chosen an 
administrator's chair instead of a courtside bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I made the right decision,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
