<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cubs' Wood Hospitalized for Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood was hospitalized for  
precautionary testing Wednesday after the NL Rookie of the Year 
missed his third straight day of spring training workouts because 
of a lingering illness. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason for putting him in is to get some blood cultures  
and see if we can pin down exactly what the cause is and just be 
careful and stay ahead of it,'' Cubs team physician Dr. John 
Marquardt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, 21, struck out 20 batters in just his fifth major league  
start last year. He was bothered by a sore elbow at the end of last 
season, and began his offseason workout program earlier than ever. 
</P>
<P>
	But last month, he developed an upper respiratory ailment. Then  
last week, Wood was hospitalized briefly with gastrointestinal 
problems that included diarrhea, vomiting and dehydration. 
According to Marquardt, Wood lost 12 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason we put him in was to get him rehydrated, which he  
did. He responded well,'' Marquardt said. ``And then over the 
weekend, he started with a cough. He started on medication Monday 
and he has persisted to have chills and fever in the early 
mornings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, having trouble keeping his energy level up, has been  
feeling better since beginning the medication. But Marquardt said 
the team wanted to do ``some more investigating to see if we can 
find if there is anything else going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, 13-6 last year, participated in Sunday's first day of  
drills for pitchers and catchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He felt good Sunday morning and then he started to get dizzy  
as the day went on. His temperature was about 101 and he 
struggled,'' Cubs general manager Ed Lynch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said missing time early in the spring  
isn't crucial. The full squad is scheduled for its first workout 
Friday, although Sammy Sosa won't participate until Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love spring training, but we don't need six weeks,''  
Riggleman said. ``In this case, you are glad you got extra time. 
Kerry can catch up on his conditioning once he gets his strength 
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood could remain in Mesa Lutheran Hospital for two days until  
test results are available, Marquardt said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
