<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Feb. 25, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Rap Artist Sets Grammy Award Record  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Breaking a record for female artists, hip-hop  
star Lauryn Hill Won five Grammy Awards Wednesday night. Another 
big winner was the ``Titanic'' ballad ``My Heart Will Go On'' 
taking four awards, including song and record of the year. Hill 
stepped away from the Fugees to win album of the year for ``The 
Miseducation of Lauryn Hill'' and best new artist. Madonna won 
three Grammys, including best pop album. Shania Twain, Stevie 
Wonder, the Dixie Chicks and the Brian Setzer Orchestra each were 
double winners. 

</P>
<P>
	China Eyes Macedonia Punishment  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Punishing Macedonia for establishing ties  
with Taiwan, China said Wednesday it will cast its fifth veto in 
history to block the extension of a U.N. peacekeeping force in the 
former Yugoslav republic. Diplomats and human rights officials 
decried the decision, saying the peacekeepers were the only 
remaining barrier preventing the ethnic violence in Serbia's Kosovo 
province from spilling across the border into Macedonia. China 
severed ties with Macedonia after it established diplomatic 
relations with Taiwan last month. 

</P>
<P>
	Americans Favor Troops in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than half of Americans say they favor  
U.S. participation in a NATO peacekeeping force in Kosovo, but four 
out of five think President Clinton should get approval from 
Congress first, says a new Gallup poll. People were about evenly 
divided when asked whether they favored a U.S. role in NATO 
airstrikes against Serb military installations if the Serbs and 
ethnic Albanians fail to reach a peace agreement to end their 
yearlong conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	Kurd Rebel Allowed To See Lawyers  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Lawyers defending Kurdish rebel chief  
Abdullah Ocalan have been granted permission to visit him for the 
first time since his capture last week, his attorneys said 
Wednesday. Turkish commandos seized Ocalan Feb. 16 in Kenya. He has 
been under interrogation since then, and his legal team has been 
worried about his treatment. Ocalan's rebel army has waged a bloody 
15-year struggle for autonomy in Turkey's Kurdish-dominated 
southeast. The conflict has claimed an estimated 37,000 lives. 

</P>
<P>
	Surgery Shown on Superfast Internet  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a live demonstration of the promise of a  
superfast Internet, a physician in Washington collaborated 
Wednesday night over a special high-speed network with surgeons 
working on a patient at a hospital in Ohio. The remote 
``operation'' took place over the $500 million Abilene Network, a 
new data pipeline that links more than three dozen research 
universities nationwide. It works at speeds 45,000 times faster 
than the best telephone modems that people now use to surf the Web. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Wait 18 Mos. for Pregnancy  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Spacing your kids 2 1/2 years apart may be ideal  
for producing a healthy, full-term baby, according to a study that 
found a sound medical basis for what many women are doing already. 
A study by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention found 
that while having babies too close together can be bad for the 
infants' health, having them too far apart may be even worse. Both 
situations raise the risk that the new baby will be premature or 
small, which can cause long-term health problems, even death. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Mission To Be Shut in Angola  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council this week is  
preparing to shut down a U.N. mission in Angola, convinced that the 
military observers have no job to do because the 1994 peace accord 
they were overseeing have collapsed. On Wednesday, the United 
States, Russia and Portugal, the three nations overseeing the peace 
accord, circulated a draft resolution that would phase out U.N. 
Observers in Angola by March 20. The council was expected to adopt 
the resolution Friday. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices advanced Thursday. The Nikkei  
Stock Average rose 63.52 points, ending the morning session at 
14,418.97. In New York Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average 
closed down 144.75 at 9,399.67. 

</P>
<P>
	Mighty Ducks Beat Oilers 2-1  
</P>
<P>
	EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Paul Kariya scored the game winner and  
added an assist as the Anaheim Mighty Ducks beat the Edmonton 
Oilers 2-1 Wednesday night. Kariya broke a 1-1 tie with 5:04 left 
in the third period when he took a drop pass from Steve Rucchin 
just inside the Edmonton blue line and fired a slap shot over 
goalie Steve Passmore's glove. Passmore was making his NHL debut 
after being called up earlier this week from the Hamilton Bulldogs 
of the AHL. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
