<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Islanders Goalie Potvin Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- New York Islanders goaltender Felix  
Potvin was injured in practice on Wednesday and could be lost to 
the team for the rest of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	A team spokesman said that Potvin suffered a groin injury and  
will be out for four to six weeks. The regular season ends on April 
18. 
</P>
<P>
	The Islanders acquired Potvin in a trade with Toronto on Jan. 9,  
sending defenseman Bryan Berard to the Maple Leafs. The teams also 
swapped sixth-round picks in the 1999 NHL Entry Draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal ended a season of grief in Toronto for Potvin, who left  
the team on Dec. 2 after he had been relegated to the No. 2 goalie 
position after the acquisition of Curtis Joseph. 
</P>
<P>
	Potvin was Toronto's No. 1 goalie for five seasons, twice  
helping the Maple Leafs to the Western Conference finals, but was 
bumped to a backup role when Joseph signed a four-year, $24-million 
contract in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Potvin started only five of the Maple Leafs' first 25 games,  
posting a 3-2 record with a goals-against average of 3.81. With the 
Islanders, Potvin has shared goaltending duties with Tommy Salo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:53:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hill, Twain Are Early Winners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lauryn Hill's solo debut album ``The  
Miseducation of Lauryn Hill'' and the hit single ``Doo Wop (That 
Thing)'' won the hip-hop star three Grammys awards Wednesday night. 
The ``Titanic'' ballad ``My Heart Will Go On'' won three, including 
song of the year, and Madonna also won three. 
</P>
<P>
	Shania Twain, Stevie Wonder, the Brian Setzer Orchestra were  
double winners. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, whose 10 nominations led a parade of women up for awards,  
won best rhythm and blues album, best R&AMP;B song and the R&AMP;B vocal 
performance Grammy for ``Doo Wop.'' She had three remaining chances 
during the CBS-TV broadcast from the Shrine Auditorium. 
</P>
<P>
	She lost a major category in the pre-telecast when non-classical  
producer of the year went to Rob Cavallo, who worked with the Goo 
Goo Dolls, Green Day and Alanis Morissette. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, 23, and her acclaimed album -- mixing rap and R&AMP;B, and  
touching on family and political issues -- had a chance to win the 
most Grammys ever by a female artist in one night. Carole King won 
four in 1971 for ``Tapestry.'' Hill has two past Grammys from her 
stint with the Fugees. 
</P>
<P>
	No hip-hop artist has won album of the year, a category  
dominated this year by women. Other contenders: Sheryl Crow's ``The 
Globe Sessions,'' Madonna's ``Ray of Light,'' Twain for ``Come on 
Over,'' and ``Version 2.0'' by alternative rocker Garbage, led by 
singer Shirley Manson. (No hip-hop artist has ever won song or 
record of the year, either.) 
</P>
<P>
	Crow, a five-time Grammy winner in recent years, and country-pop  
crossover sensation Twain received six nominations each. Madonna 
had five bids. 
</P>
<P>
	Women also dominated the record of the year category. Madonna's  
``Ray of Light'' and Twain's ``You're Still the One'' were up 
against Brandy &AMP; Monica (``The Boy Is Mine''), Celine Dion (``My 
Heart Will Go On'') and the lone male entry, ``Iris,'' by the Goo 
Goo Dolls. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're Still the One'' won best country song for Twain and  
husband Robert John ``Mutt'' Lange and female country vocal 
performance for Twain. 
</P>
<P>
	``My Heart Will Go On'' brought the female pop vocal trophy to  
Dion and honors to writers James Horner and Will Jennings as best 
song written for a motion picture or television. The writers also 
won for song of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Madonna got the first musical Grammy of her career -- best dance  
recording for ``Ray of Light.'' The song also won short form music 
video. Her only previous Grammy was for video in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brian Setzer Orchestra, riding the swing revival, captured  
two pop honors, performance by a duo or group and instrumental 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The male R&AMP;B vocal Grammy went to Wonder for ``St. Louis  
Blues.'' The tune also earned him and two colleagues the award for 
instrumental arrangement with vocals. The two Grammys brought 
Wonder's career total to 21. 
</P>
<P>
	That ties him with Pierre Boulez, who also won two Wednesday  
night -- orchestral performance and opera recording. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Sir Georg Solti, Quincy Jones and Vladimir Horowitz have  
won more. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandy &AMP; Monica won the R&AMP;B duo or group performance trophy for  
``The Boy Is Mine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In rap categories, Jay-Z's ``Vol. 2 ... Hard Knock Life'' won  
best album. The rapper had said he would skip the show because he 
doesn't like the way the Grammys treat rap. In other awards, the 
Beastie Boys won duo or group performance for ``Intergalactic'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his 12th Grammy victory of the 1990s, Eric Clapton won male  
pop vocal for ``My Father's Eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burt Bacharach had his first win since 1986, giving him Grammys  
in three different decades. He and Elvis Costello won for pop 
collaboration with vocals on ``I Still Have That Other Girl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnny Cash, Mel Torme, Smokey Robinson and the late Sam Cooke  
and Otis Redding each received lifetime achievement awards from the 
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences at the 41st annual 
Grammy Awards. Rosie O'Donnell served as master of ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	The songwriting teams of Alan Jay Lerner and Frederick Loewe,  
Kenneth Gamble and Leon Huff, and Jerry Leiber and Mike Stoller 
were honored with trustees' awards for outstanding contributions by 
nonperformers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
