<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall, 30-Yr Yields Rise / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Long-term Treasury bond yields shot up to a  
six-month high Wednesday as the market declined sharply for a 
second straight day. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were disappointed with a Treasury auction of two-year  
notes and continued to fret about Federal Reserve policy as the 
central bank's chairman, Alan Greenspan, wrapped up two days of 
congressional testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 3/32  
points, or $10.94 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 5.51 percent from 5.43 percent 
late Tuesday and 5.35 percent Monday. It was the highest yield for 
30-year bonds since Aug. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the decline in the bond market came late in the  
afternoon following a Treasury auction of $15 billion in two-year 
notes, which drew only lukewarm interest from investors. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, there is a perception in the market that the next  
policy move by the Fed, which cut a key short-term interest rate 
three times last year, will be to raise rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's two days of testimony before congressional  
committees was interpreted as signaling that if an economic 
slowdown doesn't occur, the central bank is prepared to increase 
interest rates to make it happen. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates would hurt bond prices by making the  
yields on bonds already in circulation less attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were off as much as 1/8 point, and intermediate maturities were off 3/8 
point to 17/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, fell 5.3 
points to 1,287.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills held at 4.65 percent as the  
discount was unchanged from Tuesday at 4.54 percent. Six-month 
yields rose to 4.68 percent, as the discount rose 0.04 percentage 
point to 4.52 percent. One-year yields rose to 4.80 percent as the 
discount rose by 0.04 percentage point from late Monday to 4.59 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.75 percent from 4.69 percent Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 124 23/32 from 125 1/32. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 5.17 percent from 5.15 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
