<HEADLINE> Alomars Reunited With Indians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINTER HAVEN, Fla. (AP) -- The Indians were back together on  
Wednesday, and so were the Alomars. 
</P>
<P>
	``This doesn't feel like anything special yet, because it's  
still spring training,'' Sandy said as Cleveland held its first 
full-squad workout. 
</P>
<P>
	His brother, Roberto, left the Baltimore Orioles as a free agent  
and signed a $32 million, four-year contract with the Indians. The 
addition of the Gold Glove second baseman gives Cleveland an 
All-Star at every position. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will feel more special when the regular season begins,''  
Sandy said. ``But this is really a thrill for both of us, because 
we've always dreamed about being on the same team in the major 
leagues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the exception of designated hitter, there won't be any  
competition for jobs in camp. The DH spot will be contested by Wil 
Cordero, signed a few weeks before camp, and Richie Sexson, who hit 
.310 in the second half of last season while filling in for injured 
first baseman Jim Thome. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordero, who spent last season with the White Sox, is getting  
another chance at a fresh start with Cleveland. Two years ago, 
while with Boston, he was convicted of attacking his wife and 
remains on probation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians signed him at the urging of the Alomar brothers.  
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was a chance for me to show what kind of person I  
am,'' Cordero said. ``And for me to come to the organization like 
the Cleveland Indians is a dream come true. I want the people in 
the Cleveland organization to know that I won't disappoint them or 
the fans. I don't think anybody is perfect, and I am willing to get 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Mike Hargrove said the loser of the DH duel will still  
make the team as a bench player. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing we've got to be alert for is complacency,'' Hargrove  
said. ``We need to be aware of it, and we'll take steps to combat 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians were criticized last year for playing uninspired  
baseball in the second half. They went 39-38 after the All-Star 
break, but still easily clinched another AL Central title. 
</P>
<P>
	Turning up the intensity level is one of the club's goals for  
this season. When the players arrived at camp, they found T-shirts 
in their lockers that said: ``100+: Go Hard or Go Home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 100 doesn't stand for 100 percent, but 100 wins.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's important for us to set the tone from Day 1,'' Hargrove  
said. ``And I think we did that.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Hargrove greeted 56 players, who began the day by  
completing the dreaded ``Warrior Run,'' an 850-yard sprint arranged 
by strength and conditioning coach Fernando Montes. Pitchers 
Charles Nagy, Richard Negrette, and shortstop Omar Vizquel led the 
pack, finishing in a three-way tie for first 2 minutes, 46 seconds. 
``This thing has taken on monstrous proportions,'' Hargrove said of 
the run, which Kevin Mitchell couldn't finish a couple of years 
ago. ``It's like the Great Wall of China.'' ... Thome did not take 
part in the run, and held a limited workout because of a sore back. 
``It locked up on me a couple of days ago,'' Thome said. ``I don't 
think it's anything serious. I had something like this in spring 
training a couple of years ago.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
