<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olivetti Revamps Takeover Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Olivetti SpA early Thursday morning filed a  
revamped initial takeover offer for Telecom Italia which leaves 
unchanged the basic financial details first announced Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti, after many hours of consultations with Italian  
stock-market regulator Consob, said it would offer more than $58 
billion in cash, bonds and shares for Telecom's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti's board of directors met throughout the night in Milan  
to discuss Consob's earlier ruling that the company's initial bid 
to take over Telecom Italia required modifications to be legally 
valid. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by the regulatory agency Consob gave Telecom, the  
world's sixth-largest phone company, breathing space to start 
mounting a defense against the hostile bid by a rival one-fifth its 
size. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti also said Thursday that the tender offer for the  
telecom company's shares will begin on an unspecified day in April 
and that a detailed calendar for the offer will be agreed upon with 
the stock-market regulator. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of a date for a tender offer had been a key omission in  
Olivetti's initial announcement last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Consob's final approval of this offer is expected anytime within  
the next 15 days. With this filing, however, Telecom can't alter 
its capital or share structure, in accordance with Italian law, 
unless Consob rules against Olivetti. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe has long been dominated by national companies accustomed  
to little if any competition within their respective borders. Since 
the deregulation of Europe's telecommunications industry last year, 
established companies have begun to face a growing challenge from 
entrepreneurial firms like Olivetti, a former maker of typewriters 
and computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom's board of directors was to meet Thursday to try to  
forge a strategy for fending off the Olivetti bid. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Telecom's options is to merge with Telecom Italia Mobile,  
a cellular phone company in which it already holds a 60-percent 
stake. Such a merger appeared initially as a way for Telecom to 
make Olivetti's takeover effort much more expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a surprise move late Wednesday, Consob announced that  
Olivetti's bid would not have to include an offer for any of the 40 
percent of shares in the cellular phone subsidiary that are not 
owned by Telecom Italia. This additional stake in Italia Mobile has 
a market value of about $20 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Consob cautioned that it would reconsider its ruling at the time  
of Olivetti's revised bid. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Telecom's chief executive Franco Bernabe gave no  
details of a possible merger when he met with union officials 
earlier Wednesday. He emphasized, however, that he expected the 
Italian government to remain neutral in Telecom's struggle with 
Olivetti. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom, a former government monopoly, was privatized in 1997.  
The Italian Treasury retains 3.4 percent of Telecom shares and has 
veto power over all major decisions through the end of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that veto power, Italy's Premier Massimo D'Alema has  
said his government will not choose sides in the takeover battle. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's Treasury said Wednesday that it has started the process  
necessary for selling its stake in Telecom. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
