<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Defense Fund Gets $2.3M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While Bill Clinton was being impeached,  
supporters contributed $2.3 million to help him pay his legal 
bills. 
</P>
<P>
	That's how much Clinton's legal defense fund took in between  
mid-August, after Clinton's first public admission of an improper 
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, and mid-February, when the 
Senate acquitted the president of perjury and obstruction of 
justice. 
</P>
<P>
	More money is expected. The fund recently sent out letters that  
noted: ``The effort to impeach President Clinton is only the latest 
in a series of legal actions that have left the First Family with a 
staggering personal debt. ... If you are disturbed by the way 
politics is conducted today, then what better response than to 
offer the first family your own gesture of support?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the fund raised $4.5 million during its first year,  
from 50,000 contributions, trustees reported Wednesday. The money 
helped whittle the Clintons' outstanding legal bills from $9 
million to $5.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	One $10,000 donor, Atlanta businessman J.B. Fuqua, said wealthy  
individuals who prospered under the Clinton administration have an 
obligation to help the president financially. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all knew when he ran for president the first time that he  
played around with women,'' Fuqua said. ``I don't approve of it, 
but nevertheless that's a fact of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton received 56 contributions of $5,000 or more during the  
last six months, including $10,000 apiece from Lew Wasserman, 
former chairman of Universal Studios; singer Tony Bennett; and Don 
Henley, a member of the Eagles musical group. Archer Daniels 
Midland executive Dwayne Andreas gave $5,000, as did author Stephen 
King and actor Robert DeNiro. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the average contribution was $90, trustees said, and 95  
percent of the donors gave $100 or less. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen an overwhelmingly positive response to our  
efforts to reduce this enormous financial burden, from average 
Americans and larger donors alike,'' the fund's executive director, 
Anthony Essaye, said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last six months, the fund has sent out hundreds of  
thousands of letters to prospective donors, cultivating its mailing 
list from a variety of sources including Democratic Party 
contributors. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Essaye said, the fund will ask earlier contributors  
to give again. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund so far has paid $3 million of Clinton's legal expenses  
from the now-dismissed Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, the 
impeachment trial and Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's 
continuing investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Another $5.2 million remains to be paid, as well as any new  
legal expenses the president may incur, Essaye said. He said he 
expects their total legal bills will reach $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Only six people -- all small donors -- have asked for refunds,  
Essaye said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new fund is operating under fewer restrictions than an  
earlier legal defense fund, which was shut down in 1997. Unlike the 
first fund, the new venture actively seeks contributions and 
accepts donations of up to $10,000 a year, rather than the old 
$1,000 limit. 
</P>
<P>
	The new fund already has raised more money in six months than  
the initial fund did in 3 1/2 years. In that time, it raised $1.3 
million and paid $800,000 of Clinton's legal bills. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
