<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arizona Executes German Citizen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLORENCE, Ariz. (AP) -- A German citizen who chose the gas  
chamber over lethal injection in a bid to avoid execution was put 
to death by injection Wednesday night after being given a 
last-minute choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned a lower  
court and cleared the way for the execution of Karl LaGrand. The 
federal appeals court had ruled earlier in the day that the use of 
cyanide gas was cruel and unusual punishment, just as LaGrand had 
calculated 
</P>
<P>
	LaGrand, 35, was executed for fatally stabbing a bank manager  
during a botched robbery in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	At the last-minute, LaGrand was given the chance to switch to  
lethal injection even though he had chosen death by gas. 
</P>
<P>
	He apologized to the family of his victim and to a woman injured  
during the robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	LaGrand's brother, Walter, 37, is set to die in the gas chamber  
next week for the same crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers' request for death by cyanide, a method far more  
painful than injection, was a calculated move designed to keep them 
from becoming the first German citizens to be executed in the 
United States since World War II, when several prisoners of war 
were hanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the LaGrands, who have been on death row since  
1984, gambled -- successfully -- that an appeals court would buy 
their argument that gas is cruel and unusual punishment. A 
three-judge panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled 
unanimously in LaGrand's favor. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Supreme Court lifted the stay late Wednesday afternoon.  
</P>
<P>
	Arizona last executed a prisoner with gas in 1992. The death was  
regarded as so gruesome that voters approved the use of lethal 
injection. Killers who were convicted before the law passed were 
given a choice of injection or gas. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers came to the United States as boys in 1967 after  
their mother married an American serviceman. Their case has drawn 
widespread attention in Germany, which does not have the death 
penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, a state clemency board rejected impassioned pleas  
from a German delegation that included Germany's ambassador to the 
United States and a member of Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	German officials complained that they did not learn of the  
brothers' case until 1992, eight years after they were condemned to 
die. International law requires nations to notify consulates when 
foreign citizens have been arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona officials said the brothers were afforded all the legal  
rights of U.S. citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 18:33:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 15-Lb. Teen's Mom Won't Stand Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- A woman whose 15-year-old daughter had  
cerebral palsy and died weighing just over 15 pounds will not stand 
trial for child neglect, a judge ruled Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Richard Werner ruled that Karen Kuffer, 50, is mentally  
incompetent for trial on the charge of felony child neglect in the 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	Guy Taylor, Kuffer's attorney, had requested a mental competency  
exam of his client in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said it was unlikely they would try to have Kuffer  
committed to a mental hospital for child neglect. 
</P>
<P>
	Kay Kuffer died Nov. 25 after being taken to the emergency room  
by her mother. The girl died in the emergency room weighing just 15 
pounds and one ounce and was 3 1/2 feet tall, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	An autopsy indicated she died from starvation and dehydration.  
</P>
<P>
	Kay had cerebral palsy, mental retardation and epilepsy, and her  
mother has said that she cared for her daughter the best she knew 
how. 
</P>
</TEXT>
