<DOCNO> APW19990224.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:55:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Film Execs Woo Hollywood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- In a sign that relations between  
Beijing and Hollywood are on the mend, Chinese officials wooed 
American filmmakers on Wednesday with the prospect of doing 
business with the image-conscious government. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit suggests Chinese officials have set aside the ire  
prompted by films such as Walt Disney Co.'s 1996 ``Kundun.'' The 
movie about the life of Tibet's Dalai Lama was seen as critical of 
Chinese rule over Tibet and never officially screened in China. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is normal now,'' Zheng Quan Gang, president of the  
China Film Co-Production Corp., said of relations with Disney. 
</P>
<P>
	But basic rules still apply. Movies are out not only if they  
display too much sex or violence but if they are deemed insulting 
to China's government and culture. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no need to make that kind of film,'' said Zheng, whose  
government agency oversees foreign film production in China. ``The 
Chinese people always say, 'Look forward, not backward.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Zheng spoke to about 50 American film executives in a  
presentation sponsored by the American Film Market, where foreign 
distributors gather each year to review and bid overseas rights to 
English language films. 
</P>
<P>
	Zheng also visited the Burbank headquarters of Disney Studios,  
whose animated feature ``Mulan'' opened in Chinese theaters on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on a Chinese tale, ``Mulan'' tells the story of a girl who  
disguises herself as a man to replace her father in battle. 
</P>
<P>
	China Film is willing to help finance foreign productions that  
pass muster, either directly or through a new fund the agency plans 
to create with Strategic Capital Group, a Hong Kong-based 
investment bank. The China Film Fund has an initial fund-raising 
target of $50 million, said Eric N. Solberg, Strategic Capital's 
managing director. 
</P>
<P>
	The advantages of co-production are significant, said Zheng.  
Joint productions with China Film are exempt from a government 
quota that allows only about 20 foreign films into the country each 
year. Foreign partners also get a bigger share of the box office 
take -- 35 percent compared to half that for distributors of movies 
filmed outside of China. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese market is growing but still is relatively small  
considering the country's population of 1.2 billion. The annual box 
office take is about $250 million, according to estimates by China 
Film officials. That compares to 1998 revenues of $6.95 billion at 
U.S. and Canadian theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	China has about 9,000 movie screens in theaters, plus about  
50,000 mobile screens that travel from village to village. New 
multiplex theaters are being built to boost movie distribution, 
Zheng said. 
</P>
<P>
	China's eagerness to do business is driven in part by economics.  
The government is pushing film studios to become financially 
independent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every studio in China is desperate for co-production,'' said  
Peter Dekom, a financial consultant and former entertainment 
attorney who moderated the presentation by Zheng and other 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting a script past China's censors can be tough, but it is  
worth the effort, said independent producer Peter Shiao, whose 
romantic comedy ``Restless'' was filmed in Beijing last year. 
</P>
<P>
	For Shiao, the obstacles included convincing Chinese officials  
to allow him to cast a Taiwanese actress in the role of a mainland 
Chinese woman. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a testament to the censors' pragmatism that this went  
through. We were audacious enough to ask for it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans sometimes create problems for themselves that have  
nothing to do with politics, said director Anna Chi, who hoped to 
talk with Chinese officials about distributing her movie 
``Blindness,'' a drama focusing on a Chinese-American family. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Chi, who has filmed documentaries and television specials in  
China, said Americans often expect Chinese film crews to be 
submissive and work long hours, including unscheduled overtime 
without extra pay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's a certain way American producers perceive  
Chinese, that they always bow and are always respectful,'' she 
said. ``But on the other hand, Chinese people aren't saints, 
either. They see this opportunity and they become very 
shortsighted. They become money grabbers and do all kinds of things 
to trick you.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 19:14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guest List for State Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Guest list for state dinner in honor of Ghana President Jerry  
John Rawlings, as provided by the White House: 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton.  
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore and Tipper Gore.  
</P>
<P>
	President Jerry John Rawlings and Nana Konadu Agueman-Rawlings.  
</P>
<P>
	Fati Habib Jawula, member, council of state.  
</P>
<P>
	James Victor Ohuho, minister of foreign affairs.  
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John Frank Ahu, minister of trade and industry.  
</P>
<P>
	Kofi Benturn Quantson, national security coordinator.  
</P>
<P>
	Cecilia Johnson, deputy minister of local government and rural  
development. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Mohammed Ibn Chambas, deputy minister of education.  
</P>
<P>
	Victor Selormey, deputy minister of finance.  
</P>
<P>
	Koby Koomoon, ambassador of Ghana to the United States.  
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Bertha Koomson.  
</P>
<P>
	Kofi Attohi, member of parliament and chairman, parlimentary  
committee on foreign affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Kobina Wudu, director of state protocol.  
</P>
<P>
	Henry ``Hank'' Aaron, senior vice president of the Atlanta  
Braves, and Billye Aaron. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Maya Angelou, professor and writer, Wake Forest University,  
and DeFoy Glenn. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Vincent Anku, director, Cleveland Cancer Institute, and  
Cynthia Ferguson, National Summit on Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Kofi Annan, secretary general of the United Nations, and Nane  
Annan. 
