<DOCNO> APW19990224.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:56:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Pins Hopes on Ice Skaters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- The girl is willowy and blond. A long braid bobs  
on the back of her blue bodysuit as she floats across the ice, 
executing graceful double toe-loops, blinding spins and sly little 
dance steps. 
</P>
<P>
	She is warming up for the Winter Olympics -- the games of, say,  
2010. 
</P>
<P>
	Her name is Svetlana and she is 8 years old.  
</P>
<P>
	Russia -- sad, bedraggled Russia -- is counting on her and  
thousands more like her to maintain its dominance in at least one 
realm: figure skating. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia makes few things these days that can compete on the world  
market. Vodka, caviar, Kalashnikov rifles, nuclear power plants, 
jet fighters, booster rockets -- the list gets thin after that. 
</P>
<P>
	But Russians still know how to make gold medal figure skaters  
better than anyone else in the world. While everything else has 
been falling apart, Russian skaters have just kept getting better. 
</P>
<P>
	At last year's Olympic Games in Nagano, Japan, Russians took the  
gold in the men's, pairs and ice dance competitions, failing to win 
a medal only in the U.S.-dominated women's event. 
</P>
<P>
	At the World Figure Skating Championships in Minneapolis, the  
Russians did it again, winning the gold in all but the women's 
event, and taking the silver and bronze in that. 
</P>
<P>
	In Prague this year at the European Championships, the Russians  
took first place in every event, and all three top spots in the 
men's and women's individual competitions. And they did it with 
some of their best cooling their skates at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``If everyone from Russia had been allowed to compete, we would  
have taken the top five or six places in a row,'' said Raphael 
Arutunian, a coach whose best skater, Alexander Abt, skipped the 
competition because of knee surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians' spectacular performance in Prague came as a  
welcome tonic to a country that has become accustomed to nothing 
but bad news. The economy may be in shambles, the president ill and 
the army weak, but Russians can still skate circles around most of 
the rest of the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``Remember, not everything is lost,'' journalist Boris Minayev  
wrote in the Ogonyok magazine. ``We still have this world of these 
sliding gods. It's real, it's ours, and in this world we're 
unbeatable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The secret of Russia's success can be seen in rinks around the  
country, in places such as the Spartak Ice Palace, where young 
Svetlana skates in a class of two dozen 8-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	These classes are the legacy of the vaunted Soviet sports  
machine, which created a brilliant and sometimes brutal system for 
culling and training the nation's best athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	In other sports, the system has retrenched or collapsed. In  
skating, thanks in large measure to the efforts of Valentin Piseev, 
president of the Russian Figure Skating Federation, it is mostly 
intact. 
</P>
<P>
	Children as young as 3 or 4 can attend daily classes; by the  
time they reach school age, they might spend half their day at the 
rink, five days a week. The best move up to better coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Free in Soviet times, the training at Spartak runs about $4.50 a  
month, still affordable for most Russian families. 
</P>
<P>
	The system remains large and well-honed, and the Russians have  
hung onto many of the best Soviet coaches. It is a daunting thought 
to Jimmy Disbrow, president of the U.S. Figure Skating Association, 
whose skaters will face the Russians at the 2002 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Russians certainly have a number of good skaters in place  
right now,'' he said. ``That will be the challenge for everybody 
else in 2002.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians have good reason to be confident.  
</P>
<P>
	The current men's national champion, Yevgeny Plushchenko, is  
only 16. The women's national champion, 26-year-old Maria 
Butyrskaya, has stiff competition from 17-year-old Julia Soldatova 
and 16-year-old Viktoria Volchkova. And there are plenty of other 
strong young skaters in the wings. 
</P>
<P>
	But Piseev worries about the future.  
</P>
<P>
	While youth skating programs remain strong in Moscow and St.  
Petersburg, there are signs of trouble elsewhere. Piseev estimates 
that 20 percent of the nation's ice rinks have closed because of 
economic problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, he says Russia has a very small number of enclosed ice  
rinks, and most rinks are rudimentary by international standards, 
lacking up-to-date gyms and other training equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Many top athletes and coaches have chosen to train in the West,  
mainly in the United States. If that continues, some warn, it could 
be the end of Russian skating dominance. 
</P>
<P>
	The renowned coach Tatiana Tarasova now works in New Jersey.  
Tamara Moskvina, who coaches world pairs champions Yelena 
Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze, works in the United States and 
also coaches an American pair. Other top Russian coaches work 
exclusively with foreign skaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Arutunian, too, is considering a move to the United States. If  
he goes, his skaters go with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know,'' said Abt, 22, who is considered a potential  
Olympic medalist, ``in the United States we'd have good ice rinks, 
good conditions, good everything. And so we're probably going, 
because in the United States we'd have more possibilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marina Druzik, who coaches at the Spartak rink, worries about  
the talent drain. For now, though, she believes the future is 
bright for skaters such as Svetlana. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the girl had been gliding about the rink on one skate,  
her other leg stretched out horizontally behind her. Bringing 
day-glo pink mittens to her mouth, she blew kisses to her adoring -- 
and still quite imaginary -- fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sveta!'' Druzik yelled across the crowded rink. ``I don't  
recognize you today! Your jumps are awful!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Caught short, Svetlana lost a bit of attitude, took a deep  
breath and went back to practice. Her fans could wait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
