<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Church Tried for Electing Gay Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMDEN, Conn. (AP) -- The First Presbyterian Church of Stamford  
goes on trial under religious law Friday for electing an openly gay 
man to the congregation's governing board. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is being watched by gay rights groups and church  
members as the first test of a recent amendment to the Presbyterian 
Church constitution that bars practicing homosexuals from being 
ordained or serving on governing boards, known as sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	The denomination, which has 3 million members in the United  
States, regards gay sex as a sin. 
</P>
<P>
	If the court rules against First Presbyterian, Wayne Osborne's  
election will be declared void and a new contest will be held. 
</P>
<P>
	Osborne, 38, an ordained elder, served on the session several  
years ago, before he publicly disclosed his homosexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	Presbyterian elders are ordained for life, and because Osborne  
hadn't disclosed his homosexuality at the time he was ordained, his 
status as an elder is not at issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Elders and deacons help with church governance, serving  
communion and performing other activities. When elders are elected 
to the session, they can represent the church at presbytery 
meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Osborne was elected in May, but his installation was put on hold  
after two members of the congregation, James McCallum and Mairi 
Hair, filed a complaint. They said Osborne's lifestyle violated 
church doctrine. 
</P>
<P>
	Osborne would not discuss the case.  
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Mary Marple Thies, co-pastor at First Presbyterian,  
said that in electing Osborne, the congregation did not intend to 
challenge church doctrine. She described Osborne as ``a valued and 
beloved member of the congregation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the church is behind him,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	An ecclesiastical court composed of six members of the Southern  
New England Presbytery will hear the case at Quinnipiac College Law 
School. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
