<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Denies Sabotage Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Microsoft engineer rejected as ``completely  
unfounded'' a courtroom claim by Apple Computer that Microsoft 
tried to sabotage Apple's multimedia software. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Engstrom also argued forcefully that proposals to cooperate  
with Apple on Internet video and audio software stemmed from 
Microsoft's desire to help frustrated customers, not from a desire 
to eliminate competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Wednesday, the government began questioning Joachim  
Kempin, the senior Microsoft executive responsible for the 
company's business deals with the nation's computer makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Kempin, who refuses all press interviews and isn't widely known  
even within Microsoft, has argued that the company allows computer 
makers to install whatever rival software they choose and to make 
it easily accessible for consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Kempin also was expected to defend Microsoft's restrictions  
against removing or hiding any part of its Windows operating 
system, such as its Internet browser software. The government 
contends those restrictions illegally hurt Netscape, Microsoft's 
primary Internet software rival. 
</P>
<P>
	In connection with Engstrom's testimony, the government alleges  
that Microsoft encouraged Apple to adopt its own proprietary 
technologies, which would have required Apple's Quicktime customers 
also to use Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department David Boies said Quicktime's ability to run  
across different operating systems posed a threat to Microsoft, 
which depends financially on consumer demand for Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just another example of Microsoft going to a platform  
company and saying, 'If you'll stop doing this, we'll help you in 
some other area,''' Boies said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Microsoft's Engstrom said his company's offer to cooperate  
with Apple on multimedia technology during that industry's 
adolescence several years ago stemmed from customer frustration. 
</P>
<P>
	During that period, rival formats for digital audio and video  
often required consumers to download specific viewer software, such 
as Apple's Quicktime or Microsoft's own Windows Media Player. 
</P>
<P>
	That requirement, which occasionally still occurs, is the  
equivalent of having to buy and configure different television sets 
to watch incompatible broadcast programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Engstrom said he told Apple executives: ``I'm tired of the  
results of our squabbling ... being passed on to our customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He admitted under questioning by Justice Department lawyer Phil  
Malone that Microsoft told Apple that if it didn't cooperate, then 
Microsoft would write its own software tools for others to produce 
multimedia content on the Internet, an industry that Apple 
considered lucrative. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would have no choice,'' he said. ``It was not work I looked  
forward to doing.'' But Engstrom insisted: ``We never said we would 
not compete with Apple if they used our runtime (technology).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Apple executive Avadis Tevanian testified previously that  
Microsoft designed parts of Windows to bypass Quicktime and created 
misleading error messages. 
</P>
<P>
	But Engstrom said Microsoft blamed the problem on Apple's own  
faulty software, an explanation verified by some independent 
experts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was amazing to me that Dr. Tevanian could come in here and  
make the claim that we sabotage Quicktime,'' Engstrom said. ``At 
Microsoft, our company would never do anything like that.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
