<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Webber Returns to Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At a recent Washington Wizards game, two fans  
held up a banner that read: ``C.Webb fan 4 life. Payback 2/25.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payback is now at hand.  
</P>
<P>
	In easily the most anticipated game on the Washington schedule,  
the Wizards on Thursday will play host to the Sacramento Kings and 
former teammate Chris Webber, the mercurial talent who was traded 
against his wishes last year mostly because of his off-the-court 
behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm going to get a little more hyper,'' Webber said.  
``But hopefully I won't overdo it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Webber spent four years in Washington playing alongside Michigan  
buddy Juwan Howard. They were supposed to bring a championship 
contender to the nation's capital. They didn't win even a single 
playoff game. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, last year, Webber was arrested on marijuana charges in  
January -- a jury found him innocent in December -- and he and Howard 
were accused of sexual assault after a late party at Howard's house 
in April, although no charges were filed. Webber also skipped team 
functions, such as an autograph session for season ticket-holders 
and the filming of the team's video. 
</P>
<P>
	That was more than enough for Wizards management, who sent him  
into what is generally regarded as NBA exile. The small-market 
Kings have endured an NBA-record 15 consecutive losing seasons, and 
there was doubt whether Webber would report to his new team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he felt good about that trade,'' said Wizards  
guard Rod Strickland, offering a candidate for understatement of 
the year. ``He may have something inside of him that he wants to 
prove.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thus setting the stage for an emotional evening. Webber has  
always been one to wear his heart on his sleeve, especially on the 
court. Try as he might to think one game at a time, he can't keep 
his mind on this one. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very tough,'' Webber said after a recent game in Orlando.  
``You just try to occupy your mind with other things. Over the 
years, I've learned, and coaches teach you, don't look to the next 
game. That's what I'm trying to do. But it's tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings played Wednesday night in Philadelphia and will leave  
Friday at noon for Dallas, so there won't be time for much of a 
reunion among old acquaintances. It'll be interesting to see how 
Howard and Webber interact -- their relationship grew somewhat 
frosty after they each offered conflicting and self-serving 
explanations as to what happened at the infamous April party. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard says that's old news.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good friend of mine,'' Howard said. ``And he's a  
teammate that we miss and I miss. Now he's on the other end, and 
he's looking to come in here and win. We want to disrupt that. We 
both are competitive individuals, we're going to do whatever it 
takes to help our team win. We'll see what the outcome will be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Howard and Webber were teammates for six of the last seven  
years. They've faced each other only in high school camps and AAU 
tournaments in the Midwest and, of course, in lots and lots of 
practices. 
</P>
<P>
	If early season form is any indication, Webber will come out on  
top. Howard has struggled lately, making just eight of 27 shots in 
his last two games. Webber, while making it clear he's not where he 
wants to be, has been sensational, averaging 22 points and 14 
rebounds through Tuesday's games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something that I want to get to, enjoy, and get it over  
with as soon as possible,'' Webber said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
