<HEADLINE> Robin Ventura Arrives at Mets Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- Robin Ventura arrived at New York  
Mets camp Wednesday, intent on adjusting to his new team and a new 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, who left the White Sox to sign a $32 million, four-year  
contract with the Mets in December, went through spring drills and 
took batting practice with his unfamiliar teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels great,'' Ventura said. ``I spent most of today  
meeting the guys and learning their names.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, a five-time Gold Glove winner, is slated to be the  
Mets' everyday third baseman when the regular season begins. 
</P>
<P>
	His addition was part of a busy offseason for the Mets, who  
spent $163.9 million to keep Mike Piazza, Al Leiter and Dennis 
Cook, and sign Rickey Henderson and Ventura. General manager Steve 
Phillips also traded for Bobby Bonilla and Armando Benitez. 
</P>
<P>
	``They brought everybody in here for a particular reason,''  
Ventura said. ``Mine is to play third base and do what they need me 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, who hit .263 with 21 homers and 91 RBIs last season,  
will be called upon to add punch to an offense that was 11th in the 
National League in runs scored last season. 
</P>
<P>
	He will have to learn new pitchers after spending his entire  
10-year career with the White Sox in the American League. Ventura 
has faced some NL pitchers who used to play in the AL or in 
interleague play, but he knows he will have an adjustment to make. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think at first the pitchers will have the advantage,''  
Ventura said. ``But they still throw it, so I'm still going to try 
and hit it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another player who reported Wednesday was outfielder Jason  
Tyner, who was the Mets' first-round draft choice out of Texas A&AMP;M 
in 1998. Tyner spent last season with the Class A team in Port St. 
Lucie and followed that with a session in the Mets' Instructional 
League. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedy center fielder has added 12 pounds to his frame since  
playing college baseball last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Mets manager Bobby Valentine spent part of the day watching his  
pitching staff throw live batting practice against the position 
players who have already reported to camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being the first time, it looked like the pitchers were ahead  
of the hitters,'' Valentine said. ``I thought Al (Leiter), Rick 
Reed and Johnny (Franco) looked really sharp. I thought (Masato) 
Yoshii's control was very good.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
