<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Combustible Rodman in Tinseltown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dennis Rodman is not the first player to get a coach fired.  
Maybe just the first to get it done without ever setting foot in 
the place. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Los Angeles Lakers handed Del Harris his  
walking papers. He won a lot of regular-season basketball games, 
yet always seemed to be hanging on by his fingernails. He was all 
of a dozen games into the season with a 6-6 record when he finally 
lost his grip. Around the same time, through the same revolving 
door, in walked Rodman. 
</P>
<P>
	Coincidence?  
</P>
<P>
	No.  
</P>
<P>
	Just the beginning.  
</P>
<P>
	It doesn't matter which one of Harris' assistants -- Kurt Rambis  
or Larry Drew -- gets the head coaching job. To Rodman, he's just 
fresh meat. But wrecking a coach's psyche, or the Lakers' 
chemistry, or even the anatomy of whatever unfortunate winds up in 
the main ring of his nightly circus won't be the worst thing he 
does. Not even close. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman, after all, will be working in the NBA, not NASA. So  
there really is a limit on how much damage he can do unto others. 
The worrisome part is what he's going to do to himself, and by 
extension, a league that provides everything necessary for a 
fireworks show but the matches. 
</P>
<P>
	If Rodman's performance at a news conference in Beverly Hills,  
Calif., the other day was an act, then we know why Hollywood was no 
longer an option. And if it wasn't an act, well, then he needs more 
help than the Lakers are ever going to be able to provide. There is 
a sense of desperation about Rodman that wasn't there a few short 
years ago, a supporting cast that isn't there now. Any team that 
exploits him does so knowing the risks. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, when Rodman moved from San Antonio to Chicago, his rap  
sheet held nothing worse than skipped practices, suspensions and 
stockinged-feet strikes. When the Bulls expressed an interest in 
signing him, he flew to Chicago and -- talk about odd couples -- 
actually stayed with general manager Jerry Krause. He had plenty of 
reasons to behave. 
</P>
<P>
	Ever since Pistons coach Chuck Daly left him behind in Detroit  
in 1992, Rodman struggled with his work and his finances. Ron 
Rothstein, who followed Daly in Detroit, didn't have a clue how to 
motivate Rodman or enough talent on the Pistons to simply ignore 
him. Neither did his coaches in San Antonio, John Lucas and Bob 
Hill, who played the alternate ends of the good cop-bad cop game 
with the same result. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulls, though, offered everything the Spurs could not.  
Rodman was leaving a young team for one packed with veterans. He 
was trading a soft, middle-of-the-pack Western Conference squad led 
by nice guy David Robinson for a nasty Eastern Conference side led 
by Michael Jordan, who still had something to prove. Rodman picked 
up an agent who was just as skilled as the client at wacky 
promotions, but better at keeping a checkbook. Most important, 
perhaps, Rodman was getting a coach, Phil Jackson, whose take on 
the game occasionally made Dennis' understanding of things seem 
downright technical. 
</P>
<P>
	And even with all that, Rodman eventually started throwing  
gaskets. He head-butted a referee, kicked a cameraman in the groin, 
and publicly insulted the entire Mormon population of Utah. Then he 
took off to wrestle with Hulk Hogan instead of practice during the 
playoffs. By last season's NBA Finals, Rodman's most important 
assignment appeared to be distracting Karl Malone. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, any semblance of order is gone. Rodman is 37, but more like  
47 in terms of wear and tear. Finding him turned out to be an 
exhausting enough task for the Lakers' management, and signing him 
wasn't much easier. Rodman fired agent Dwight Manley and apparently 
turned over the bookkeeping to his sister, Debra, then wept at how 
little he was getting paid. 
</P>
<P>
	From the look of things at the news conference, his off-again,  
on-again wife, Carmen Electra, has become not just his emotional 
support, but his promoter as well, a kind of Don King with better 
hair and a formfitting silver dress. 
</P>
<P>
	And finally, there was Rodman's own explanation for why he was  
coming back. ``What got me over the hump was the fact I'm bored, 
I'm tired of not doing anything. I want to go back out and 
entertain the people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On either side of that pronouncement, Rodman ripped into his  
teammates-to-be, revealed more about his marital bed than anyone 
cared to know and left few doubts that whatever restraints were 
intact last season won't automatically carry over into this one. 
</P>
<P>
	Worse yet, Rodman practically has a license to misbehave in L.A.  
Most of the higher-ups on the club voted ``no'' about acquiring 
him. But the only two votes that counted belonged to the star, 
Shaquille O'Neal, and the owner, Jerry Buss. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dennis will treat them all equally -- which is to say with  
disdain. He will be asked to police the menace himself, an idea 
that looks worse by the day. Remember: this is a man who promised 
to walk off the court naked. With only so much ability left, even 
less to prove and no one in control, that day is almost certainly 
closer than any of us think. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@apmail.ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
