<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Solomon Northup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) -- For a black man living decades before  
the Civil War, Solomon Northup had a wonderful life. 
</P>
<P>
	Born a free man, Northup was a well-regarded resident of  
Saratoga Springs, a hard worker with a family and his own home, and 
a talented violinist who was popular at parties. 
</P>
<P>
	All that changed dramatically in March 1841 when he met two men  
who lured him to Washington, D.C., with the promise of a job and 
sold him into slavery for $650. 
</P>
<P>
	The remarkable story of Northup's experience as a slave working  
the sugar cane and cotton plantations of Louisiana's Red River 
Valley was recounted in his 1853 autobiography. ``Twelve Years a 
Slave.'' Although overshadowed by the best-selling ``Uncle Tom's 
Cabin,'' published the year before, Northup's book sold a 
respectable 30,000 copies and still has impact today. 
</P>
<P>
	```Uncle Tom's Cabin' was fiction. Solomon Northup was real,''  
said Khayree Miles, a Union College sophomore who was part of a 
research team that created a Northup exhibit. Miles changed his 
major from engineering to African Studies during his research, 
after finding an original bill of sale for Northup. 
</P>
<P>
	Northup's story carried a special horror because he was  
transformed from a literate, property-owning, voting citizen of New 
York state into a shackled slave renamed Platt who was whipped when 
he did not bring in enough cotton at the end of the day. He was 
nearly hanged for daring to defend himself from a brutal beating by 
a cruel master. He was 32 at the time of his kidnapping. 
</P>
<P>
	Each step of the way, for every cruelty and indignity he faced,  
Northup was able to see the good in the people around him. When he 
was about to be hanged by an outraged slave owner, he was saved by 
the brave intervention of a white overseer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, he was rescued from slavery by Henry B. Northup, the  
son of the man who had given Solomon's father freedom from slavery 
a generation earlier and whose name the black and white families 
shared. It was Henry B. Northup, after receiving a letter secreted 
out of the South, who traveled to Albany, then to Washington, and 
into the remote bayou country of Louisiana to seek out and demand 
the release of the enslaved Solomon Northup. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon Northup was big news in his day.  
</P>
<P>
	Salmon P. Chase, the future Chief Justice of the U.S. Supreme  
Court, argued his case against the kidnappers and The New York 
Times carried a dramatic front page story about him. There were 
trials in Washington and Ballston Spa, N.Y., but the kidnappers 
were never convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The book was reprinted by Louisiana State University Press in  
1968 and in 1984 became the subject of a movie directed by Gordon 
Parks and starring Avery Brooks (``American History X'' and TV's 
``Star Trek: Deep Space Nine''). The entire 273-page book is online 
at the University of North Carolina Web site and, most recently, 
was the subject of an exhibition at Union College in upstate New 
York. A house that Northup lived in is now a museum in nearby Fort 
Edward. 
</P>
<P>
	The Union College exhibit, which runs through March 14, includes  
shackles used on slaves, and a reproduction of the bill of sale for 
Northup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good for Solomon. He's living on. He's having his  
justice. He's still telling his piece,'' Miles said. 
</P>
<P>
	The brutality of slavery is told in a dispassionate style, yet  
some incidents are almost too painful to read. There's the story of 
Eliza, a mother separated from her children who never stopped 
mourning her loss and died a slow death. There is Northup's account 
of being forced to whip Patsy, a slave and friend. 
</P>
<P>
	But there is a remarkable lack of bitterness in Northup's story.  
He was able to write kindly of the slave owners and whites who 
treated him with respect and he blamed the cruelties of others on 
what the institution of slavery had done to the men who claimed to 
own him. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the book found its way into the hands of Rachel  
Seligman, director of the Mandeville Gallery at Union College, 
whose idea it was to create an ambitious exhibit commemorating 
Northup and his book. A research team, including professor Clifford 
Brown and four students, pored over local historical archives and 
abandoned cemeteries, and even traveled to Louisiana to collect 
more information. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were driving where Solomon walked miles without shoes,''  
said Miles, who retraced Northup's journey through Washington, 
D.C., to the bayou country. 
</P>
<P>
	The Union College researchers were following a path of discovery  
taken more than 60 years ago by Sue Eakin, who read Northup's book 
when she was a teen-ager growing up on a Louisiana plantation. The 
encounter with ``Twelve Years a Slave'' led her to a life of 
historical research, much of it devoted to Solomon Northup. 
</P>
<P>
	Eakin, a retired Louisiana State University history professor,  
is thrilled at the attention Northup is receiving. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very excited. I've worked a lifetime to get some of this  
going. 
</P>
<P>
	``My love is historical research and bringing up a picture of  
the South that is realistic. I am 80 years old and there has not 
been a day gone by that I haven't done something with this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She has collected oral history, and thousands of pictures and  
documents related to Northup and Southern history. She is still 
working to restore the Epps Plantation house where Northup spent a 
decade as a slave, as well as historical markers identifying the 
highlights of Northup's life. 
</P>
<P>
	After his book came out, Northup traveled around the Northeast  
speaking against slavery. Among the Union troops who marched 
through the Louisiana plantations where he had been enslaved was 
2nd. Lt. William H. Root. he had read Northup's book and described 
in detail the scene of the freed slaves, writing that many 
remembered Northup and the day he was freed. 
</P>
<P>
	By that time, though, Northup had apparently died. No researcher  
has been able to find out what happened to him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
