<HEADLINE> Salmon Predicts Angels Trades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Tim Salmon believes he may soon lose one of  
his longtime Angels teammates, either Garret Anderson or Jim 
Edmonds. 
</P>
<P>
	They are rumored as trade possibilities for a starting pitcher,  
possibly Toronto's Pat Hentgen, to reduce the glut of Anaheim's 
outfielders. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to believe a trade is coming down some time,''  
Salmon said Wednesday. ``That's tough because we've grown up around 
each other our whole career. 
</P>
<P>
	``You hate to see anybody move on, which will probably happen,  
not because they can't play. There's not enough room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anaheim manager Terry Collins has four outfielders for three  
positions -- Darin Erstad, Salmon, Anderson and Edmonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Erstad or Anderson might be used as a designated hitter  
occasionally. Salmon does not want to fill that role again. 
</P>
<P>
	He reiterated that he is a right fielder first and foremost. He  
was the designated hitter last season, playing through the pain of 
a torn ligament in his left foot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pacing myself in spring training and getting my feet ready  
for the season,'' Salmon said. ``I'm healthy. I feel like I can 
play every day in the outfield. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't plan on being in any part of a rotation in the  
outfield.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the plate, Salmon will hit behind slugger Mo Vaughn in the  
batting order. 
</P>
<P>
	``That spot was tremendous for Nomar Garciaparra the last couple  
of years,'' said Salmon, who batted .300 with 26 home runs and 88 
RBIs last year despite the foot injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll get my swing going, no matter what. If they are going to  
walk Mo and pitch to me, that's fine; I'll take the challenge.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
