<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daly Is Forgotten Tournament's Star  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- No wonder John Daly is fond of the Tucson  
Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the 54-year-old tournament itself, Daly is an afterthought  
as the golfing world focuses its attention on the Andersen 
Consulting World Match Play Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucson is the only PGA Tour event this week, but that didn't  
keep the PGA from scheduling the $5 million match-play event the 
same weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization compensated by contributing $750,000 to the  
Tucson purse. Coupled with the backing of Touchstone Energy, a new 
sponsor, the infusion helped tournament organizers offer a record 
$2.75 million purse with a winner's share of $495,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But that pales with the $1 million awaiting the winner at the La  
Costa Resort and Spa in Carlsbad, Calif., where the top 64 players 
on the World Golf Ranking assembled. That group includes David 
Duval, who becomes only the second defending Tucson champion who 
failed to return the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The first was 1956 winner Ted Kroll, who won the World  
Championship of Golf later that year, and in 1957 skipped Tucson to 
honor contracts to play a series of exhibitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just saddens me that a tournament that's been here this  
long would have La Costa taking it away,'' Daly said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly, a former PGA and British Open champion whose problems with  
alcoholism never seemed to erode his popularity, is easily the 
biggest name in the Tucson field. 
</P>
<P>
	The perennial longest hitter on tour, he is outdriving Tiger  
Woods, who is No. 2 in the category, by 14 yards and the 
fourth-ranked Duval by nearly 23 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	But while Woods and Duval are rated 1-2 the world and are the  
two biggest money-winners this season, Daly's best finish in four 
tournaments was a tie for 14th in Phoenix, and he didn't rank in 
the top 100 -- let alone the top 64 -- when the world-championship 
field was determined. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you, I'd be glad to win here,'' Daly said.  
``Personally, I'd rather be here. It rains there, and there's a lot 
of sunshine here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also in Tucson are former U.S. Open champion Corey Pavin and  
Fuzzy Zoeller, who has a Masters title among his 10 victories. 
</P>
<P>
	In the absence of Duval, Jeff Sluman and Phil Mickelson, who  
account for the last four Tucson titles among them, the hottest 
young entrants are Ted Tryba and David Toms. 
</P>
<P>
	Toms tied Justin Leonard for second last year, and Tryba fired a  
61 last Saturday to lead after three rounds of the Nissan Open. He 
shot par 72 on Sunday to tie Woods and Davis Love III for second. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wasn't disappointed not to be in Carlsbad.  
</P>
<P>
	``They're getting a little free cash and playing for a lot more  
money, but there's a lot of good players in this tournament and I'm 
sure we're going to have a great champion here,'' Tryba said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to Davis Love and Tiger about it, and they hadn't  
played here anyway, so they weren't going to play here 
regardless,'' he went on. ``We're only missing 10 or 15 players 
that are actually in the world championship that would have been 
here, so it's not like they're missing 50 guys.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
