<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilians Show Resentment of IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- When the new Congress convened for  
its opening session this week, the first speech was a warning to 
the International Monetary Fund not to meddle in the nation's 
affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Days earlier, the governor of a Brazilian state joked to  
reporters that he wouldn't visit Brasilia, the capital, if it meant 
sitting in the chair recently occupied by Stanley Fischer, the 
IMF's chief economist. 
</P>
<P>
	As Brazil negotiates with the Washington-based fund for help to  
fix its battered economy, a long-standing resentment of ``yankee'' 
influence is slowly reviving. 
</P>
<P>
	The hostility could make it harder for President Fernando  
Henrique Cardoso to make the budget cuts he promised to the IMF in 
return for a $41.5 billion loan package. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IMF is the scapegoat,'' said Luciano Dias, a political  
scientist with Goes e Consultores Associados in Brasilia. ``It 
crystalizes the popular discontent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The most recent protest came from an unlikely source: Senate  
president Antonio Carlos Magalhaes, a veteran power-broker and 
conservative ally of Cardoso. 
</P>
<P>
	``We understand that the government must go to the IMF, but that  
doesn't mean the IMF can meddle in national problems, especially to 
create difficulties for the poorer classes,'' Magalhaes told the 
new legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	A Rio newspaper columnist wrote his column in English, quipping  
that the local press has the patriotic duty to publish news in 
English so the IMF knows what's going on ``before telling us what 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The resentment stems partly from a common view that the IMF  
teams examining Brazil's economy are number crunchers who care 
little about the people. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics cite the IMF's recipe for the economy: high interest  
rates to curb inflation and spending cuts to reduce the deficit. 
Analysts say the formula spells recession and higher unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund did little to improve its image during a review of the  
loan agreement this month. The IMF released a statement saying it 
supported new Central Bank President Arminio Fraga. But the clumsy 
Portuguese translation read that the fund ``put up with'' Fraga, 
and the press had a field day. 
</P>
<P>
	Anti-IMF sentiment is nothing new. In 1959, Brazil broke off  
negotiations when the fund insisted the government adopt an 
austerity program. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1980s, the government signed nine letters of intent with  
the fund but failed to meet the targets in any of them. Brazilians 
felt humiliated, and graffiti reading ``Fora FMI'' -- or ``Get Out 
IMF'' -- sprouted in cities across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, President Fernando Collor de Mello ordered the  
expulsion of an IMF technician who had the temerity to suggest 
Brazil needed to reduce its budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Cardoso, a former sociology professor and leftist senator,  
was an outspoken critic of the IMF. Now, he's on the other side. 
</P>
<P>
	``The anti-IMF sentiment is really against the fiscal reform,''  
said Dias. ``Cardoso has a very difficult task ahead.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 15:16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Lower; Dow Off 144.75 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks beat a hasty retreat in the final hour of  
trading Wednesday, giving back more than half of Monday's big 
gains, as interest rates rose to the highest level in six months in 
the bond market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average slid 144.75 to close at  
9,399.67, surrendering more than two-thirds of Monday's 212-point 
gain. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow, which slipped 8.26 points on Tuesday, now sits about  
250 points, or 2.5 percent, below the record close of 9,643.32, set 
Jan. 8. Even so, the barometer of 30 major companies still holds a 
gain of 2.4 percent for the new year. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks actually rallied in the morning after a weak opening,  
briefly lifting the Dow over 9,600. The market began retreating by 
late morning however, then staged an outright retreat in the 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although (stock) market internals don't look so bad, the  
weakness in bonds is a problem,'' said Scott Bleier, chief 
investment strategist at Prime Charter. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds fell sharply after the Treasury sold a total of $15  
billion in new, two-year notes at just over 5 percent, a six-month 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year bond fell $10.94 for every $1,000  
valuation. Its yield, which moves opposite the price, unnerved 
investors by moving back above the 5.50 percent level, finishing at 
5.51 percent. The yield, a key influence on borrowing costs for 
consumers and companies, hadn't finished above 5.50 percent since 
Aug. 20 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's rise in interest rates was particularly injurious to  
technology and financial stocks, which had been providing some 
leadership to the upside in recent sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was led lower by Hewlett-Packard, down 2 3/8 at 70 3/4, and  
American Express, down 3 15/16 at 107 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, which briefly pushed into  
record territory earlier in the session, closed 17.77 lower at 
1,253.41. The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was higher 
most of the day, but finally capitulated, too, ending 36.97 lower 
at 2,339.38. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues overtook advancers late in the day on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 946.80 million shares, on 
par with Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The markets weren't helped either by Federal Reserve Chairman  
Alan Greenspan's testimony before a Congressional committee. Making 
his second appearance in two days on Capitol Hill, Greenspan 
reiterated signals that the Fed is more likely to raise interest 
rates over the near term than to shorten them. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said the Fed expects the U.S. economy to slow to a  
growth rate of between 2.5 percent and 3 percent this year, down 
from about 4 percent in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he warned that the economy is ``stretched'' after eight  
years of expansion and suggested the Fed may need to raise interest 
rates to guard against inflation if the economy does not slow as 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock investors would not welcome higher interest rates, which  
would raise corporate borrowing costs and could eat into earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	One bright spot, however, was transportation stocks, which rose  
after Merrill Lynch made Delta Air Lines its ``Focus 1'' stock of 
the week and raised its earnings estimate for the carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta's shares surged 3 1/16 to 61. The Dow Jones transportation  
index, of which Delta is a component, rose 27.89 points, or nearly 
1 percent, to 3,249.60. 
</P>
<P>
	In other market activity, the New York Stock Exchange composite  
index fell 6.45 to 591.57, and the American Stock Exchange 
composite index fell 5.13 to 695.79. The Russell 2000 index of 
smaller companies declined 3.75 to 395.26. 
</P>
<P>
	In overseas stock markets, the Nikkei 225 index in Tokyo dropped  
1 percent. In Europe, London's FTSE 100 index rose 2.5 percent, the 
DAX in Frankfurt added 1.5 percent, and the CAC index in Paris 
climbed 0.14 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
