<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 16:33:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC's Coles in Bribe Controversy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Phil Coles, an International Olympic  
Committee member from Australia, wrote a thank-you note to Salt 
Lake Olympic bid officials who put him up for two weeks at an 
expensive Deer Valley lodge. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter is among proof the Salt Lake Organizing Committee  
plans to produce in the face of Coles' repeated claims he did not 
stay at the Deer Valley lodge over the Christmas holiday in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC says its records show the bid committee paid the  
$9,426.70 tab for Coles at a plush 20-room lodge -- believed to be 
the Goldener Hirsch Inn -- at the ski resort 26 miles east of Salt 
Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles came under scrutiny in a lengthy report Feb. 9 from an  
ethics committee for the Salt Lake committee that said he treated 
his official IOC visits ``like vacations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report said Salt Lake bid boosters paid for four U.S. visits  
by the families of Coles and another IOC member, Willi Kaltschmitt 
of Guatemala. On one of the visits, Coles was treated to a Super 
Bowl game in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has called the allegations unfounded or inaccurate. In  
particular, he has denied staying at the Deer Valley lodge. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Salt Lake committee has receipts to prove it and a  
letter from Coles, who wrote that he ``had a great trip,'' SLOC 
spokeswoman Caroline Shaw said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also has another letter written by former bid  
executive Tom Welch, who wrote that he hoped Coles enjoyed his stay 
at Deer Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaw said the committee was sending copies of all the supporting  
documents, including airline receipts, to Coles and the IOC. The 
material was inadvertently left out of an appendix of the 300-page 
ethics report. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hasn't seen the evidence and we wanted to get it off to  
him,'' said Shaw, who declined to provide copies of the materials. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC members are not supposed to accept gifts worth more than  
$150, and Coles is under investigation by the IOC for possibly 
breaking that rule. Coles stepped down from the organizing 
committee of the 2000 Sydney Games a day after he was named in the 
Salt Lake report. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics report said ``some IOC members treated their site  
visits more like vacations,'' and then discussed the case of the 
Coles and Kaltschmitt families. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Coles and Kaltschmitt families stayed at expensive hotels  
and followed the same recreational itinerary. Two of these trips 
were only four months apart in 1995, including a Super Bowl trip 
that does not appear to have included a visit to Salt Lake City. 
Mr. Welch served as their host at the Super Bowl; the expenses were 
paid as reimbursements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has strongly denounced those allegations and challenged  
Salt Lake officials to produce the documentation. He complained 
that the only thing missing from his media treatment was ``the 
guillotine in the city square.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He repeated his denials Tuesday for The Australian newspaper,  
saying that he and his family spent Christmas 1995 with fellow IOC 
member Jim Eason at Eason's condominium in Deer Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	``We stayed there. We cooked our own meals and did everything  
ourselves, and my records show that,'' Coles said. ``These people 
have got it wrong again.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 19:14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Accused of Undermining Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Human rights groups accused the United  
States Wednesday of trying to undermine the world's first permanent 
war crimes tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States voted against the treaty establishing the  
International Criminal Court last July, but it has the right to 
participate in preparatory meetings for the tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	During the inaugural two-week session, which ends Friday, the  
United States submitted a list of proposed ``elements'' that would 
constitute genocide, war crimes and crimes against humanity. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lawyers Committee for Human Rights accused the United States  
of trying to redefine these international crimes and insert 
elements which would restrict the court's reach. Human Rights Watch 
also warned that Washington is discussing a protocol to weaken the 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is dangerous and harmful to reopen the definition of  
genocide 50 years after the Genocide Convention was adopted.'' 
Michael Posner, the Lawyers Committee's executive director said, 
urging countries to reject the U.S. proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States voted against the treaty because American  
officials felt it yielded too much prosecutorial power to the new 
court, leaving U.S. troops and citizens vulnerable to politically 
motivated prosecutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Program coordinator Jelena Pejic said the committee believes the  
U.S. proposals are designed to achieve what Washington didn't 
achieve in the treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you make the elements more restrictive and make it harder  
for the prosecutor to prove a case, then there's less of a 
likelihood that U.S. soldiers and others will be brought before the 
court. So its part of a systematic pattern to shield U.S. nationals 
from the International Criminal Court,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Scheffer, U.S. ambassador-at-large for war crimes issues,  
called the committee's allegations ``absolutely false and extremely 
misleading.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the United States was working closely with Switzerland,  
which also presented proposals on what elements constitute genocide 
and other crimes, ``to marry our two documents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philippe Kirsch, the preparatory commission chairman, called the  
U.S. proposal ``a very important paper'' and said negotiations 
``are taking place in a positive atmosphere and the United States 
is acting constructively.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
