<DOCNO> APW19990224.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 19:14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *Spencer Martin Allen    	
</P>
<P>
	MERRITT ISLAND, Fla. (AP) -- Spencer Martin Allen, a former TV  
news anchorman and editorialist in St. Louis, Mo., died Tuesday. He 
was 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen began his career at radio stations in Texas and in  
Missouri. He moved to Chicago in 1941 to work at WGN radio. After a 
wartime stint as an Army public relations officer, he rejoined WGN 
and established one of the first local TV news operations. He 
worked there until 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked briefly in Columbus, Ohio, before going to St. Louis  
in 1958 and joining KMOX-TV (now KMOV), where he became news 
director and chief news anchor. In 1964, Allen went to rival KTVI, 
where he stayed for three years before returning to KMOX as 
editorial director. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen, a founding board member of the St. Louis Press Club, also  
was chairman of the National Broadcast Editorial Association and 
the Journalism Foundation of Metropolitan St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	He left television in 1972 to teach at the University of  
Missouri School of Journalism branch in St. Louis. He retired to 
Florida in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include two sons and two grandchildren.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Bill Beers    	
</P>
<P>
	PRESCOTT, Ariz. (AP) -- Bill Beers, an outdoorsman and wildlife  
conservationist who wrote a column for The Daily Courier for years, 
died Friday. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Beers wrote outdoors columns for the Prescott Courier, later The  
Daily Courier, from about 1950 to 1975 and again from 1988 to 1998. 

</P>
<P>
                               *Biki    	
</P>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- Biki, a Milan designer who opened a fashion  
atelier in 1936 and went on to create outfits for opera diva Maria 
Callas and others, died Tuesday of the flu and bronchitis. She was 
92. 
</P>
<P>
	Biki, born Elvira Leonardi, was known abroad, especially in  
Japan, where she opened a shop with the Japanese in 1969. Other 
well-known clients included Esther Williams, the American swimmer 
and film star, and French actress Jeanne Moreau. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was her work for Callas that gave Biki her biggest fame.  
She reportedly numbered the clothes and accessories so the soprano 
would know how to best put them together for an elegant look. 
</P>
<P>
	She also designed for many of the women who frequented the  
circle of Gabriele D'Annunzio, the Italian poet and soldier. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, she designed a children's collection that sold abroad.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Roger Boka    	
</P>
<P>
	HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Roger Boka, a leading African black  
empowerment advocate whose bank collapsed last year amid 
questionable practices, died Sunday at age 54. 
</P>
<P>
	He died aboard a private jet as it approached Harare's airport.  
His daughter, Rudo, said Boka was returning from the United States 
where he sought treatment. She would not specify the illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Boka was wanted for questioning over the alleged illegal  
transfer abroad of $25 million from his collapsed United Merchant 
Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Boka's bank offered loans to blacks at favorable terms and  
accused multinational banks of discriminating against black 
entrepreneurs who lacked collateral. 
</P>
<P>
	Boka's bank collapsed after it allegedly sold faked bonds,  
purportedly to raise capital for a state-owned slaughter and meat 
processing firm. 

</P>
<P>
                           *William Bronk    	
</P>
<P>
	HUDSON FALLS, N.Y. (AP) -- William Bronk, an award-winning poet  
who wrote a poem for former New York governor Mario Cuomo's first 
inauguration, died Monday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Bronk first gained national attention when he won the American  
Book Award for Poetry in 1982 for ``Life Supports,'' a compilation 
of poems he'd written over 32 years. He wrote about things he 
encountered in his daily life. 
</P>
<P>
	Bronk said in an interview that he first declined to write the  
poem ``Waterland,'' for Cuomo's inauguration. But after jotting 
down a few lines and giving the idea some thought, he changed his 
mind. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Dennis Cassano    	
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Dennis Cassano, a longtime reporter for the  
Star Tribune, died Monday of cancer. He was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a beat reporter, he covered everything from city government  
and the criminal justice system to issues of urban sprawl,'' said 
Joe Rigert, a reporter who worked with Cassano for nearly 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Cassano joined the Minneapolis Tribune, the Star Tribune's  
predecessor, in 1969. His most recent assignment was covering 
suburban news. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Nancy; two sons; a daughter; and a  
sister. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Virginia Foster Durr    	
</P>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Virginia Foster Durr, a Southern  
belle-turned-New Deal liberal who helped Rosa Parks get out of 
jail, died Wednesday in her sleep. She was 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Durr and her late husband, civil rights attorney Clifford  
Durr, bailed Mrs. Parks out of jail in 1955 after she was arrested 
for refusing to give up her seat to a white man on Montgomery's 
segregated city buses. The arrest prompted a bus boycott that 
propelled Martin Luther King Jr. to leadership and helped start the 
civil rights movement. 
</P>
<P>
	A close friend of Mrs. Parks, Mrs. Durr was viewed by many as  
the white matron of a movement Mrs. Parks inspired. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Durr began rebelling against Old South ways while in  
college at Wellesley. She helped fight racist poll taxes, supported 
New Deal programs and backed the civil rights movement. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Durr never held public office, but made a losing bid for  
the Senate as a Progressive Party candidate in Virginia. She was an 
engaging and inspirational figure for movement veterans as well as 
powerful figures in Washington. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Carlos Hathcock II    	
</P>
<P>
	VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) -- Retired Gunnery Sgt. Carlos Hathcock  
II, who killed 93 enemy soldiers as a Marine sniper in Vietnam and 
was awarded a Silver Star for saving seven Americans after a mine 
explosion, died Monday of multiple sclerosis. He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sept. 16, 1969, Hathcock was riding an amphibious assault  
vehicle when it ran over a Vietnamese mine and exploded. Hathcock 
was sprayed with flaming gasoline and severely injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Although writhing in pain from burns to his face, arms, legs and  
body and at great risk from exploding ammunition, Hathcock went 
back into the flames and dragged seven Marines from the vehicle. He 
was awarded the Silver Star, the military's third-highest 
decoration, in November 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The burns ended Hathcock's combat career, but he remained in the  
service until retiring in 1979. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Sir Anthony Nutting    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir Anthony Nutting, who resigned from the  
government in 1956 because he felt he could not defend Britain's 
Suez Canal policy, died Tuesday at age 79. The cause of death was 
not announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Nutting was a Foreign Office minister in Sir Anthony Eden's  
government when the Suez crisis broke in 1956. 
</P>
<P>
	Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser nationalized the canal in  
July 1956. When negotiations for a diplomatic settlement failed, 
Eden's government secretly agreed with France and Israel on a plan 
to retake the canal. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan was for Israel to attack Egypt, which it did on Oct.  
29, 1956. Britain and France then moved to seize the canal on Nov. 
5 on the pretext of separating the combatants. 
</P>
<P>
	Facing opposition from the United States, Britain and France  
agreed to withdraw in favor of a U.N. peacekeeping force. The 
debacle shattered Eden's career, and he resigned in January 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	Nutting resigned his ministerial post on Oct. 31, 1956, saying  
he was not prepared to lie to defend the policy, and quit the House 
of Commons later the same year. He told his side of the story in 
his book, ``No End of a Lesson,'' published in 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	He succeeded to the baronetcy when his father died in 1972.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 15:34:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Oust American 'Bud' Brand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Switzerland's highest court has ruled  
against U.S.-brewed ``Bud'' beer in a battle over the Budweiser and 
Bud trade names, according to a report being published Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri-based Anheuser-Busch took its case to the Federal  
Tribunal in late 1997 after a trade tribunal ruled against its 
``Bud'' beer. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribunal said the U.S. beer should not be sold as ``Bud'' in  
Switzerland because of a risk of confusion with the name 
``Budweiser,'' claimed by state-owned Czech brewer Budejovicky 
Budvar. 
</P>
<P>
	Switzerland's Supreme Court has upheld that decision, the Zurich  
weekly Cash reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch chief executive and president Stephen J. Burrows  
said the ruling would not affect the company's pending trademark 
case against Budvar outside of Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	The two brewers have been claiming rights to the Budweiser name  
since 1911. 
</P>
<P>
	The Czech brewery exports to 37 countries, mainly in Europe. Its  
St. Louis-based rival is the world's biggest brewer and has sales 
in more than 70 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The German immigrants who founded Anheuser-Busch in 1876 used  
the Budweiser name for their beer because it was well-known in 
their homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	Budweis is the German name for the original brewery's hometown,  
Ceske Budejovice, now in the Czech Republic. The Czechs say 
``Budweiser'' describes the beer and the area, in the same way 
Burgundy and Champagne describe wines and wine-making regions in 
France. 
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch still holds unchallenged rights to the Budweiser  
name in most of the world, including North and South America and 
virtually all of Asia. Some European countries have ruled in its 
favor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will continue to market our brand under a new name using  
the same label format to protect our sales base in Switzerland, 
which is less than 1 percent of our European sales,'' Burrows said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an unfortunate decision because Anheuser-Busch has  
been brewing Budweiser since 1876, long before Budvar was founded 
in 1895.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1997 ruling, the Swiss trade tribunal said its verdict  
was based on Anheuser-Busch's 1983 removal of the name 
``Budweiser'' from the Swiss register of brand names, following a 
Czech protest. No mention was made of ``Bud.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 12:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Suttons Give Opponents Double Vision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Amy Sutton is No. 11, the shooting  
guard with the tan religious bracelet. Jill Sutton is No. 12, the 
point guard who wears a blue one. 
</P>
<P>
	That's all the help you get trying to distinguish the identical  
twin sophomore starters for Texas Christian. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sutton sisters provide the Horned Frogs (15-9, 7-5 Western  
Athletic Conference) with a quality backcourt. Combined, they 
average 25.3 of the team's 76.6 points per game. Individually, Amy 
scores 14.4 points and Jill averages 11. 
</P>
<P>
	They are among at least 17 sets of twins playing Division I  
women's basketball. While Kelly and Coco Miller of No. 14 Georgia 
may be the best, it's hard to imagine any two who are closer than 
the Suttons. 
</P>
<P>
	The 19-year-olds live together, take the same classes and are  
best friends. They're both early risers and don't like to stay out 
late. 
</P>
<P>
	They're both good students who share the same major: education.  
Both aspire to become basketball coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	They have a joint checking account and share all their clothes.  
That's why they don't see a need to exchange birthday or Christmas 
gifts -- a plan that makes perfect sense to them but bewilders their 
friends. 
</P>
<P>
	They are so devoted to remaining mirror images that if one wants  
a new hairstyle, the other does the same to avoid the chance ``one 
of us will look bad,'' Amy says. 
</P>
<P>
	Although both are quick to smile, their personalities differ  
somewhat. They don't always like the same music or laugh at the 
same jokes. Amy, who is older by less than a minute, is more 
talkative. 
</P>
<P>
	But the similarities far outweigh the differences.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're not real outgoing without each other, so I guess it's  
good that we've always had each other so we'll have at least one 
friend around,'' Jill says, laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	The farthest apart they've been is 1,000 miles for 17 hours --  
four months ago, Amy was on campus while Jill represented TCU at 
the WAC media day in Las Vegas. Jill was invited because she had 
the better freshman year. Amy, though, is doing better this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Both take losing hard, even to each other. Asked what they  
compete at, they quickly said: ``Everything.'' In unison. 
</P>
<P>
	``Amy and Jill have always pushed each other,'' said their  
mother, Brenda Hankey. ``The thing I was always thankful for is 
that they were always so close, in their grades and in their 
abilities in basketball. They were never jealous of each other. 
They've always supported each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Out of uniform and without their bracelets -- emblazoned with  
``WWJD'' for ``What Would Jesus Do?'' -- it's practically impossible 
tell who's who. They're used to being asked, ``Which one are you?'' 
and almost always give the real answer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone asks us if it bothers us,'' Amy says. ``But it  
doesn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once in high school they switched classes, only to be given away  
by their classmates' giggles. They haven't tried anything since, 
but they are plotting a prank on their teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``They think they know how to tell us apart,'' Amy says. ``We'll  
have to do a little test to see just how well they know us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opposing coaches and referees need not fear. The Suttons promise  
they won't switch jerseys at the start of the WAC tournament or at 
halftime of a game when one is in foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Their word will have to do because even their playing styles are  
similar. Amy is probably a slightly better rebounder, Jill the 
better passer. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 5-foot-9 guards both dribble well with either hand and  
neither can be left alone from the outside. Jill set the school 
freshman record with 34 points last year; Amy set the school record 
with 39 points this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Both wear knee pads because they play so aggressively. Amy also  
has worn a mouthpiece since getting a tooth knocked out at last 
year's WAC tournament; Jill started wearing one, too, but recently 
gave it up. 
</P>
<P>
	On the court together, a sixth sense seems at work.  
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of feel like Amy knows that if she wants to cut to the  
basket, I'll throw it to her,'' Jill says. ``We're thinking on the 
same level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amy and Jill have always been basketball junkies. Growing up in  
Gunter, a town of about 840 roughly 25 miles south of the 
Texas-Oklahoma border, their activities centered around church, 
school and basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever since they've been big enough to even bounce a  
basketball, they have,'' says their stepfather, Don Hankey, a 
former coach in Durant, Okla. ``Where most girls push dolls, they 
pushed basketballs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In second grade, it quickly became obvious they were special.  
They competed in boys' leagues and made all-star teams, then became 
four-year starters at their Class 2A high school. 
</P>
<P>
	Gunter went 132-9 with the Suttons in the lineup, reaching the  
state tournament in their sophomore, junior and senior seasons. 
They lost in the finals as juniors and fell in the semifinals the 
other two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were devastated when they lost that last one,'' says  
their mother. ``They started crying the instant we started to walk 
out the gym, knowing they wouldn't have another chance to come 
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Summers were spent traveling on AAU teams, wowing college  
scouts. Recruiters were told in advance to offer two scholarships 
or none. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was too important for them to be together, even if that  
meant playing Division II or going to a junior college,'' their 
mother says. ``But from the first day, from the way our phone was 
ringing, it was obvious that plenty of people were interested in 
taking them both.'' 
</P>
<P>
	TCU beat about 25 schools, in part because it's a 1 1/2-hour drive  
from Gunter. 
</P>
<P>
	The sisters know they'll be together two more years, but they  
also know that eventually they must go their separate ways. 
</P>
<P>
	The odds of being teammates on a pro team are quite long. They  
could be in different leagues, different countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our Mom is real worried about that,'' Jill says.  
</P>
<P>
	Wherever they end up, the sisters don't expect to be far apart.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'll probably always live near each other, in the same  
vicinity,'' Jill says. ``It's not like we're going to move across 
the country from each other. In the same state at least.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their mother figures that even though they spend so much time  
playing basketball and so little time dating, a boyfriend will 
eventually break them up. 
</P>
<P>
	And for that guy, she has one piece of advice: ``Good luck to  
the men that do the separating.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 12:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Suttons Give Opponents Double Vision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Amy Sutton is No. 11, the shooting  
