<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broadcasters Plan To Sue DirecTV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Broadcasters want a court to immediately stop  
the nation's largest satellite TV company from beaming CBS and Fox 
programs to its customers. 
</P>
<P>
	DirecTV Inc. on Thursday plans to directly offer customers  
nationwide the option of buying a new package of broadcast network 
stations, including CBS and Fox affiliates. 
</P>
<P>
	By dumping its supplier, PrimeTime 24, and directly offering the  
network programs itself, DirecTV contends it is not affected by a 
federal court order that would cut customers off from CBS and Fox 
signals on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	But broadcasters disagree, calling DirecTV's plans ``a brazen  
attempt to ignore'' the court order issued last year by a federal 
judge in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	All four major broadcast networks -- CBS, Fox, ABC and NBC -- and  
their affiliates intend to seek a court order to block DirecTV from 
continuing to provide customers with CBS and Fox, the National 
Association of Broadcasters said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broadcasters' suit, which was to be filed Wednesday, will  
ask the judge to act on their request by Thursday, said broadcast 
officials, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	DirecTV's announcement Tuesday was the latest twist in a fight  
between satellite companies and broadcasters over how viewers who 
get their TV from satellite can watch networks' local affiliates. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law allows DirecTV and other satellite companies to  
provide ``distant'' network signals -- which come from other 
broadcast areas -- to customers only if those customers can't 
receive their local stations using rooftop antennas. 
</P>
<P>
	But satellite and broadcasting industries have been at odds for  
years over how to interpret an arcane legal test for determining 
when a satellite customer can't get a local signal. 
</P>
<P>
	DirecTV maintains it can offer the Fox and CBS affiliates  
because the federal court order with a Sunday deadline applies only 
to the company's former programming supplier, PrimeTime 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if DirecTV's plans prevail, several hundred thousand  
satellite customers nationwide are still supposed to be cut off 
from Fox and CBS programs on Sunday under the court order obtained 
by the networks last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Hewitt, president of the Satellite Broadcasting and  
Communications Association, believes many of these satellite 
customers to be cut off from the signals can't receive a decent 
picture from their local Fox or CBS stations on their antennas. 
</P>
<P>
	Reps. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., and Billy Tauzin, R-La., intend to  
introduce legislation Thursday that would permit satellite 
customers cut off from CBS and Fox on Sunday to once again receive 
the signals but only for three months, said Tauzin's spokesman, Ken 
Johnson. During that period, Congress would try to pass legislation 
to resolve the problem, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	DirecTV, meanwhile, said it will determine whether customers  
buying its distant network programming can receive a local station 
on their antenna. If so, they'll be cut off from that network's 
distant signal. 
</P>
<P>
	Another order by the same court will cut off an additional 1.5  
million customers from CBS and Fox signals by April 30. Both 
injunctions are against PrimeTime 24 for allegedly violating 
copyright law and do not affect NBC, ABC or other networks' 
affiliates. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
