<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Lead Board of Trade Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures prices plummeted Wednesday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, with soybeans falling to levels not seen 
since the 1970s, on the worsening of an already dim outlook for 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, pork futures prices sank, as did orange juice.  
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans tumbled amid reports buyers of competing palm oil and  
Brazilian soybean oil had canceled deliveries, an indication that 
demand for U.S. products will not brighten for some time. 
</P>
<P>
	With prices continuing to sink across the globe, analysts said  
it is likely that people who ordered soybean products a few weeks 
ago at prices that were 20 percent higher than current levels would 
cancel those deals and wait for the market to bottom out. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices already had been pummeled amid government  
predictions that demand from the important Asian region will remain 
weak through yearend, a huge problem given that Argentina and 
Brazil are getting ready to harvest bumper competing crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Even more vexing to traders are forecasts that American farmers  
will plant record soybean acreage this spring, since that would 
still be a better alternative to planting low-priced corn, wheat 
and other crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat sank as traders eyed extremely low prices offered by  
competing French exporters for an Egyptian purchase. That 
reinforced views that prices must go much lower to stimulate demand 
for exports and for use in animal feeds as an alternative to corn. 
</P>
<P>
	Egypt is one of the United States' best customers for wheat, but  
it has continually bypassed American exporters in favor of cheaper 
European or Australian wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures retreated in sympathy with the plunging wheat and  
soybean prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for March delivery fell 7 1/2 cents to $2.44 1/4 a bushel; March  
oats fell 6 1/4 cents to $2.08 3/4 a bushel; March oats fell 1 3/4 cents to 
$1.00 1/2 a bushel; March soybeans fell 16 1/2 cents to $4.57 1/2 a bushel, 
the lowest since late 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures tumbled on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange amid  
expectations improving weather conditions would lead to more 
marketings during a period of lower demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of Nebraska and Iowa, the nation's largest hog-producing  
state, suffered from heavy snow earlier this week, sharply reducing 
the number of slaughter-ready pigs coming to market. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle fell 0.17 cent to 67.45 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle fell 0.40 cent to 73.57 cents a pound; April lean 
hogs fell 1.83 cents to 43.42 cents a pound; March pork bellies 
fell 1.95 cents to 50.85 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Frozen, concentrated orange juice futures retreated on the Board  
of Trade of the City of New York amid concern about weak demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were concerned that with the peak winter consumption  
period winding down, there will be fewer takers of orange juice, in 
which there are ample inventories. While Florida, the nation's 
biggest grower, is expected to produce a smaller crop this year, 
the figure is down only 20 percent from a record crop a year 
earlier leaving ample supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	May orange juice fell 1.55 cents, or 1.8 percent, to 84.95 cents  
a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
