<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stocks Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian share prices ended mixed on Wednesday, as  
markets failed to find clear direction from U.S. Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan's hints of a possible restrictive monetary 
policy in the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, a weak futures market dragged down share prices, while  
the U.S. dollar edged up higher against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 145.20 points,  
or 1.00 percent, closing the day at 14,355.45. The average rose 
243.98, or 1.71 percent, on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan spoke before the U.S. Congress on Tuesday, saying a  
``surprisingly robust'' U.S. economy should continue growing this 
year but at a much slower pace than in 1998. Greenspan was to 
deliver the second part of his speech late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo was for the most part neutral over Greenspan's comments.  
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei slipped amid ``speculative movement in the futures  
market'' with heavy selling toward the end of the session, said 
Kiyoshi Kimura of Societe Generale Securities in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar bought 121.36 yen in late  
afternoon trading, up 1.02 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also 
above its late New York level of 120.81 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's comments on Wednesday had  
decidedly more impact than Greenspan's. Obuchi said the government 
was ``paying close attention to currency moves and will respond at 
the right time in the right way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such remarks often refer to intervention by Japan's central bank  
in currency markets. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kong Kong, shares rose for a second consecutive session amid  
strong buying of HSBC Holdings PLC, the banking group that is the 
biggest company listed in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue chip Hang Seng Index jumped 243.58 points, or 2.6  
percent, to 9,677.57. The index had gained 204.65 points, or 2.2 
percent, on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	News on Monday that the bank plans a Wall Street listing and  
plans to buy back its own shares in the Hong Kong market helped 
fuel interest in the shares. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares rose on late buying in shares of major  
commercial banks. The SET index rose 2.46 points, or 0.73 percent, 
to close at 336.17. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares rose amid heavy buying in in tobacco and mining  
shares. The JSX Composite Index rose 4.063 points, or 1 percent, to 
close at 401.998 points. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares fell on concerns over corporate earnings.  
The Composite Index fell 9.66 points, or 1.7 percent, to close at 
553.13 points. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares fell as investors locked in profits after two  
consecutive days of gains. The PSE index fell 24.59 points, or 1.3 
percent, to close at 1,934.11. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares rose on gains in banking, finance and diversified  
resources sectors. The All Ordinaries rose 10.15 points, or 0.4 
percent, to close at 2,934.5. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares fell on worries over labor unrest. The KOSPI fell  
4.46 points, or 0.8 percent, to close at 498.42. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose on foreign-led buying towards the close  
of trading. The STI index rose 10.55 points, or 0.75 percent, to 
close at 1,410.98. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares rose following the government's recent  
market-boosting measures. The Weighted Price Index rose 57.93 
points, or 0.93 percent, to close at 6,238.87. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares fell following a slide in forestry sector  
stocks. The NZSE-40 capital index fell 28.21 points, or 1.3 
percent, to close at 2,206.22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
