<DOCNO> APW19990224.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:44:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Trials Might Trip First Lady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For all the current excitement of a possible  
Senate bid, Hillary Rodham Clinton also faces unwelcome attention 
in federal courtrooms from a familiar problem: Whitewater. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is referred to 36 times in a fraud indictment  
against her former law partner, Webster Hubbell, signifying that 
her name will be brought up repeatedly in her old friend's trial, 
scheduled to begin June 14. She could even be called as a witness. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady's name also could come up in next month's  
criminal contempt trial of former Whitewater partner Susan 
McDougal, who is accused of obstructing Independent Counsel Kenneth 
Starr's investigation. The indictment against Mrs. McDougal details 
a series of grand jury questions about Mrs. Clinton that Mrs. 
McDougal refused to answer. 
</P>
<P>
	Political scientist Larry Sabato of the University of Virginia  
sees a series of obstacles in Mrs. Clinton's potential run for a 
New York Senate seat. 
</P>
<P>
	``She will be target No. 1 not just for the New York press corps  
but for, as Mrs. Clinton calls it, `the vast right-wing 
conspiracy,''' Sabato said. ``The truth is that over the past six 
years she has been at least a peripheral figure in many of the 
Clinton administration scandals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hubbell trial could present an especially serious political  
and legal problem for Mrs. Clinton. She could be called as a 
witness, either by Starr's prosecutors or Hubbell's defense team. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr alleges Hubbell concealed his and Mrs. Clinton's work  
during the 1980s on a failed Arkansas land deal known as Castle 
Grande that federal regulators say was riddled with ``insider 
dealing, fictitious sales and land flips.'' The Clintons' 
Whitewater partner, Jim McDougal, tried to sell off pieces of 
Castle Grande to prop up his collapsing savings and loan. The 
indictment against Mrs. McDougal contains questions about Mrs. 
Clinton and Castle Grande. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Hubbell case, ``it seems that one side or the other's got  
to call Mrs. Clinton as a witness because if she's inextricably 
bound up in these affairs, she's got information that one side or 
the other would want,'' said George Washington University law 
professor Mary Cheh. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hubbell trial could inject an unpleasant issue into any  
Senate campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``The minute she runs, all that stuff is coming back,'' said  
Democratic political consultant Vic Kamber. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Clinton political consultant Dick Morris suggests the  
first lady should postpone running for office until 2004, when 
``she will be able to confront doubters and accusers with a clean 
bill of health.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For next year, said Morris, ``one can imagine a situation where  
Hubbell is convicted and questions linger about Hillary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr would have to weigh the risks of calling Mrs. Clinton as a  
witness before a jury in the District of Columbia, where the ratio 
of Democrats to Republicans is more than 10-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell's lawyers might call her to the stand if Starr doesn't.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a way to bring in a popular witness for the defense and a  
potential character witness, but once they put Hubbell's character 
into evidence, he does get opened up and he's got a lot of 
baggage,'' said St. John's University law professor John Barrett. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton testified by videotape before a grand jury  
investigating Castle Grande last year. In 1996, she appeared before 
Starr's grand jury in Washington to discuss the still-unexplained 
discovery of her billing records revealing her work on Castle 
Grande. The records had vanished after the 1992 presidential 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Confronted with the billing records, Mrs. Clinton said she was  
unable to recall her legal work in 1985 and 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	A part-owner of the Castle Grande development, Hubbell's  
father-in-law, Seth Ward, collected $300,000 from McDougal's S&AMP;L. 
The billing records identify 15 conversations between Mrs. Clinton 
and Ward, but both say they don't remember them. 
</P>
<P>
	The development ended up costing the S&AMP;L $3.8 million in unpaid  
principal and interest, according to federal regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell, the No. 3 Justice Department official during Clinton's  
first term, pleaded guilty to tax evasion and mail fraud in 1994 
and promised to fully cooperate with Starr. He served a year and a 
half in prison. Suspicious that Hubbell was withholding 
information, Starr began investigating him again in 1996, trying to 
determine whether Hubbell was being paid ``hush'' money to 
stonewall Starr's investigation of the Clintons. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the Castle Grande case, Hubbell now also faces  
new tax evasion charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 16:13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lauryn Hill Seeks Record 10 Grammys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lauryn Hill won the Grammy for best rhythm  
and blues song for ``Doo Wop (That Thing)'' and Shania Twain and 
husband Robert John ``Mutt'' Lange were honored for writing the 
country song ``You're Still the One'' in pre-telecast awards 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill led a parade of women up for awards, with 10 nominations.  
She lost one category in the pre-telecast show when non-classical 
producer of the year went to Rob Cavallo, who worked with the Goo 
Dolls, Green Day and Alanis Morrisette. 
</P>
<P>
	Twain and Lange, who had 11 nominations between them, won best  
country song for ``You're Still the One,'' a slick, poplike 
relationship song. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Titanic'' ballad ``My Heart Will Go On'' earned honors for  
James Horner and Will Jennings. It was named best song written for 
a motion picture or television. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, 23, and her acclaimed album ``The Miseducation of Lauryn  
Hill'' had a chance to win the most Grammys ever by a female 
artist. Carole King won four in 1971 for ``Tapestry.'' Michael 
Jackson holds the overall record of eight. 
</P>
<P>
	No hip-hop artist has won album of the year, a category  
dominated this year by women. Other contenders: Sheryl Crow's ``The 
Globe Sessions,'' Madonna's ``Ray of Light,'' Twain for ``Come on 
Over,'' and ``Version 2.0'' by alternative rocker Garbage, led by 
singer Shirley Manson. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Grammy voters shattered their penchant for mainstream  
best sellers by naming Bob Dylan's ``Time Out of Mind'' as best 
album. Some hoped that would pave the way for Hill's stylish social 
commentary to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Crow, a five-time Grammy winner in recent years, and country-pop  
crossover sensation Twain received six nominations each. Madonna's 
five nominations gave her a chance to win her first musical Grammy. 
She picked up a video award in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Women also dominated the record of the year category. Madonna's  
``Ray of Light'' and Twain's ``You're Still the One'' were up 
against Brandy &AMP; Monica (``The Boy Is Mine''), Celine Dion (``My 
Heart Will Go On'') and the lone male entry, ``Iris,'' by the Goo 
Dolls. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnny Cash, Mel Torme, Smokey Robinson and the late Sam Cooke  
and Otis Redding each received lifetime achievement awards from the 
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences at the 41st annual 
Grammy Awards. Rosie O'Donnell served as master of ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	The songwriting teams of Alan Jay Lerner and Frederick Loewe,  
Kenneth Gamble and Leon Huff, and Jerry Leiber and Mike Stoller 
were honored with trustees' awards for outstanding contributions by 
nonperformers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
