<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Torre Signs Extension Through 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- The long expected two-year contract extension  
for New York Yankees manager Joe Torre has be finalized. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously I'm happy it happened, but it happened a long time  
ago ... I just didn't get around to signing it,'' Torre said. ``We 
had agreed to it, probably, during the World Series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal with owner George Steinbrenner, worth about $2 million  
a year, covers 2000 and 2001. While leaning toward stepping down 
when the new deal expires, Torre has not ruled out a longer stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see it going past what my contract is now -- but you  
never now. As long as it's fun,'' Torre said. ``That's my end of 
it. Now you have to ask George the same question.' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 08:46:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise a Bit; Dow Up 11.19 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were moderately higher at mid-morning,  
after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan reiterated his view 
that even though growth in the U.S. economy is likely to slow 
mildly in 1999, he remains worried that it could overheat. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 11.19 at 9,555.61. The Dow peaked just over 9,600, up 55 points, 
before trimming its gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was up 5.64 at 1,276.82, and the technology-heavy Nasdaq 
composite index was up 8.69 at 2,385.04. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6 to 5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 212.1 million shares, 
well below Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan, making his second appearance in two days on Capitol  
Hill, hewed close to the remarks he made Tuesday, when he gave the 
Senate Finance Committee signals that he was leaning toward raising 
interest rates eventually. Today the Fed chairman was speaking 
before the House Banking Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said the Fed expects the U.S. economy to slow to a  
growth rate of between 2.5 percent and 3 percent this year, down 
from about 4 percent in 1998. But, he added that the economy is 
``stretched'' after eight years of expansion and suggested the Fed 
may need to raise interest rates if the economy does not slow as 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks again led the market. IBM was up 3/4 at 43 7/8.  
America Online led the NYSE trading in volume and was up 1 15/16 at 
89 15/16. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
