<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Ghanaian Leader Seek Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton offered his support  
Wednesday for black Americans seeking dual citizenship with Ghana 
and made his own overture at cross-cultural relations: a White 
House state dinner laced with the colors and flavors of the African 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The dinner honoring Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings topped a  
day of talks between the two leaders in which Clinton said the 
Ghanaian parliament had ``a clever idea'' in extending dual 
citizenship to black American descendants of African slaves. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Ghana does this, it certainly won't hurt in trying to get  
more Americans interested in Ghana, going to Ghana and contributing 
to Ghana's future,'' said Clinton, who was the first American 
president ever to visit Ghana. 
</P>
<P>
	``My continent is the mother not of all continents, but humanity  
today,'' Rawlings said at a news conference. ``There is no reason 
why I would deny my fellow black African the right to enjoy the 
same citizenship that I enjoy as an African.'' 

</P>
<P>
	A tribute to Rawlings Wednesday night provided another  
opportunity for the two leaders to emphasize the ties between their 
nations and the areas in which such alliances could grow. 
</P>
<P>
	That Ghana was the first stop on Clinton's tour of Africa was no  
accident, the president said in his toast. 
</P>
<P>
	It ``allowed us to highlight for all Americans the progress  
Africa has made and the promise of our future together,'' the 
president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings echoed the sentiments, but stressed that the future of  
this partnership would also hinge on such issues as trade and 
regional stability. 
</P>
<P>
	He shared his conviction ``that Ghana can be secure and  
prosperous only when Africa is secure and prosperous'' and called 
on the United States and the international community to act 
decisively in promoting stability in all African nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Conflicts in some African regions warrant the kind of  
international concern and involvement shown to problems in Kosovo, 
the Balkans and the Middle East, Rawlings said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Clinton said he would support ``whatever  
necessary force'' is required to ensure peace in the Congo region, 
which has been seized for months by civil war. He did not commit 
himself to the idea of offering soldiers, but said the United 
States would take part, if asked, in ``an internationally 
recognized'' peacekeeping effort. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, who was in town meeting with  
congressional leaders on such issues as U.S. arrears to the United 
Nations, attended the dinner. Annan also used his Washington visit 
to discuss with leaders the need for more international 
peacekeeping in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very pleased with the discussions,'' Annan said Wednesday  
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Other guests celebrated the growing alliance between the two  
nations and their respective leaders. Poet Maya Angelou called the 
tribute ``fitting'' for ``two young men that have great hope for 
their countries. They both are courageous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Susan Taylor, editor-in-chief of Essence Magazine, said she  
considers Ghana a second home and owns property there. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if she would consider taking up the offer of dual  
citizenship, she responded: ``Absolutely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the evening, White House chefs prepared an ice cream dessert  
flavored with mango and pineapple -- two of Ghana's favorite fruits 
-- and decorated with a traditional kente sash. 
</P>
<P>
	Worn by noblemen and kings in Ghana and used for ceremonies, the  
kente cloth is also one of the most famous products from the 
hometown of Rawlings' wife -- Nana Konadu Agyeman-Rawlings. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of her official state gift, Ms. Agyeman-Rawlings  
presented Mrs. Clinton with three framed pieces of the Ghanaian 
cloth. She also gave the first lady a necklace made of yellow 
stones, which Mrs. Clinton wore when the two women had coffee 
earlier in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings offered Clinton a symbol of authority -- an Ashanti  
stool -- as his official gift. 
</P>
<P>
	Covered in deep green-colored damask tablecloths, the East Room  
dinner tables featured floral arrangements of cream and red roses, 
flowering quince branches, rose colored tulips and white lilacs. 
Gold candles in gold candlesticks surrounded the flowers so that 
the centerpiece gave off hints of gold, red and green -- the colors 
of the Ghanaian flag. 
</P>
<P>
	Place settings featured Eisenhower gold base plates and gold  
flatware from the Vermeil Collection, with the FDR china reserved 
for dinner service. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200 dinners guests were to feast on a dinner ``hinting  
at the first harbingers of spring,'' said executive chef Walter 
Scheib. Grilled yellow tail snapper, one of the main entrees, 
offers a sure sign that warmer weather is about to come, Scheib 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
