<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Hospital Plan Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration's proposed year  
2000 budget for veterans hospitals fails to keep pace with the 
costs of medicine and medical center payrolls and will force the 
hospitals to scale back services, system officials and veterans 
complained Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Administering this budget would be like trying to build a  
house of cards in an Oklahoma tornado,'' recently retired Veterans 
Health Administration official Tom Trujillo told the House 
Veterans' Affairs subcommittee on health. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would have to have large reductions in force and close  
numerous facilities to live within this budget,'' he said. ``We 
have stretched ourselves way too thin and are ready to snap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trujillo was joined at the hearing by current regional directors  
of the system who agreed with his assessment but didn't describe 
the situation as colorfully. 
</P>
<P>
	Veterans groups offered their own denunciations.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is unfair that in the presence of the largest budget  
surplus in recent history, while other federal agencies will have 
double-digit increases, veterans are being asked to once again 
sacrifice,'' said the Veterans of Foreign Wars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paralyzed Veterans of America accused the Clinton  
administration of crafting a budget that kills the VA health system 
``through intentional budget strangulation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers also piled on.  
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody on either side of the aisle likes this budget. This  
budget does stink,'' said Rep. Mike Doyle, D-Pa. ``I don't know how 
we can flat-line a budget from 1997 to 2002 and not expect the 
system to collapse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Under Secretary for Health Thomas Garthwaite said the  
administration was aware of ``significant financial challenges 
ahead,'' but that plans still were being formulated to prepare for 
the possibility that Congress might not add extra money to the 
administration's spending request. 
</P>
<P>
	The veterans' organizations made public an internal Department  
of Veterans Affairs memo written by Under Secretary Kenneth Kizer, 
who heads the hospital system. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we are in a serious and precarious situation and  
that if we do not institute these difficult changes in a timely 
manner, then we face the very real prospect of far more problematic 
decisions, e.g. mandatory employee furloughs, severe curtailment of 
services or elimination of programs, and possible unnecessary 
facility closures,'' Kizer wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Around the country, James Farsetta, director of the VA region  
that operates seven medical centers in New Jersey and southern New 
York, said he has already submitted a request to eliminate 400 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	William Galey, who oversees services in Alaska, Washington,  
Oregon and Idaho, told the subcommittee he's considering staff 
reductions of anywhere from 300 to 800. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Miller, whose region encompasses Ohio and northern  
Kentucky, said the no-growth budget proposal has her bracing for a 
cut of 200 positions next year, most likely achieved by closing 
hospital wards and suspending plans for new outpatient clinics. 
</P>
<P>
	``When your drug costs go up 15 percent a year and employee  
salaries go up 4 percent a year and our employees are 70 percent of 
our budget, at some point there are choices that have to be made,'' 
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
