<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United States 3, Finland 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The U.S. women's soccer team, featuring a  
lineup of primarily young players, defeated Finland 3-1 Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six players made their international debuts and two Americans  
scored their first international goals as the United States built a 
3-0 lead before allowing a late goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Jen Grubb opened the scoring in the seventh minute with a  
thundering free kick that hit the left goalpost and bounced in from 
25 yards. It was Grubb's second international goal in 12 matches. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team scored again off a corner kick in the 17th minute.  
Michelle French sent a cross to Samantha Baggett, who met the ball 
with a glancing header that went in from 10 yards. The goal was 
Baggett's first in international play and came in just her second 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Beth Keller, a sophomore midfielder from Clemson University,  
scored her first goal for the United States on her first touch as 
an international player. Keller entered the match in the 68th 
minute and scored just seconds later when the Americans caught 
Finland off-guard with a quickly taken free kick. French hit Jen 
Streiffer with a short pass, and she fed Keller in the box for a 
goal from six yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans outshot Finland 13-5 and U.S. goalkeeper Tracy  
Ducar was forced to make just one save. But she could do nothing 
about Finland's goal, which came on a breakaway in the 83rd minute 
by Notre Dame star Anne Makinen, who rolled her shot into the right 
corner from 15 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great performance by our young personalities,'' said  
U.S. assistant coach Lauren Gregg, who also serves as the head 
coach of the U.S. under-21 team. ``They played with the poise and 
winning mentality that the U.S. women are known for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The teams meet again Saturday in Tampa, where the United States  
will use its veterans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
