<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Glitch Hits Schwab Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charles Schwab became the latest Internet  
brokerage to frustrate online investors as a computer crash just 
minutes after Wednesday's opening bell left the industry's dominant 
player offline for most of the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The online system went down at 9:37 a.m. EST due to software  
problems with a new mainframe computer that was added to help 
Schwab handle its booming Internet business, a spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem was fixed by 11:08 a.m., but some customers  
continued to experience delays as technicians gradually restored 
the system. By early afternoon, the company said, service was back 
to normal. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwab, the dominant player in the burgeoning online trading  
industry, asked customers who couldn't place trades through its Web 
site to phone in their trades or visit a broker at one of the 
company's 293 branch offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The company moved additional staffers to the phone lines and  
offered discounted trading fees to mollify angry investors. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, Schwab's stock fell $3.81 1/4 a share, or 5  
percent, to $$69 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Dan Hubbard said Schwab installed a third mainframe --  
a giant computer that runs smaller computer networks -- over the 
weekend as part of its plan to handle booming business. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Francisco-based brokerage now handles about 153,000  
online trades per day, a market-leading 28 percent of all online 
transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We needed to increase capacity to keep things running smoothly  
for our customers,'' Hubbard said. ``The technology apparently 
wasn't perfect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The system failure follows a series of similar embarrassments at  
Schwab's main online rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	In early February, software problems at ETrade Group Inc.  
derailed online trading three separate times, prompting two 
class-action lawsuits against that brokerage. Ameritrade and Datek 
have also experienced service interruptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Complaints about those problems have prompted increased  
attention from regulatory authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	New York state's attorney general recently launched an  
investigation into online brokerages, and the National Association 
of Securities Dealers has laid out guidelines for online brokerages 
to disclose the potential for service problems. 
</P>
<P>
	In terms of system capacity, Schwab already ranks at or near the  
top. Barring technical difficulties, the company's computers can 
handle 88,000 customers at a time. 
</P>
<P>
	But with no end in sight to the surging demand for online  
trading, Schwab and its rivals will be forced to continually 
upgrade their systems, opening the door to more glitches. 
</P>
<P>
	Julio Gomez, founder of Internet consulting firm Gomez Advisors,  
said online brokerages are experiencing severe growing pains as 
millions of investors discover the speed and relative ease of 
online trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a matter of 'if the system crashes,' it's a matter of  
'when it crashes,''' Gomez said. ``They are all still marketing 
aggressively, and they're not yet ready to handle all that 
volume.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 08:36:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors Call Rev. Lyons Greedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARGO, Fla. (AP) -- The Rev. Henry Lyons stole money intended to  
rebuild burned black churches and spent it on himself, returning it 
only when his ``world went into flames,'' a prosecutor told jurors 
in closing arguments today. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons, president of the National Baptist Convention USA, was  
given the money by the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guess which account he put it in? His secret Baptist  
builders-fund account. And then he went on to spend it not on the 
burned churches, but for his own personal purposes,'' Assistant 
State Attorney Jim Hellickson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hellickson began his closing arguments Tuesday in Lyons'  
racketeering and grand theft trial. The defense was expected to 
give its closing argument later today. 
</P>
<P>
	The proceedings resumed this morning shortly after Lyons learned  
that his grandmother, 81-year-old Minnie Lyons -- who helped raise 
him -- died Tuesday night in Gainesville. The judge asked Lyons if 
he was all right to go on with the trial, and he nodded. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons and co-defendant Bernice Edwards, a convicted embezzler  
and the convention's former public relations director, are charged 
with racketeering, accused of swindling more than $4 million from 
corporations seeking to market products to members of the powerful 
black church organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons alone is charged with grand theft, accused of stealing  
almost $250,000 from the ADL. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawyers have said he planned to distribute the money, and he  
repaid it when the ADL asked for its return. They maintain the 
other charges involve failed business deals that are not criminal 
matters. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hellickson said Lyons had to scramble, taking money from a  
variety of convention accounts and his own personal savings 
account, to repay the funds to the ADL. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything was fine. Nobody knew what happened to that money  
until July 6, 1997, when the defendant's world went into flames.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons' finances came under investigation after his wife set  
several small fires that day inside a waterfront home owned by 
Lyons and Ms. Edwards. She told deputies she found the deed to the 
home in her husband's briefcase and believed he and Ms. Edwards 
were having an affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lyons, later convicted of arson and sentenced to probation,  
has since said she does not believe Ms. Edwards was her husband's 
mistress and that she supports him. Ms. Edwards also denied on the 
stand that she had an affair with Lyons, but prosecutors described 
her as his mistress. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Hellickson described the pair as the ``Bonnie and  
Clyde'' of the denomination, stealing money and then spending it on 
fancy cars, vacations, jewelry and real estate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of using a gun to go and rob their victims, they used  
a pen and they used their word,'' he told jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	Hellickson said the two duped the companies by selling a  
membership mailing list that never existed and then used the money 
to buy the $700,000 waterfront home, a time share condominium, a 
huge diamond ring and luxury cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had to think of a name for this case ... I think I would  
call it, `Their creed was greed,'' he said. ``They had their fancy 
cars. They had their fancy vacations to Lake Tahoe, to Hawaii a 
couple times. They had their jewelry. They had the real estate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons did not testify on his own behalf, a decision his lawyers  
said was made because he still faces a federal trial in April on 54 
counts including tax evasion, extortion and money laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990224.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 05:22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC Retains Lead in Sweeps Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- George Clooney wasn't the only big draw on  
television last week, though he was enough to give NBC a big 
ratings boost during the key ``sweeps'' period. 
</P>
<P>
	Clooney's last regular appearance on ``ER'' as Dr. Doug Ross was  
only one example of the ``sweeps'' shows that profited from a 
ballooning number of viewers last week, Nielsen Media Research said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Viewership last Thursday jumped 30 percent, thanks to ``ER'' and  
other programs, including the final chapter of Stephen King's ABC 
miniseries ``Storm of the Century'' and the Fox reality special 
``World's Most Shocking Medical Videos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In a sea of network erosion, if you put the right programs on  
people will tune in to the networks. Thursday was a clear example 
of that,'' said industry analyst Mark Berman of New York-based 
Seltel. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's top-rated ``ER'' had the biggest audience for an episode  
of any regular entertainment series this season, with viewership 15 
percent higher than normal for the series. 
</P>
<P>
	The third and final part of the King miniseries ranked 11th for  
the week; the Fox special was 30th. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC won the week of Feb. 15-21 with a 9.9 rating and 16 share,  
keeping the network ahead during the February sweeps, when ratings 
are used to set local advertising rates. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS was second with a 9.5 rating and 15 share, followed by ABC  
with a 9.2 rating and 15 share. Fox earned a 6.8 rating and 11 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the emerging networks, WB had a 3.7 rating and 6 share,  
UPN had a 2.3 rating and 4 share and PAX TV had a 0.7 rating and 1 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. Share is the 
percentage of televisions in use that are tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	Other shows enjoying a sweeps dividend included a two-hour  
episode of ``Star Trek: Voyager,'' with its highest rating since 
October 1997. It was UPN's highest-rated program of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Homicide'' received its best rating since November 1997  
with the conclusion of a crossover episode with ``Law &AMP; Order'' 
that jabbed at a Kenneth Starr-like special prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	In the news competition, NBC's ``Nightly News'' posted an 8.3  
rating and 17 share to edge out ABC's ``World News Tonight,'' which 
had an 8.2 rating, 16 share. The ``CBS Evening News'' had a 7.9 
rating and 16 share. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of Feb. 15-21, the top 10 shows, their networks and  
ratings were ``ER,'' NBC, 23.8; ``Friends,'' NBC, 19.0; 
``Frasier,'' NBC, 18.8; ``Jesse,'' NBC, 15.9; ``Veronica's 
Closet,'' NBC, 15.6; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS, 14.9; ``CBS Sunday Movie, 
Too Rich: The Secret Life of Doris Duke,'' Part 1, CBS, 14.3; 
``Touched by an Angel,'' CBS, 14.0; ``ABC Monday Night Movie: Storm 
of the Century,'' Part 2, ABC, 12.2; ``Dateline NBC-Tuesday,'' NBC, 
12.2. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
